|2014\n|align=center|2018\n|Built in 1863 as an intermediate stop on the [[Ffestiniog Railway]] for the railway's Superintendent.  Later used as a holiday home by [[Granville Bantock|Sir Granville Bantock]]. Renovated following a joint appeal with the railway.<ref>{{Citation|last=Ffestiniog & Welsh Highland Railways|title=Coed y Bleiddiau appeal|date=27 June 2016|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=GNUhsSjaQ7k|accessdate=24 May 2018}}</ref>  Opened for lets April 2018.  Retains a private platform to the railway as its main access.\n|-\n|Dolbelydr\n|\n|Trefnant\n|Denbighshire\n|align=center|1999\n|align=center|2003\n|\n|-\n|[[Llwyn-celyn Farmhouse, Llanvihangel Crucorney|Llwyn Celyn]]\n|[[File:Llwyn-celyn Farmhouse, Llanvihangel Crucorney.jpg|120px]]\n|[[Llanvihangel Crucorney]]\n|Monmouthshire\n|align=center|2014\n|\n|align=center|Medieval Hall House, formerly part of the [[Llanthony Priory]] Estate in the [[Brecon Beacons]] Black Mountain area.  Under scaffolding from 2009, acquired 2011.  Opened for lets October 2018 after two years' on site restoration.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.landmarktrust.org.uk/news-and-events/upcoming-events/7---10-october-llwyn-celyn/|title=Llwyn Celyn Open Days {{!}} The Landmark Trust|website=www.landmarktrust.org.uk|language=en|access-date=2018-10-04}}</ref> \n|-\n|[[Maesyronnen Chapel]]\n|[[File:Capel Maesyronnen.jpg|120px]]\n|near Hay-on-Wye\n|Powys\n|align=center|1985\n|align=center|\n|\n|-\n|[[Monkton Old Hall]]\n|[[File:The Old Hall, Monkton - geograph.org.uk - 981245.jpg|120px]]\n|Monkton\n|Pembrokeshire\n|align=center|1979\n|align=center|1982\n|\n|-\n|Paxton's Tower Lodge\n|\n|Llanarthney\n|Carmarthenshire\n|align=center|1966\n|align=center|1967\n|\n|-\n|[[Plas Uchaf]]\n|[[File:Landmark Plas Uchaf south side.JPG|120px]]\n|near Corwen\n|Merionethshire\n|align=center|1971\n|align=center|1973\n|Leased from [[Merionethshire]] County Council, 1971.  Updated 2010 including underfloor heating, new kitchen and reconfigured bathroom.  \n|-\n|Poultry Cottage\n|\n|Leighton, Welshpool\n|Powys\n|align=center|1988\n|align=center|\n|\n|-\n|Stockwell Farm\n|\n|Old Radnor\n|Powys\n|align=center|\n|align=center|\n|\n|-\n|Tower Hill\n|\n|St David's \n|Pembrokeshire\n|align=center|1965\n|align=center|\n|Dilapidated cottages replaced by new building for first lets\n|-\n|Ty Capel, Rhiwddolion\n|\n|near Betws-y-Coed\n|Gwynedd\n|align=center|1967\n|align=center|\n|\n|-\n|Ty Coch, Rhiwddolion\n|[[File:Ty Coch - Rhiwddolion - geograph.org.uk - 1517369.jpg|120px]]\n|near Betws-y-Coed\n|Gwynedd\n|align=center|1968\n|align=center|\n|\n|-\n|Ty Uchaf, Rhiwddolion\n|[[File:Ty Uchaf, Rhiwddolion - geograph.org.uk - 400995.jpg|120px]]\n|near Betws-y-Coed\n|Gwynedd\n|align=center|1998\n|align=center|2001\n|\n|-\n|[[West Blockhouse Fort|West Blockhouse]]\n|[[File:Inspecting the West Blockhouse - geograph.org.uk - 1155054.jpg|120px]]\n|Dale\n|Pembrokeshire\n|align=center|1969\n|align=center|\n|[[Palmerston Forts, Milford Haven|Palmerston Fort]], protecting [[Milford Haven]]\n|}\n\n===Belgium===\n*[[Hougoumont]], close to the site of the [[Battle of Waterloo]]. The Trust contributed to the Chateau Hougoumont farm's \u00a33M restoration, from 2013.  An apartment in the former gardener's cottage over the south gates has been let since 2015.\n\n===France===\n* [[La C\u00e9libataire]], Le Maison des Amis and Le Moulin de la Tuilerie, Gif-sur-Yvette, Essonne.  Let since 2010.\n\n===Italy===\n[[File:Rome-PlaceEspagne.jpg|thumb|right|The Spanish Steps, seen from Piazza di Spagna, Italy. [[John Keats]] lived in the house in the right foreground.]]\n* Casa de Mar, San Fruttuoso \u2013 from summer 2016\n* [[Casa Guidi]], Florence \u2013 from 1995\n* [[Piazza di Spagna (apartment)|Piazza di Spagna]], Rome \u2013 from 1982\n* [[Sant'Antonio (monastery)|Sant'Antonio]], Tivoli \u2013 from 1995\n* [[Villa Saraceno]], Agugliaro \u2013 restored 1984\u20131995\n* Villa dei Vescovi, Padua (two apartments) \u2013 from 2006\n\n===United States===\n* [[Amos Brown House]]\n* [[The Dutton Farmhouse]]\n* [[Naulakha (Rudyard Kipling House)]]\n* Kipling's Carriage House, Naulakha\n* [[The Sugarhouse, Vermont|The Sugarhouse]]\n\n== Properties under restoration ==\nAs at March 2020, the following properties were being restored by the Trust for future lettings:\n\n*[[File:Chatley Heath Semaphore Tower - geograph.org.uk - 18673.jpg|right|thumb|Chatley Heath Semaphore Tower]]Semaphore Tower, [[Chatley Heath]], Cobham, Surrey.  Only remaining semaphore tower from the Napoleonic era, listed Grade II*.  An appeal for \u00a3160,000 representing the remaining 25% of its restoration cost was launched on 19 March 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.landmarktrust.org.uk/support-us/projects-and-appeals/semaphore-tower-appeal/|title=Semaphore Tower {{!}} The Landmark Trust|website=www.landmarktrust.org.uk|access-date=2019-03-19}}</ref>  The appeal has reached its target, and restoration work is now underway.<ref>{{cite web |title=Our plans for Semaphore Tower |url=https://www.landmarktrust.org.uk/news-and-events/Current-Restoration-Projects/semaphore-tower-appeal/our-plans/ |website=Landmark Trust |accessdate=21 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Projects in development ==\nAs at March 2019, plans for restoring and renovating the following properties were under active development:\n* Calverley Old Hall, Main Wing \u2013 adjacent to existing property let.  The pre-qualification stage of an architectural competition for the Hall's restoration closed on 1 August 2017, when likely construction costs were estimated at \u00a32.3m.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.landmarktrust.org.uk/get-involved/calverley-old-hall-competition/sections/competition-brief2/|title=The Landmark Trust|website=www.landmarktrust.org.uk|accessdate=5 August 2017}}</ref>  On 13 February 2018 the Trust announced the competition had been won by [http://www.cowpergriffith.co.uk Cowper Griffith].  Consultation with local residents on the proposed designs took place in March 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.landmarktrust.org.uk/news-and-events/latest-news/calverley-old-hall-design-competition-winners-announced/|title=Calverley Design Competition winners {{!}} The Landmark Trust|website=www.landmarktrust.org.uk|accessdate=24 May 2018}}</ref>  Awaiting appeal launch, previously planned for 2019.\n* Fairburn Tower, Inverness.  Category A listed Tower House, built in 1545 for Murdo Mackenzie, Gentleman of the Bedchamber for [[James V of Scotland|King James V.]]  Restoration proposals developed by [http://simpsonandbrown.co.uk Simpson and Brown] as Project Architects.  \u00a3500,000 grant pledged by [[Historic Environment Scotland]].  Appeal for \u00a3800,000 launched May 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.landmarktrust.org.uk/support-us/projects-and-appeals/fairburn-tower-appeal/|title=Fairburn Tower {{!}} The Landmark Trust|website=www.landmarktrust.org.uk|accessdate=24 May 2018}}</ref>  By autumn/winter 2019 all but \u00a389,000 had been raised.  Restoration work was expected to start soon thereafter for a planned completion in late summer 2021.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://issuu.com/landmark_trust/docs/landmark_trust_winter_newsletter_2019/8|title=Landmark Trust Winter Newsletter 2019|website=issuu|access-date=2020-02-06}}</ref>\n\nNew potential projects announced by February 2020 for development were<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.landmarktrust.org.uk/support-us/projects-and-appeals/future-projects/|title=Future projects|website=www.landmarktrust.org.uk|access-date=2020-02-06}}</ref>:\n\n*[https://nfknowledge.org/contributions/still-watching-over-ibsley/#map=10/-1.78/50.88/0/24:0:0.6|39:1:1|40:1:1 Ibsley Watch Tower], Ibsley, Hampshire - Derelict watch tower at one of the twelve RAF airfields in the New Forest.  Held on 99-year lease by RAF Ibsley Heritage Trust.\n*Mayor's Parlour Block, [https://www.dover.gov.uk/Leisure-Culture-Tourism/Heritage--Museums/Town-Hall/Maison-Dieu-Restoration-Project.aspx Maison Dieu], Dover, Kent - Part of 1835 transformation of Grade I complex of civic buildings dating back to 1204.\n*[http://www.mavisbank.org.uk Mavisbank], nr Edinburgh, Midlothian - Joint project with Historic Environment Scotland for Scotland's first Palladian villa.\n\n== Other projects previously considered for restoration ==\nOther properties previously considered by the Trust, but not progressed to completion, include:\n\n* Almshouses, [[Denton, Lincolnshire|Denton]], Lincolnshire<ref name=\":2\" /> \u2013 demolished by then owner Sir Bruno Welby, subsequently convicted in 1980 of unauthorised demolition of historic buildings and fined \u00a31,000 plus costs<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.lincstothepast.com/Almshouses--Denton/1403274.record?pt=S|title=Welby Almshouses, Denton|website=Lincs to the Past|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130503101526/http://www.lincstothepast.com/Almshouses--Denton/1403274.record?pt=S|archivedate=3 May 2013|url-status=dead|accessdate=30 March 2017}}</ref>\n*Falsgrave Signal Box, Scarborough, North Yorkshire - under consideration from 2016 to March 2019<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.landmarktrust.org.uk/support-us/projects-and-appeals/future-projects/|title=Future projects|website=www.landmarktrust.org.uk|accessdate=24 May 2018}}</ref>\n*The Master's House, Maidstone, Kent \u2013 rejected 2002 on grounds of size\n* Mausoleum, [[Seaton Delaval Hall|Seaton Delavel]] \u2013 rejected for risk of repayment of Department of the Environment grant<ref name=\":2\" />\n* Warder's Tower, Biddulph, Staffordshire \u2013 leased from Staffordshire County Council 2008\u20132010, returned when no acceptable solution could be found for dealing with four colonies of bats\n\n== Former properties ==\nProperties formerly run as holiday lets and owned, leased or run by the Landmark Trust on a management arrangement basis include:\n* All Saint's Vicarage, Maidenhead \u2013 First floor flat in Vicarage complex designed by [[George Edmund Street|G.E. Street]].  Advertised as being prepared for opening for lets in 1990<ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|year=1989|title=New properties open in 1990|url=|journal=Landmark Trust Newsletter|volume=|pages=|via=}}</ref> and in 1991 but not listed in 1992.\n* Edale Mill, [[Edale]], Derbyshire \u2013 The Trust bought the mill in 1969 and converted it into seven flats.  Six were sold after conversion with one being retained for holiday lets until c2012.\n* Fish Court, [[Hampton Court Palace]] \u2013 owned by [[Historic Royal Palaces]].  Withdrawn from property portfolio in 2014.\n* The Harp Inn, [[Old Radnor]], Powys \n* Higher Lettaford, North Bovey, Devon \u2013 sold in 2013 as no longer appropriate to the Trust's property portfolio\n* [[Hill House, Helensburgh]] \u2013 top floor flat returned to National Trust for Scotland in 2011.\n* The Master's House, [[Gladstone Pottery Museum|Gladstone Pottery]] \u2013 The Gladstone Pottery Museum was transferred to Stoke-on-Trent Museums in 1994.\n* Meikle Ascog, Ascog, Argyll & Bute \u2013 sold in 2013 as no longer appropriate to the Trust's property portfolio\n* Sandford House, 7 Lower High St, Stourbridge, West Midlands<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite book|title=Landmark Handbook 1988|last=Smith|first=Sir John|publisher=Landmark Trust|year=1988|isbn=0 9512953 0 6|location=|pages=6, 9}}</ref>\n* 30, St Mary's Lane, Tewkesbury \u2013 bought in 1969 and let to local tenants from 2006.\n* Wellbrook Beetling Mill, Cookstown, Co Tyrone \u2013 returned to National Trust\n\n== Legacy Estate \u2013 other properties owned by the Trust ==\nIn addition to properties let for Holiday rentals, the Trust has been bequeathed other properties which it has refurbished and managed in other ways, through its Legacy Estate.  These include:\n\n* Fountain Hotel, 92 High Street, Cowes, Isle of White \u2013 acquired 2010\n* The Tower, [[Netherne Hospital]], Netherne-on-the-Hill, Coulsdon, Surrey \u2013 bequeathed 2015<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.landmarktrust.org.uk/news-and-events/latest-news/legacy-case-study/|title=Legacy Case Study \u2013 Netherne-on-the-Hill|website=www.landmarktrust.org.uk|accessdate=5 August 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Handbooks ==\nDetails of each property available to rent are available online, on the Trust's website, and in a Handbook.  Twenty-five editions of the Handbook have been published to December 2016:\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Edition number\n!Year\n!Editor\n!Cover \n|-\n|1\n|1966\n|\n|\n|-\n|2\n|1968\n|\n|Green\n|-\n|3\n|1970\n|\n|Moss/Lime Green\n|-\n|4\n|1971\n|\n|Red\n|-\n|5\n|1972\n|\n|Blue\n|-\n|6\n|1973\n|\n|Moss Green\n|-\n|7\n|1977\n|John Smith\n|New Inn, Peasenhall\n|-\n|8\n|1988\n|Charlotte Haslam\n|Laughton Place\n|-\n|9\n|1989\n|Charlotte Haslam\n|Cawood Castle\n|-\n|10 (25 years anniversary edition)\n|1990\n|Charlotte Haslam\n|Swarkestone Pavilion\n|-\n|11\n|1991\n|Charlotte Haslam\n|Kingswear Castle\n|-\n|12\n|1992\n|John Smith and Charlotte Haslam\n|The Bath House\n|-\n|13\n|1993\n|John Smith and Charlotte Haslam\n|Prospect Tower\n|-\n|14\n|1994\n|Charlotte Haslam\n|Woodspring Priory\n|-\n|15\n|1995\n|Charlotte Haslam\n|Beamsley Hospital\n|-\n|16\n|1996\n|Constance Barrett\n|Tixall Gatehouse\n|-\n|17\n|1998\n|\n|Old Light, Lundy\n|-\n|18\n|1999\n|Constance Barrett\n|Banqueting House\n|-\n|19\n|2001\n|Constance Barrett\n|Swarkestone Pavilion\n|-\n|20\n|2003\n|Sophie Horton and Katherine Oates\n|Prospect Tower\n|-\n|21 (40 years anniversary edition)\n|2005\n|not credited\n|Freston Tower\n|-\n|22\n|2006\n|\n|Gothic Temple\n|-\n|23\n|2008\n|\n|The Pineapple\n|-\n|24\n|2011\n|\n|Culloden Tower\n|-\n|25 (50 years anniversary edition)\n|2014\n|Helen Hartstein\n|The Library\n|-\n|26 (published November 2018)\n|2018\n|\n|St Winifred's Well\n|}\n\n==Archives==\nThe Landmark Trust Lundy Island Philatelic Archive was donated to the [[British Library Philatelic Collections]] in 1991 and is located at the [[British Library]].<ref>[http://sherpa.bl.uk/42/01/philatelicresearchbl.pdf Philatelic Research at the British Library] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110722070224/http://sherpa.bl.uk/42/01/philatelicresearchbl.pdf |date=22 July 2011 }} by [[David Beech]]</ref>\n\n== Further reading ==\n* ''Landmark, A History of Britain in 50 Buildings''. 2015. Keay, Anna and Stanford, Caroline.  Francis Lincoln Ltd.  {{ISBN|978-0-7112-3645-5}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Landmark Trust}}\n*{{Official website|http://www.landmarktrust.org.uk|Landmark Trust}} \u2013 official site\n*[https://www.flickr.com/groups/landmarktrust/pool Landmark Trust] properties' photos on [[Flickr]]\n\n[[Category:Architecture of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Conservation organisations based in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Environmental charities based in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Landmark Trust| ]]\n[[Category:Lundy]]\n[[Category:Organisations based in Berkshire]]\n[[Category:Royal Borough of Windsor and Maidenhead]]\n[[Category:Organizations established in 1965]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2018}}\n{{Use British English|date=July 2018}}\n\n{{Infobox organization\n| name          = The Landmark Trust\n| logo          = LandmarkLogo.png\n| logo_size     = 299px\n| logo_alt      = Landmark Trust logo\n| formation     = 1965\n| status        = Building conservation and preservation charity\n| headquarters  = [[Shottesbrooke]], Berkshire, United Kingdom\n| region_served = Predominantly UK \n| leader_title  = Director\n| leader_name   = Dr [[Anna Keay]]\n| website       = [http://www.landmarktrust.org.uk/ www.landmarktrust.org.uk]\n}}\nThe '''Landmark Trust''' is a British [[architectural conservation|building conservation]] [[charitable organization|charity]], founded in 1965 by [[John Smith (Conservative politician)|Sir John and Lady Smith]], that rescues buildings of historic interest or architectural merit and then makes them available for holiday rental. The Trust's headquarters is at [[Shottesbrooke]] in Berkshire.\n\nMost Trust properties are in England, Scotland and Wales. Several are on [[Lundy Island]] off the coast of north Devon, operated under lease from the [[National Trust for Places of Historic Interest or Natural Beauty|National Trust]]. In continental Europe there are Landmark sites in Belgium, France and Italy. Five properties are in the United States \u2014 all in [[Vermont]] \u2014 one of which, [[Naulakha (Rudyard Kipling House)|Naulakha]], was the home of [[Rudyard Kipling]] in the 1890s.\n\nThe Trust is a charity registered in England & Wales<ref>{{EW charity|243312}}</ref> and in Scotland.<ref>{{Scottish charity|SC039205}}</ref> The American sites are owned by an independent sister charity, Landmark Trust USA. There is also an [[Irish Landmark Trust]].<ref name=\"Irish site\">{{cite web | url=http://www.irishlandmark.com/ | title=Irish Landmark | accessdate=1 July 2012}}</ref>\n\nThose who rent Landmarks provide a source of funds to support restoration costs and building maintenance. The first rentals were in 1967 when six properties were available.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Landmark Trust Handbook 2014|last=|first=|publisher=Landmark Trust|year=2014|isbn=978-0-9533124-8-1|location=|pages=10|quote=|via=}}</ref> The Trust's 200th property, Llwyn Celyn, opened for rental in October 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.landmarktrust.org.uk/search-and-book/properties/llwyn-celyn-property-51563/?ZJjYEWg8T5Uilneb2kJmmXCLhs1A/lUcavLTH7npv6EIhfGEa0L0BGPuAa1pOr9Y52FQu5RoLiEcJ32yYCOHXT3Kj5qnm8CFdKLLu7UEBt+M0w/Ic1c6qoBrlPtTfgvxtHltvi2XfDoSmc5q/ZKGHwX5fu9v7KzZCvEUD9hUslw=|title=Holiday at Llwyn Celyn in Cwmyoy, Monmouthshire {{!}} The Landmark Trust|website=www.landmarktrust.org.uk|language=en|access-date=2018-10-08}}</ref> Landmark sites include forts, farmhouses, manor houses, mills, cottages, castles, gatehouses, follies and towers and represent historic periods from medieval to the 20th century.\n{{TOC limit|3}}\n\n== Governance and administration ==\nThe Trust employs a 400-strong workforce headed by a Director.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.landmarktrust.org.uk/about-us/about-us/landmark-staff/|title=Staff|last=|first=|date=|website=Landmark Trust|accessdate=30 March 2017}}</ref> [[Anna Keay]] was appointed Director in 2012,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.landmarktrust.org.uk/about-us/about-us/landmark-staff/Dr-Anna-Keay-Director/biography/|title=Biography \u2013 Dr Anna Keay|last=|first=|date=|website=Landmark Trust|accessdate=30 March 2017}}</ref> succeeding Peter Pearce (1995\u20132012) and Robin Evans FRICS (1986\u20131995).\n\nThe work of the Trust is overseen by a Board of Trustees chaired by [[Neil Mendoza]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.landmarktrust.org.uk/about-us/about-us/landmark-trustees/|title=Trustees|last=|first=|date=|website=Landmark Trust|accessdate=30 March 2017}}</ref>\n\n[[Charles, Prince of Wales|Prince Charles]] became Patron of the Landmark Trust in 1995.\n\nA group of high-profile supporters act as Ambassadors for the Trust, helping to raise awareness of the Trust's role in rescuing and preserving remarkable buildings.  As at March 2017<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.landmarktrust.org.uk/about-us/about-us/landmark-ambassadors/|title=Ambassadors|last=|first=|date=|website=Landmark Trust|accessdate=30 March 2017}}</ref> these were: [[David Armstrong-Jones, 2nd Earl of Snowdon|David Armstrong-Jones]]; [[George Clarke (architect)|George Clarke]]; [[Nicholas Coleridge]]; [[Simon Jenkins]]; [[Griff Rhys Jones]]; and [[Natascha McElhone]].\n\n==In media==\nThe Gothic Temple at Stowe was filmed in March 1999 as the Scottish Chapel in the Bond movie ''[[The World Is Not Enough|The World is Not Enough]]''.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|year=1999|title=Gothic Mystery|url=|journal=Landmark Trust Newsletter \u2013 Autumn 1999|volume=|pages=|via=}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2015 five life-sized sculptures by [[Antony Gormley]], titled ''Land'', were placed near the centre of the UK and at four compass points, in a commission by the Landmark Trust to celebrate its 50th anniversary. They were at [[Lowsonford]] (Warwickshire), [[Lundy]] (Bristol Channel), [[Clavell Tower]] (Dorset), [[Saddell Bay]] (Mull of Kintyre), and the [[Aldeburgh#Martello Tower|Martello Tower]] ([[Aldeburgh]], Suffolk).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-32702277|title=Sir Antony Gormley sculptures placed at five UK beauty spots|website=BBC News|date=12 May 2015|accessdate=8 July 2015}}</ref> The sculpture at Saddell Bay is to remain in place permanently following an anonymous donation and the granting of planning permission.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-39127010 | title = Antony Gormley sculpture gets permanent home | website = BBC News | date = 4 March 2017 | access-date = 24 July 2018}}</ref> The sculpture on Lundy was relocated to [[Cambridge]].<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.cam.ac.uk/news/celebrated-sculptor-sir-antony-gormley-unveils-sculpture-at-university-of-cambridge | title = Celebrated sculptor Sir Antony Gormley unveils sculpture at University of Cambridge | date = 2 December 2016 | access-date = 28 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe work of the Trust was the subject of a six-part [[Channel 4]] television documentary, ''Restoring Britain's Landmarks'', first broadcast in October 2015.<ref>{{cite web|title=Restoring Britain's Landmarks|url=http://www.channel4.com/programmes/restoring-britains-landmarks|publisher=Channel Four Television|accessdate=19 July 2016}}</ref>\n\nFour Channel 4 programmes, ''Great British Buildings: Restoration of the Year,'' transmitted from 23 March 2017, were co-hosted by Landmark Trust Director [[Anna Keay]] and [[Kevin McCloud]]. Buildings featured included [[Belmont, Lyme Regis|Belmont]].\n\n==Properties available for holiday lets==\nThe following lists aim to be complete and illustrate both the variety of structures and geographical spread of the trust.  In the Trust's early years, prior to the incorporation of the charity, properties were often bought with the support of the Manifold Trust.  The Trust's current portfolio also includes properties bequeathed to the Trust, leased, or operated through a management agreement on behalf of other owners.  Dates of acquisition and first lettings are shown where available from Landmark Trust or other published sources; time differences between dates often reflect previous/current ownership and the extent of restoration required.\n\nDetailed histories of each building are prepared by the Trust's Historian during its renovation.  These include summaries plus before and after photographs of restoration works as carried out.  Each building history is then left as an album in the property for visitors to peruse.  All Trust [https://www.landmarktrust.org.uk/about-us/history-albums/ property history albums] were made available online for the first time in October 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.landmarktrust.org.uk/news-and-events/latest-news/history-albums-online-for-the-first-time/|title=The history of Landmark Trust buildings {{!}} The Landmark Trust|website=www.landmarktrust.org.uk|language=en|access-date=2018-10-16}}</ref>\n\n===Channel Islands===\n[[File:Alderney - Fort Clonque 02.jpg|thumb|right|Fort Clonque, Alderney]]\n*[[Fort Clonque]], Alderney\n*[[Nicolle Tower]], [[Saint Clement, Jersey|St Clement]], Jersey\n\n===England===\n====Lundy====\n\nThe Landmark Trust manages the Island of [[Lundy]] in the [[Bristol Channel]] on behalf of the [[National Trust for Places of Historic Interest or Natural Beauty|National Trust]], and operates a number of holiday cottages there. The properties managed by the Trust include:\n* The Barn\n* Bramble Villa East\n* Bramble Villa West\n* Castle and Keep Cottages\n* Government House\n* Hanmers\n* Millcombe House\n* The Old House\n* The Old Light\n* The Old School\n* The Quarters\n* Radio Room\n* St John's\n* Square Cottage\n* Stoneycroft\n* Tibbets\n<gallery>\nFile:The Jetty, Lundy.jpg|Jetty and harbour, Lundy\nFile:Lundy Old Lighthouse - geograph.org.uk - 15437.jpg|The Old Light, Lundy\nFile:St Helena's church, Lundy.jpg|[[St Helen's Church, Lundy]]\n</gallery>\n\n====London and South East England====\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!Name\n!Image\n!Town\n!County\n!Acquired\n!Opened for lets\n!Notes\n|-\n|43 and 45a [[Cloth Fair]]\n|[[File:Betjeman's, Cloth Fair, London EC1 - geograph.org.uk - 1140972.jpg|120x120px]]\n|[[Smithfield, London|Smithfield]]\n|London EC1\n|1981\n|\n|Two properties.  43 is the former home of the late Poet Laureate Sir [[John Betjeman]].\n|-\n|Cobham Dairy\n|\n|Cobham\n|Kent\n|2016/17\n|2019\n|Grade II* ornamental dairy designed by [[James Wyatt]] in the 1790s in the style of an Italianate chapel, on the Buildings at Risk register.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.landmarktrust.org.uk/Properties-list/Cobham-Dairy/History/#tabs=History|title=Rescuing Cobham Dairy|website=Landmark Trust|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161007173626/http://www.landmarktrust.org.uk/Properties-list/Cobham-Dairy/History/#tabs%3DHistory|archivedate=7 October 2016|accessdate=29 March 2017}}</ref>  The Trust launched an appeal in late September 2016 to rescue the building and had raised \u00a3200,000 by 31 March 2017, thereby securing a further \u00a3200,000 match funding from [[Ecclesiastical Insurance]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.landmarktrust.org.uk/news-and-events/latest-news/cobham-dairy-update/|title=Rescuing Cobham Dairy|last=|first=|date=|website=Landmark Trust|accessdate=29 March 2017}}</ref>  The full target of \u00a3954,000 was achieved by late 2017.  Renovation started during 2018 and was completed in Autumn 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.landmarktrust.org.uk/Properties-list/Cobham-Dairy/Appeal/|title=Historic Cobham Dairy|website=www.landmarktrust.org.uk|accessdate=24 May 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n|Fox Hall\n|[[File:Fox Hall, Charlton - geograph.org.uk - 1010189.jpg|120x120px]]\n|Charlton\n|West Sussex\n|1983\n|\n|\n|-\n|