Charles Voysey (architect)|CFA Voysey]] in 1900, also on the Buildings at Risk register.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.halwill.org.uk/index.aspx?articleid=7418|title=CFA Voysey's Winsford Cottage Hospital|last=|first=|date=|website=Halwill.org.uk|accessdate=29 March 2017}}</ref>  After being declared surplus to needs by the NHS in 1999, the hospital was acquired by the Winsford Trust who gained some support for renovation from English Heritage and the [[Pilgrim Trust]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.winsfordtrust.com/winsford-cottage-hospital|title=About \u2013 The Winsford Trust|last=|first=|date=|website=winsfordtrust.com|accessdate=29 March 2017}}</ref>  Proposals for joint community use and a Landmark Trust holiday let were presented to the local community in November 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/events/1840767046153232/|title=The Future of Winsford Hospital; Event \u2013 9 November 2016|last=|first=|date=|website=Facebook \u2013 The Winsford Trust, Halwill Junction|accessdate=29 March 2017}}</ref> On 8 June 2017 an appeal was launched to save the hospital by raising \u00a3355,000 within twelve months, adding to an initial \u00a396,000 grant from the [[Heritage Lottery Fund]] and money raised through other groups and supporters.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.landmarktrust.org.uk/Properties-list/winsford-cottage-hospital/Appeal/|title=Winsford Cottage Hospital|website=www.landmarktrust.org.uk|accessdate=5 August 2017}}</ref>  By April 2018, the appeal was within sight of its target, needing a final \u00a340,000 to unlock a total Heritage Lottery Fund grant of \u00a3486,000.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.landmarktrust.org.uk/Properties-list/winsford-cottage-hospital/Appeal/|title=Winsford Cottage Hospital|website=www.landmarktrust.org.uk|accessdate=24 May 2018}}</ref>  The Trust announced on 19 July 2018 the full required sum of \u00a31.5m had been raised, with restoration work scheduled to start during the summer.\n|-\n| align=\"left\" |Wolveton Gatehouse\n| align=\"left\" |\n| align=\"left\" |Near [[Dorchester, Dorset|Dorchester]]\n| align=\"left\" |Dorset\n| align=\"center\" |\n| align=\"center\" |\n| align=\"left\" |\n|-\n| align=\"left\" |[[Woodsford|Woodsford Castle]]\n| align=\"left\" |[[File:Woodsford Castle - geograph.org.uk - 1288442.jpg|120px]]\n| align=\"left\" |Near [[Dorchester, Dorset|Dorchester]]\n| align=\"left\" |Dorset\n| align=\"center\" |1977\n| align=\"center\" |1992\n| align=\"left\" |\n|-\n| align=\"left\" |[[Woodspring Priory]]\n| align=\"left\" |[[File:WoodspringPrioryFront081006.jpg|120px]]\n| align=\"left\" |Near [[Weston-super-Mare]]\n| align=\"left\" |Somerset\n| align=\"center\" |1969\n| align=\"center\" |1992\n| align=\"left\" |Priory Church, Infirmary and Farmhouse acquired from National Trust, 1969.  Restoration completed in phases:<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Crook|first=C D|year=1991|title=The Repair and Restoration of Woodspring Priory|url=|journal=Landmark Trust Newsletter \u2013 Autumn 1991|volume=|pages=|via=}}</ref>\na) Priory Tower: 1969\u20131971\n\nb) Priory exterior; removal of Priory interior additions; Infirmary: 1971\u20131976\n\nc) Farmhouse roof: 1980\u20131983\n\nd) Farmhouse window plan; South front; Interior: 1983\u20131992\n|-\n| align=\"left\" |[[Wortham Manor]]\n| align=\"left\" |[[File:Wortham Manor Near Lifton - geograph.org.uk - 105330.jpg|120px]]\n| align=\"left\" |[[Lifton, Devon|Lifton]]\n| align=\"left\" |Devon\n|align=center|1969\n|align=center|1974\n| align=\"left\" |2 flats let until 1990\n|-\n|}\n\n=== Scotland ===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"margin:0.5em auto;\"\n|+\n|-\n!|Name\n!class=\"unsortable\"|Image\n!|Town\n!|County\n!|Acquired\n!|Opened for lets\n!class=\"unsortable\"|Notes\n|-\n|align=left|[[Ascog House]]\n|align=left|[[File:Ascog_House,_Isle_of_Bute.jpg|120px]]\n|align=left|[[Ascog]]\n|align=left|Isle of Bute\n|align=center|1989\n|align=center|1993\n|align=left|\n|-\n|align=left|[[Auchinleck House]]\n|align=left|[[File:Auchinleck_House.jpg|120px]]\n|align=left|[[Auchinleck]]\n|align=left|East Ayrshire\n|align=center|1999\n|align=center|2001\n|align=left|Acquired from Scottish Historic Buildings Trust with support from the [[Heritage Lottery Fund]], [[Historic Scotland]] and an anonymous benefactor.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|year=1998|title=Introduction|url=|journal=Landmark Trust Newsletter \u2013 Autumn 1998|volume=|pages=|via=}}</ref>  Built by [[Alexander Boswell, Lord Auchinleck|Lord Auchinleck]], father of [[James Boswell]].\n|-\n|align=left|[[Berriedale, Highland|Berriedale]], Shore Cottages\n|align=left|[[File:Shore Cottages Berriedale.jpg|120px]]\n|align=left|near [[Wick, Caithness|Wick]]\n|align=left|Caithness\n| align=\"center\" |2010\n| align=\"center\" |\n| align=\"left\" |\n|-\n|align=left|[[Castle of Park]]\n|align=left|[[File:Castle of Park Glenluce exterior.JPG|120px]]\n|align=left|[[Glenluce]]\n|align=left|Dumfries and Galloway\n| align=\"center\" |1990\n| align=\"center\" |1993\n| align=\"left\" |\n|-\n|align=left|[[Collegehill House]]\n|align=left|[[File:Collegehill House Roslin 05.jpg|120px]]\n|align=left|[[Roslin, Scotland|Roslin]]\n|align=left|Lothian\n| align=\"center\" |2002\n| align=\"center\" |2002\n| align=\"left\" |\n|-\n|align=left|[[Gargunnock House]]\n|align=left|[[File:Gargunnock House - geograph.org.uk - 81483.jpg|120px]]\n|align=left|\n|align=left|Stirling\n| align=\"center\" |\n| align=\"center\" |\n| align=\"left\" |\n|-\n|align=left|Glenmalloch Lodge\n|align=left|[[File:Glenmalloch Lodge - geograph.org.uk - 1516039.jpg|120x120px]]\n|align=left|Newton Stewart\n|align=left|Dumfries and Galloway\n| align=\"center\" |2004\n| align=\"center\" |\n| align=\"left\" |\n|-\n|align=left|[[The Mackintosh Building|Mackintosh Building]]\n|align=left|[[File:A shop in the main street with an interesting design. - geograph.org.uk - 745712.jpg|120px]]\n|align=left|Comrie\n|align=left|Perthshire\n| align=\"center\" |1985\n| align=\"center\" |1985\n| ali