ber 2018 after two years' on site restoration.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.landmarktrust.org.uk/news-and-events/upcoming-events/7---10-october-llwyn-celyn/|title=Llwyn Celyn Open Days {{!}} The Landmark Trust|website=www.landmarktrust.org.uk|language=en|access-date=2018-10-04}}</ref> \n|-\n|[[Maesyronnen Chapel]]\n|[[File:Capel Maesyronnen.jpg|120px]]\n|near Hay-on-Wye\n|Powys\n|align=center|1985\n|align=center|\n|\n|-\n|[[Monkton Old Hall]]\n|[[File:The Old Hall, Monkton - geograph.org.uk - 981245.jpg|120px]]\n|Monkton\n|Pembrokeshire\n|align=center|1979\n|align=center|1982\n|\n|-\n|Paxton's Tower Lodge\n|\n|Llanarthney\n|Carmarthenshire\n|align=center|1966\n|align=center|1967\n|\n|-\n|[[Plas Uchaf]]\n|[[File:Landmark Plas Uchaf south side.JPG|120px]]\n|near Corwen\n|Merionethshire\n|align=center|1971\n|align=center|1973\n|Leased from [[Merionethshire]] County Council, 1971.  Updated 2010 including underfloor heating, new kitchen and reconfigured bathroom.  \n|-\n|Poultry Cottage\n|\n|Leighton, Welshpool\n|Powys\n|align=center|1988\n|align=center|\n|\n|-\n|Stockwell Farm\n|\n|Old Radnor\n|Powys\n|align=center|\n|align=center|\n|\n|-\n|Tower Hill\n|\n|St David's \n|Pembrokeshire\n|align=center|1965\n|align=center|\n|Dilapidated cottages replaced by new building for first lets\n|-\n|Ty Capel, Rhiwddolion\n|\n|near Betws-y-Coed\n|Gwynedd\n|align=center|1967\n|align=center|\n|\n|-\n|Ty Coch, Rhiwddolion\n|[[File:Ty Coch - Rhiwddolion - geograph.org.uk - 1517369.jpg|120px]]\n|near Betws-y-Coed\n|Gwynedd\n|align=center|1968\n|align=center|\n|\n|-\n|Ty Uchaf, Rhiwddolion\n|[[File:Ty Uchaf, Rhiwddolion - geograph.org.uk - 400995.jpg|120px]]\n|near Betws-y-Coed\n|Gwynedd\n|align=center|1998\n|align=center|2001\n|\n|-\n|[[West Blockhouse Fort|West Blockhouse]]\n|[[File:Inspecting the West Blockhouse - geograph.org.uk - 1155054.jpg|120px]]\n|Dale\n|Pembrokeshire\n|align=center|1969\n|align=center|\n|[[Palmerston Forts, Milford Haven|Palmerston Fort]], protecting [[Milford Haven]]\n|}\n\n===Belgium===\n*[[Hougoumont]], close to the site of the [[Battle of Waterloo]]. The Trust contributed to the Chateau Hougoumont farm's \u00a33M restoration, from 2013.  An apartment in the former gardener's cottage over the south gates has been let since 2015.\n\n===France===\n* [[La C\u00e9libataire]], Le Maison des Amis and Le Moulin de la Tuilerie, Gif-sur-Yvette, Essonne.  Let since 2010.\n\n===Italy===\n[[File:Rome-PlaceEspagne.jpg|thumb|right|The Spanish Steps, seen from Piazza di Spagna, Italy. [[John Keats]] lived in the house in the right foreground.]]\n* Casa de Mar, San Fruttuoso \u2013 from summer 2016\n* [[Casa Guidi]], Florence \u2013 from 1995\n* [[Piazza di Spagna (apartment)|Piazza di Spagna]], Rome \u2013 from 1982\n* [[Sant'Antonio (monastery)|Sant'Antonio]], Tivoli \u2013 from 1995\n* [[Villa Saraceno]], Agugliaro \u2013 restored 1984\u20131995\n* Villa dei Vescovi, Padua (two apartments) \u2013 from 2006\n\n===United States===\n* [[Amos Brown House]]\n* [[The Dutton Farmhouse]]\n* [[Naulakha (Rudyard Kipling House)]]\n* Kipling's Carriage House, Naulakha\n* [[The Sugarhouse, Vermont|The Sugarhouse]]\n\n== Properties under restoration ==\nAs at March 2020, the following properties were being restored by the Trust for future lettings:\n\n*[[File:Chatley Heath Semaphore Tower - geograph.org.uk - 18673.jpg|right|thumb|Chatley Heath Semaphore Tower]]Semaphore Tower, [[Chatley Heath]], Cobham, Surrey.  Only remaining semaphore tower from the Napoleonic era, listed Grade II*.  An appeal for \u00a3160,000 representing the remaining 25% of its restoration cost was launched on 19 March 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.landmarktrust.org.uk/support-us/projects-and-appeals/semaphore-tower-appeal/|title=Semaphore Tower {{!}} The Landmark Trust|website=www.landmarktrust.org.uk|access-date=2019-03-19}}</ref>  The appeal has reached its target, and restoration work is now underway<ref>{{cite web |title=Our plans for Semaphore Tower |url=https://www.landmarktrust.org.uk/news-and-events/Current-Restoration-Projects/semaphore-tower-appeal/our-plans/ |website=Landmark Trust |accessdate=21 March 2020}}</ref>.\n\n== Projects in development ==\nAs at March 2019, plans for restoring and renovating the following properties were under active development:\n* Calverley Old Hall, Main Wing \u2013 adjacent to existing property let.  The pre-qualification stage of an architectural competition for the Hall's restoration closed on 1 August 2017, when likely construction costs were estimated at \u00a32.3m.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.landmarktrust.org.uk/get-involved/calverley-old-hall-competition/sections/competition-brief2/|title=The Landmark Trust|website=www.landmarktrust.org.uk|accessdate=5 August 2017}}</ref>  On 13 February 2018 the Trust announced the competition had been won by [http://www.cowpergriffith.co.uk Cowper Griffith].  Consultation with local residents on the proposed designs took place in March 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.landmarktrust.org.uk/news-and-events/latest-news/calverley-old-hall-design-competition-winners-announced/|title=Calverley Design Competition winners {{!}} The Landmark Trust|website=www.landmarktrust.org.uk|accessdate=24 May 2018}}</ref>  Awaiting appeal launch, previously planned for 2019.\n* Fairburn Tower, Inverness.  Category A listed Tower House, built in 1545 for Murdo Mackenzie, Gentleman of the Bedchamber for [[James V of Scotland|King James V.]]  Restoration proposals developed by [http://simpsonandbrown.co.uk Simpson and Brown] as Project Architects.  \u00a3500,000 grant pledged by [[Historic Environment Scotland]].  Appeal for \u00a3800,000 launched May 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.landmarktrust.org.uk/support-us/projects-and-appeals/fairburn-tower-appeal/|title=Fairburn Tower {{!}} The Landmark Trust|website=www.landmarktrust.org.uk|accessdate=24 May 2018}}</ref>  By autumn/winter 2019 all but \u00a389,000 had been raised.  Restoration work was expected to start soon thereafter for a planned completion in late summer 2021.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://issuu.com/landmark_trust/docs/landmark_trust_winter_newsletter_2019/8|title=Landmark Trust Winter Newsletter 2019|website=issuu|access-date=2020-02-06}}</ref>\n\nNew potential projects announced by February 2020 for development were<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.landmarktrust.org.uk/support-us/projects-and-appeals/future-projects/|title=Future projects|website=www.landmarktrust.org.uk|access-date=2020-02-06}}</ref>:\n\n*[https://nfknowledge.org/contributions/still-watching-over-ibsley/#map=10/-1.78/50.88/0/24:0:0.6|39:1:1|40:1:1 Ibsley Watch Tower], Ibsley, Hampshire - Derelict watch tower at one of the twelve RAF airfields in the New Forest.  Held on 99-year lease by RAF Ibsley Heritage Trust.\n*Mayor's Parlour Block, [https://www.dover.gov.uk/Leisure-Culture-Tourism/Heritage--Museums/Town-Hall/Maison-Dieu-Restoration-Project.aspx Maison Dieu], Dover, Kent - Part of 1835 transformation of Grade I complex of civic buildings dating back to 1204.\n*[http://www.mavisbank.org.uk Mavisbank], nr Edinburgh, Midlothian - Joint project with Historic Environment Scotland for Scotland's first Palladian villa.\n\n== Other projects previously considered for restoration ==\nOther properties previously considered by the Trust, but not progressed to completion, include:\n\n* Almshouses, [[Denton, Lincolnshire|Denton]], Lincolnshire<ref name=\":2\" /> \u2013 demolished by then owner Sir Bruno Welby, subsequently convicted in 1980 of unauthorised demolition of historic buildings and fined \u00a31,000 plus costs<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.lincstothepast.com/Almshouses--Denton/1403274.record?pt=S|title=Welby Almshouses, Denton|website=Lincs to the Past|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130503101526/http://www.lincstothepast.com/Almshouses--Denton/1403274.record?pt=S|archivedate=3 May 2013|url-status=dead|accessdate=30 March 2017}}</ref>\n*Falsgrave Signal Box, Scarborough, North Yorkshire - under consideration from 2016 to March 2019<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.landmarktrust.org.uk/support-us/projects-and-appeals/future-projects/|title=Future projects|website=www.landmarktrust.org.uk|accessdate=24 May 2018}}</ref>\n*The Master's House, Maidstone, Kent \u2013 rejected 2002 on grounds of size\n* Mausoleum, [[Seaton Delaval Hall|Seaton Delavel]] \u2013 rejected for risk of repayment of Department of the Environment grant<ref name=\":2\" />\n* Warder's Tower, Biddulph, Staffordshire \u2013 leased from Staffordshire County Council 2008\u20132010, returned when no acceptable solution could be found for dealing with four colonies of bats\n\n== Former properties ==\nProperties formerly run as holiday lets and owned, leased or run by the Landmark Trust on a management arrangement basis include:\n* All Saint's Vicarage, Maidenhead \u2013 First floor flat in Vicarage complex designed by [[George Edmund Street|G.E. Street]].  Advertised as being prepared for opening for lets in 1990<ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|year=1989|title=New properties open in 1990|url=|journal=Landmark Trust Newsletter|volume=|pages=|via=}}</ref> and in 1991 but not listed in 1992.\n* Edale Mill, [[Edale]], Derbyshire \u2013 The Trust bought the mill in 1969 and converted it into seven flats.  Six were sold after conversion with one being retained for holiday lets until c2012.\n* Fish Court, [[Hampton Court Palace]] \u2013 owned by [[Historic Royal Palaces]].  Withdrawn from property portfolio in 2014.\n* The Harp Inn, [[Old Radnor]], Powys \n* Higher Lettaford, North Bovey, Devon \u2013 sold in 2013 as no longer appropriate to the Trust's property portfolio\n* [[Hill House, Helensburgh]] \u2013 top floor flat returned to National Trust for Scotland in 2011.\n* The Master's House, [[Gladstone Pottery Museum|Gladstone Pottery]] \u2013 The Gladstone Pottery Museum was transferred to Stoke-on-Trent Museums in 1994.\n* Meikle Ascog, Ascog, Argyll & Bute \u2013 sold in 2013 as no longer appropriate to the Trust's property portfolio\n* Sandford House, 7 Lower High St, Stourbridge, West Midlands<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite book|title=Landmark Handbook 1988|last=Smith|first=Sir John|publisher=Landmark Trust|year=1988|isbn=0 9512953 0 6|location=|pages=6, 9}}</ref>\n* 30, St Mary's Lane, Tewkesbury \u2013 bought in 1969 and let to local tenants from 2006.\n* Wellbrook Beetling Mill, Cookstown, Co Tyrone \u2013 returned to National Trust\n\n== Legacy Estate \u2013 other properties owned by the Trust ==\nIn addition to properties let for Holiday rentals, the Trust has been bequeathed other properties which it has refurbished and managed in other ways, through its Legacy Estate.  These include:\n\n* Fountain Hotel, 92 High Street, Cowes, Isle of White \u2013 acquired 2010\n* The Tower, [[Netherne Hospital]], Netherne-on-the-Hill, Coulsdon, Surrey \u2013 bequeathed 2015<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.landmarktrust.org.uk/news-and-events/latest-news/legacy-case-study/|title=Legacy Case Study \u2013 Netherne-on-the-Hill|website=www.landmarktrust.org.uk|accessdate=5 August 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Handbooks ==\nDetails of each property available to rent are available online, on the Trust's website, and in a Handbook.  Twenty-five editions of the Handbook have been published to December 2016:\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Edition number\n!Year\n!Editor\n!Cover \n|-\n|1\n|1966\n|\n|\n|-\n|2\n|1968\n|\n|Green\n|-\n|3\n|1970\n|\n|Moss/Lime Green\n|-\n|4\n|1971\n|\n|Red\n|-\n|5\n|1972\n|\n|Blue\n|-\n|6\n|1973\n|\n|Moss Green\n|-\n|7\n|1977\n|John Smith\n|New Inn, Peasenhall\n|-\n|8\n|1988\n|Charlotte Haslam\n|Laughton Place\n|-\n|9\n|1989\n|Charlotte Haslam\n|Cawood Castle\n|-\n|10 (25 years anniversary edition)\n|1990\n|Charlotte Haslam\n|Swarkestone Pavilion\n|-\n|11\n|1991\n|Charlotte Haslam\n|Kingswear Castle\n|-\n|12\n|1992\n|John Smith and Charlotte Haslam\n|The Bath House\n|-\n|13\n|1993\n|John Smith and Charlotte Haslam\n|Prospect Tower\n|-\n|14\n|1994\n|Charlotte Haslam\n|Woodspring Priory\n|-\n|15\n|1995\n|Charlotte Haslam\n|Beamsley Hospital\n|-\n|16\n|1996\n|Constance Barrett\n|Tixall Gatehouse\n|-\n|17\n|1998\n|\n|Old Light, Lundy\n|-\n|18\n|1999\n|Constance Barrett\n|Banqueting House\n|-\n|19\n|2001\n|Constance Barrett\n|Swarkestone Pavilion\n|-\n|20\n|2003\n|Sophie Horton and Katherine Oates\n|Prospect Tower\n|-\n|21 (40 years anniversary edition)\n|2005\n|not credited\n|Freston Tower\n|-\n|22\n|2006\n|\n|Gothic Temple\n|-\n|23\n|2008\n|\n|The Pineapple\n|-\n|24\n|2011\n|\n|Culloden Tower\n|-\n|25 (50 years anniversary edition)\n|2014\n|Helen Hartstein\n|The Library\n|-\n|26 (published November 2018)\n|2018\n|\n|St Winifred's Well\n|}\n\n==Archives==\nThe Landmark Trust Lundy Island Philatelic Archive was donated to the [[British Library Philatelic Collections]] in 1991 and is located at the [[British Library]].<ref>[http://sherpa.bl.uk/42/01/philatelicresearchbl.pdf Philatelic Research at the British Library] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110722070224/http://sherpa.bl.uk/42/01/philatelicresearchbl.pdf |date=22 July 2011 }} by [[David Beech]]</ref>\n\n== Further reading ==\n* ''Landmark, A History of Britain in 50 Buildings''. 2015. Keay, Anna and Stanford, Caroline.  Francis Lincoln Ltd.  {{ISBN|978-0-7112-3645-5}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Landmark Trust}}\n*{{Official website|http://www.landmarktrust.org.uk|Landmark Trust}} \u2013 official site\n*[https://www.flickr.com/groups/landmarktrust/pool Landmark Trust] properties' photos on [[Flickr]]\n\n[[Category:Architecture of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Conservation organisations based in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Environmental charities based in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Landmark Trust| ]]\n[[Category:Lundy]]\n[[Category:Organisations based in Berkshire]]\n[[Category:Royal Borough of Windsor and Maidenhead]]\n[[Category:Organizations established in 1965]]\n", "name_user": "DannyS712", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fixing the location of periods / full stops", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Landmark_Trust"}
{"title_page": "Land's End to John o' Groats", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2019}}\n{{EngvarB|date=October 2015}}\n{{Unreliable sources|date=October 2015}}\n[[File:Landsendsignpost.jpg|Signpost at Land's End|thumb]]\n[[File:John o' Groats.JPG|Signpost at John o' Groats|thumb]]\n{{OSM Location map\n| lat=54.6\n| lon=-3.1\n| zoom=5\n| float = right\n| width = 230\n| height = 420\n|scalemark =120\n\n| mark-lat=58.644115\n| mark-lon=-3.069552\n| label = John o' Groats\n| label-size=15\n| label-pos = right\n| mark-title=John o' Groats\n| mark-image=John o' Groats.JPG\n| mark-description=The north-easterly tip of Scotland\n\n| mark-lat1=50.06811\n| mark-lon1=-5.71526\n| label1 = Land's End\n| label-pos1 = bottom\n| label-size1=12\n| mark-title1=Land's End\n| mark-image1=Signpost at Land's End.JPG\n| mark-description1=The south-western tip of Cornwall\n}}\n'''Land's End to John o' Groats''' is the traversal of the whole length of the island of [[Great Britain]] between two [[List of extreme points of the United Kingdom#Extreme points within the UK|extremities]], in the southwest and northeast.  The traditional distance by road is {{convert|874|mi|km}} and takes most cyclists 10 to 14 days; the record for running the route is nine days. Off-road walkers typically walk about {{convert|1200|mi|km}} and take two or three months for the expedition.  Two much-photographed signposts indicate the traditional distance at each end.\n\n* [[Land's End]] is the traditionally acknowledged extreme southern point of mainland England. It is in western Cornwall at the end of the Penwith peninsula. The O.S. Grid Reference of the road end is SW342250, Post Code TR19 7AA. In fact it, or strictly speaking Dr Syntax's Head, SW341253, a few hundred yards NW of the road end, is mainland England's most ''westerly'' point.<ref>Streetmap http://www.streetmap.co.uk/map.srf?x=134150&y=25450&z=0&sv=SW341254&st=5&mapp=map.srf&searchp=ids.srf</ref> The most southerly point is [[Lizard Point, Cornwall|Lizard Point]], about {{convert|9|mi|km|0}} further south. Land's End  is sometimes reckoned incorrectly as mainland England's most southwesterly point. This accolade belongs to Gwennap Head, SW365215, which is at least {{convert|2|mi|km|1}} further south than Dr Syntax's Head but only about {{convert|1.5|mi|km|1}} less west.<ref>Streetmap http://www.streetmap.co.uk/map.srf?x=136650&y=21550&z=0&sv=SW366215&st=5&mapp=map.srf&searchp=ids.srf</ref>\n* [[John o' Groats]] is the traditionally acknowledged extreme northern point of mainland Scotland, in northeastern [[Caithness]], O.S. Grid Reference ND380735, Post Code KW1 4YR. The actual northernmost point is [[Dunnet Head]] about {{convert|2|mi|km|0}} further north. The point that is farthest by road from Land's End is [[Duncansby Head]], about {{convert|2|mi|km|0}} east of John o' Groats. Duncansby Head is also the most northeasterly point of the Scottish mainland.<ref>Streetmap http://www.streetmap.co.uk/map.srf?x=340568&y=973320&z=120&sv=340568,973320&st=4&ar=y&mapp=map.srf&searchp=ids.srf&dn=639&ax=340568&ay=973320&lm=0</ref>\n\nThe straight-line distance from Land's End to John o' Groats is {{convert|603|mi|km}} as determined from O.S. Grid References, but such a route passes over a series of stretches of water in the [[Irish Sea]].  Google Earth reports a distance of 602.70 miles between the two iconic marker points.\n\nAccording to a 1964 road atlas, the shortest route using classified roads was {{convert|847|mi|km}} but in a 2008 road atlas, the shortest route using classified roads was {{convert|838|mi|km}}. An online route planner in 2011 also calculated the quickest route by road as {{convert|838|mi|km}}, estimating a time of 15 hours 48 minutes for the journey (this uses the [[A30 road|A30]], [[M5 motorway|M5]], [[M6 motorway|M6]], [[A74(M) and M74 motorways|A74(M), M74]], [[M73 motorway|M73]], [[M80 motorway|M80]], [[M9 motorway (Scotland)|M9]], [[A9 road (Scotland)|A9]] & [[A99 road|A99]]) but the overall shortest route by road, using minor roads in numerous places and utilising modern bridges, is only about {{convert|814|mi|km}}.  This route is roughly as follows: Land's End, [[Bodmin]], [[Okehampton]], [[Tiverton, Devon|Tiverton]], [[Taunton]], [[Bridgwater]], [[Avonmouth Bridge|the M5 Avon Bridge]], the [[M48 motorway|M48]] [[Severn Bridge]], [[Monmouth]], [[Hereford]], [[Shrewsbury]], [[Tarporley]], [[St Helens, Merseyside|St Helens]], [[Preston, Lancashire|Preston]], [[Carlisle, Cumbria|Carlisle]], [[Beattock]], [[Carstairs, South Lanarkshire|Carstairs]], [[Whitburn, West Lothian|Whitburn]], [[Falkirk]], [[Stirling]], [[Crieff]], [[Kenmore, Perth and Kinross|Kenmore]], Dalchalloch, A9, [[Inverness]], [[Kessock Bridge]], [[Cromarty Bridge]], [[Dornoch Firth Bridge]], [[Latheron]], [[Wick, Highland|Wick]], John o' Groats.\n\n[[Google Maps]], on 2 August 2017, calculated the fastest route by car, from the Land's End Visitor Centre to John o' Groats as being 837 miles and taking 14 hours 40 minutes.  It also showed a walking route of 811 miles, which it suggested would take 268 hours, and involve an elevation gain of 30,148 ft and an elevation fall of 30,272 ft.\n\n== Methods ==\n\nThere are many ways to go from Land's End to John o' Groats. Traditionally considered to be a walk, the route is now traversed in a number of ways, with cycling and multi-modal expeditions being particularly popular in recent years.\n\nMost trips are done by individuals or small groups for personal fulfilment. Some expeditions are organised as charity fundraisers, sometimes involving celebrities: examples include cricketer [[Ian Botham]]'s 1985 walk and athlete [[Jane Tomlinson]] in 2003. In recent history the route has been used as a rite of passage by cyclists taking on the most iconic cycling challenge in Britain.\n\n=== Walking ===\nThe first recorded end-to-end walk (actually from John o' Groats to Land's End) was undertaken by the brothers John and Robert Naylor in 1871.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gutenberg.org/etext/14415 |title=Naylor, J. and R. (1916) '&#39;From John o' Groats to Land's End'&#39; on Project Gutenberg |publisher=Gutenberg.org |date=22 December 2004 |accessdate=29 April 2010}}</ref>  Since then the walk has been undertaken many times, more particularly since 1960, after a well-publicised road walk by [[Barbara Moore (vegetarian)|Dr Barbara Moore]].  In 1960 the entrepreneur [[Billy Butlin]] organised a road walking race, which gave further impetus to the idea.\n\nSince the 1960s, walkers have mostly chosen off-road routes, using the growing network of [[long-distance footpaths in the United Kingdom|long-distance footpaths]].  A classic account is from 1966 by the travel writer [[John Hillaby]].<ref>Hillaby, J. (1966) ''Journey Through Britain'' Republished by Constable in 1995 {{ISBN|978-0-09-474990-0}}</ref> Off-road walkers usually complete the journey in two to three months. There is a considerable choice of off-road routes, but all are much longer than the shortest road distance, usually {{convert|1200|mi|km}} or more.  The walk is still undertaken by road walkers, often doing the walk, like [[Sir Ian Botham]], for charity, or as a \"challenge walk\".  They typically take a month or even less.\n\nSome walkers aim to complete the route piecemeal, perhaps over several years, to achieve the walk within the time constraints of a working life and before the possible health problems of retirement.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Drake|first1=John|title=End to end in bits : a story of a walk from Lands End to John O'Groats|date=2011|publisher=Alewords|location=Leeds|isbn=0951904760|url=https://www.scribd.com/document/163212607/Final-Version-of-End-to-End}}</ref>\n\n==== Routes ====\n\nThere is no continuous long-distance path from Land's End to John o' Groats.  There are long-distance paths for substantial sections of the route, and where they do not exist walkers connect them by [[Rights of way in England and Wales|rights of way]] and minor roads. Most walkers broadly follow these routes:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hockeylejog.co.uk/Links.htm#Otherwebsites |title=Annotated list of walkers routes, with links to websites |publisher=Hockeylejog.co.uk |date= |accessdate=29 April 2010}}</ref>\n*from Land's End to [[Exmoor]] by the [[South West Coast Path]]; or by a shorter inland route through [[Cornwall]] and [[Devon]] by minor roads and paths, the [[Two Castles Trail]] and the towpath of the [[Grand Western Canal]]\n*across [[Somerset]] by parts of the [[Macmillan Way West]], the [[Samaritans Way South West]] or the [[Limestone Link]]\n*to the [[Peak District]] either by\n**an eastern route using the [[Cotswold Way]], the [[Heart of England Way]] (or the [[Severn Way]]), the [[Staffordshire Way]] and the [[Limestone Way]]; or\n**a western route across the [[Severn Bridge]] then by the [[Offa's Dyke Path]], the [[Maelor Way]] and the [[South Cheshire Way]]\n*to the [[Scottish Borders]] by the [[Pennine Way]]\n*by [[St. Cuthbert's Way]] and a section of the [[Southern Upland Way]] to the [[Pentland Hills]], then by\n** a western route using the towpaths of the [[Union Canal (Scotland)|Union Canal]] and the [[Forth and Clyde Canal]], then by the [[West Highland Way]] and the [[Great Glen Way]] to [[Inverness]]; or\n** an eastern route across the [[Forth Road Bridge]] to [[Perth, Scotland|Perth]] and [[Pitlochry]], then by [[Glen Tilt]] and the [[Lairig Ghru]] to [[Strathspey, Scotland|Speyside]] and the old [[Wade road]] to Inverness.\n*from Inverness to John o' Groats, either by\n**the [[John o' Groats Trail]], a mostly coastal long distance route that is rough but walkable; \n**a route that is mostly on roads with a few stretches of coast walking; or \n**some walkers head north west from the end of the West Highland Way at [[Fort William, Scotland|Fort William]] using parts of the [[Cape Wrath Trail]], then head northeast through the [[Flow Country]] of [[Caithness]].  However, this route is through remote country and requires wild camping.\n\n=== Cycling ===\nThe official [[Road Records Association]] record for a rider on a conventional bicycle is 43 hours, 25 minutes and 13 seconds, set by 40 year old [[Michael Broadwith]] on 17 June 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cyclingtimetrials.org.uk/articles/view/349|title=Inside the 2018 End to End record attempt, words by Paul Jones|work=Cyclingtimetrials.org|accessdate=26 June 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe official [[Road Records Association]] Women's record: Lynne Taylor (Lynne Biddulph), 2002, 52 hours, 45 minutes and 11 seconds. <ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|title=Records Place to Place|url=http://www.rra.org.uk/|website=Road Records Association|accessdate=26 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe official [[Road Records Association]] Mixed Tandem Record: A Wilkinson & L E A Taylor (Lynne Biddulph), 2000, 51h 19m 23s.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\nMen's tandem bicycle. 5\u20137 May 2015 Riders: Dominic Irvine and Charlie Mitchell. Time: 1 day 21 hours 11 minutes.<ref>{{cite web|title=Records Place to Place|url=http://www.rra.org.uk/|website=Road Records Association|accessdate=30 June 2015}}</ref> The previous record held for 49 years.\n\nThe record for cycling from Land's End to John o' Groats is held by Andy Wilkinson, who completed the journey in 41 hours, 4 minutes and 22 seconds on a Windcheetah recumbent [[tricycle]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.windcheetah.co.uk/record.htm|title=Windcheetah recumbent tricycle scrapbook|work=windcheetah.co.uk|access-date=5 March 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100918234801/http://www.windcheetah.co.uk/record.htm|archive-date=18 September 2010|url-status=dead}}</ref> A typical cycling time when not attempting shortest time is 10 to 14 days. James MacDonald set a record in September 2017 for cycling from John o' Groats to Land's End and back again in five days, 18 hours and 3 minutes.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.projectkansas.org |title=Fastest return journey from John o' Groats to Land's End by bicycle |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170912132237/https://www.projectkansas.org/ |archive-date=12 September 2017 |url-status=live |website=Project Kansas}} {{As of|2017|10|17}} the success of the attempt had not been confirmed by Guinness. {{cite web|url=http://www.guinnessworldrecords.com/search/applicationrecordsearch?term=return+journey+Land%27s+end+to+John+o%27+Groats+bicycle&contentType=record |title=search for return journey Land's End to John o' Groats bicycle |website=www.guinnessworldrecords.com |access-date=17 October 2017}} {{registration required}}</ref> From 1 to 4 March 2010, [[David Walliams]], [[Jimmy Carr]], [[Fearne Cotton]], [[Miranda Hart]], [[Patrick Kielty]], [[Davina McCall]] and [[Russell Howard]] cycled in a team relay from John o' Groats to Land's End to raise money for [[Sport Relief]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/local/cornwall/hi/people_and_places/newsid_8551000/8551112.stm |title=Sport Relief celebrities reach Land's End |publisher=BBC News|accessdate=5 March 2010 | date=5 March 2010}}</ref>\n\nThe first tricyclist to complete the route was Alfred Nixon, champion of the London Tricycle Club, who in 1882 made \"the first, and at present only, tricycle journey from John o' Groats to Land's End, a distance of 1007 miles, in a fortnight\".<ref>Lincolnshire Chronicle 25 September 1883 p4.</ref> The current [[Road Records Association]] record on a non-recumbent tricycle is two days, 5 hours and 29 minutes ridden by [[Ralph Dadswell]] in 1992. \n\nMen's quadricycle. In the summer of 2012. Riders: Hugo Catchpole, George Unwin, Tom Bethell and Richard Nicholls. Time 10 days 15 hours. On a four-man recumbent bike weighing 114&nbsp;kg.\n\nSeveral cyclists have completed the route on folding bicycles. The fastest reported completion of LEJOG on 16-inch wheel Brompton bicycles is currently that of Si Trickett and Stephen Brindle, between 22-29 April 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://forum.cyclinguk.org/viewtopic.php?t=50504|title=Brompton Lejog - Cycling UK Forum|website=forum.cyclinguk.org}}</ref>\n\nThere have been several [[unicycle]] completions of the journey. The [[Guinness World Record]] for the fastest completion by unicycle is held by Roger Davies and Sam Wakeling, who rode {{convert|862|mi|km}} (Land's End to John o' Groats) from 12 to 18 September 2009 in 6 days, 8 hours and 43 minutes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.guinnessworldrecords.com/records/fastest-journey-from-land-s-end-to-john-o--groats-by-unicycle-(male)|title=Guinness World Records entry for Fastest journey o' Groats by unicycle (male)}}</ref> They rode large {{convert|36|in|mm|adj=mid|-wheeled}} unicycles equipped with two-speed Schlumpf geared hubs.<ref>[http://www.redwelly.co.uk/end2end/wordpress/ Event blog with details of the trip and certificates from LEJOG Association] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101125212929/http://www.redwelly.co.uk/end2end/wordpress/ |date=25 November 2010 }}, Redwelly.co.uk</ref>\n\nThe record for riding from Land's End to John o' Groats on a [[penny-farthing]] had not been broken since 1886, when Victorian cyclist [[George Pilkington Mills]] set it with a time of five days and one hour. Richard Thoday broke the then 133-year old record by completing his ride in four days, eleven hours and fifty-two minutes.( [[Guinness World Record]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.guinnessworldrecords.com/world-records/469573-fastest-journey-from-lands-end-to-john-o-groats-by-penny-farthing-male Guinness World Record|title=Fastest Journey from Land's End to John-O'-Groats by penny farthing (male)|publisher=}}</ref>) He averaged around 200 miles a day. He had undertaken the challenge to help raise \u00a310,000 for the charity [[Children in Need|BBC Children in Need]]. <ref>{{cite web |title=Cyclist Richard Thoday breaks penny farthing record |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-derbyshire-50451465 |website=BBC}}</ref>\n\nThe oldest person to cycle from Land's End to John o' Groats is Tony Rathbone (UK, b. 10 December 1932) who was aged 81 years and 162 days when he completed the journey on 21 May 2014. Roger Anthony \"Tony\" Rathbone started his journey from Land's End to John o' Groats on 7 May 2014 with his friend, William \"Billy\" Skipper. They cycled a total of 1,526.46&nbsp;km (948.5 miles) and were riding for a total of 79 hours 34 minutes. [[Guinness World Record]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.guinnessworldrecords.com/world-records/oldest-person-to-cycle-from-lands-end-to-john-o-groats|title=Oldest person to cycle from Land's End to John-O'-Groats|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017 Amelia Sampson aged 22 months completed John o' Groats to Land's End in 14 days in her trailer towed by her parents riding a tandem.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.touchnote.com/2017/06/23/epic-family-journey/|title=Cycling the country end-to-end: Postcards from an epic family journey  |publisher=[[Touchnote]]|date=23 June 2017|accessdate=11 July 2017}}</ref>\n\nAt the age of 4 years and 4 months, Rhoda Jones is believed to have become the youngest to cycle Land's End \u2013 John o' Groats on 2 September 2018.<ref>{{cite web |title='Famous' cyclist, 4, in record ride bid |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-northamptonshire-45399394 |accessdate=15 April 2019 |date=3 September 2018}}</ref> Cycling on a trailerbike with her parents Katie and Tom Jones<ref>{{cite web |title=Cyclists aged 83 years apart complete Land\u2019s End-John O\u2019 Groats within days of each other |url=https://road.cc/content/news/247861-cyclists-aged-83-years-apart-complete-lands-end-john-ogroats-within-days-each |website=road.cc |accessdate=15 April 2019 |language=en |date=4 September 2018}}</ref> she completed the ride in 22 days, 3 hours, 26 minutes. Her sister Ruth Jones, aged 5, completed the journey before her and became the fastest on a trailerbike.{{cn|date=April 2019}}\n\nOn 3 August 2018, Joshua Moisey, aged 7 years and 2 months, became the youngest Land's End \u2013 John o' Groats cyclist on a standard bicycle, riding his own bike alongside brother Reuben (10) and parents Alvin and Hiroko, and raising money for [[Alzheimer's Society]].<ref name=\"mcinerney\">{{cite news |last1=McInerney |first1=Liam |title=Penge boy, 7, becomes the youngest person to ever cycle the length of Britain |url=https://www.newsshopper.co.uk/news/16415254.penge-boy-7-becomes-the-youngest-person-to-ever-cycle-the-length-of-britain/ |accessdate=7 September 2018 |work=[[News Shopper]] |date=13 August 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | work=Bromley Times | page=6|date=16 August 2018 | url=http://edition.pagesuite-professional.co.uk/html5/reader/production/default.aspx?pubname=&edid=52e0fe25-5fbd-4af0-84d2-a4d552d448f5| access-date=8 September 2018 | title=Cycling family make history on musical ride out| last=Gantzer | first=Olivia}}</ref>\n\nThere are several annual mass participation cycle rides that go from Land's End to John o' Groats, the biggest of which is the Deloitte Ride Across Britain,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rideacrossbritain.com|title=Land's End to John O'Groats \u2013 Deloitte Ride Across Britain|work=Deloitte Ride Across Britain}}</ref> run by Threshold Sports. The Ride Across Britain takes over 800 riders the full length of Britain, taking nine days and covering {{convert|969|mi}}, with each rider covering an average of {{convert|107|mi}} per day. Previous celebrity participants include GB rower and Olympic gold medallist [[James Cracknell]] and former England Rugby captain [[Lewis Moody]].\n\n=== Running ===\nThe record time for a runner to complete the route, as reported by the Land's End John o' Groats Club, is nine days and 2 hours, by Andi Rivett.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.endtoenders.co.uk/transport.php | title=Methods of Transport | author=Land's End and John o' Groats Club | accessdate=25 March 2008 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080518014331/http://www.endtoenders.co.uk/transport.php | archive-date=18 May 2008 | url-status=dead }}</ref> In July 2008, Dan Driver became the first to run the route solo, meaning he carried all his equipment with him whilst he ran it.  He completed the run in just over 17 days.<ref name=\"devon\">{{cite news|title=Dan's the first to run the length of Britain without back-up team|url=http://www.devonlive.com/dan-s-run-length-britain-team/story-11806590-detail/story.html|accessdate=6 June 2017|work=devonlive.com|date=27 July 2008}}{{Dead link|date=February 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nThe current women's record of 12 days, 15 hours and 46 minutes was set by Marina (Mimi) Anderson from 16-28 July 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.guinnessworldrecords.com/world-records/fastest-journey-from-lands-end-to-john-o-groats-on-foot-(female)|title=Fastest journey from Land's End to John-O'-Groats on foot (female)|website=Guinness World Records}}</ref> In August 2019 the BBC reported that Sharon Gayter had completed the run four hours faster, in 12 days 11 hours 6 minutes, still to be verified by Guinness.<ref>{{cite news|title= Woman, 55, sets John O'Groats to Land's End running record|URL=https://www-bbc-co-uk.cdn.ampproject.org/v/s/www.bbc.co.uk/news/amp/uk-49212792?amp_js_v=a2&amp_gsa=1&usqp=mq331AQEKAFwAQ%3D%3D |work=BBC News|date=2 August 2019|access-date=4 August 2019| last=Agerholm|first=Harriet}}</ref>\n\nFred Hicks was an early record holder. He ran the journey between 20 and 30 May 1977 in 10 days 3 hours and 30 minutes. He ran this for charity, not aiming to set any records, and it was only later, when he was approached by the Road Running association asking if they could pursue the record with Guinness, that he became aware he had set a new record.{{cn|date=October 2017}} \n\nOn 12 July 2009 British [[ultramarathon]] runner Kevin Carr successfully completed the first ever attempt to run the route off-road, becoming the first athlete to run the length of the UK as a fell/trail run. Like Driver, Carr ran unsupported and solo\u2014a format commonly known amongst fell runners as a mountain marathon. Carr ran the challenge as part of an event organised by Benumber1,<ref>http://benumber1.co.uk/lejog.htm{{Dead link|date=February 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> an event that saw several top-level British athletes (mainly Olympians) completing the challenge. The event was designed to encourage school students to participate in sport and to realise the benefits of a healthy lifestyle, whilst raising funds for the [[British Heart Foundation]]. The run covered {{convert|1254|mi|km}} over footpaths, bridleways, canal paths, river banks, national trails, fields, moorland and mountains. Over 80% of the route was off-road, the route resorting to tarmac only when necessary to link two trails, or where a trail passed through a village/town. The run took 6 weeks 3 days and 17 hours (including three rest days). Factoring in the rest days, this run called for an average effort of just under {{convert|30|mi|km|sigfig=1}} a day, every day, for more than six weeks.{{Citation needed|date=June 2017}}\n\nIn July 2011, a team of runners from [[Calday Grange Grammar School]], Wirral completed a relay from Land's End to John o' Groats, becoming the first school to do so.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wirralnews.co.uk/news/local-news/calday-grange-grammer-school-runners-6570939|title=Wirral|work=liverpoolecho}}</ref> They raised \u00a3200,000<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.caldaygrangegrammarschool.co.uk/news/?pid=10&nid=1&storyid=42|title=Calday Grange Grammar School|work=caldaygrangegrammarschool.co.uk}}</ref> for [[Alder Hey Children's Hospital]], Liverpool.\n\nIn mid summer of 2011 Anthony Band from Surrey ran 1000 miles barefoot, all in aid for Help for heroes. Band took 29 days, running on average 36 miles per day.{{Citation needed|date=June 2017}}\n\nOn 3 August 2014, Marie-Claire Oziem became the first female runner to complete the distance unsupported and solo.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.triblogs.com/blog/1000miles/about-me?pid=2907|title=About Me|work=triblogs.com}}</ref> She pushed all her provisions in a pram and camped along the way. Her route consisted of both on and off-road sections. Oziem ran for the charity [[Mind (charity)|Mind]], based in Taunton for its project Go Wild, Stay Well, which aims to support those with mental illness through the use of various green therapy schemes. She started her run on 23 June and finished on 3 August 2014, regularly running distances of over 32 miles daily.{{Better source|reason=Source is an 'about me' page. A disinterested source is necessary.|date=June 2017}}\n\n=== By horse ===\n{{refimprove section|date=June 2017}}\nThe journey with a horse is generally completed north to south, starting in April to avoid the midges in the Highlands but also to benefit from warmer weather.{{cn|date=September 2018}}\n\nEvelyn Burnaby was the younger brother of the famous English Long Rider Colonel [[Frederick Burnaby]]. Whereas the elder brother was famous for having ridden across Central Asia and the Ottoman Empire, Evelyn decided to keep his equestrian adventures closer to home. He set off in 1892 to ride from Land's End, Cornwall to John o' Groats, Scotland. Evelyn's journey was soon serialised in a popular publication, ''[[The Country Gentleman]]'', and was published in book form the following year as ''A Ride from Land's End to John O' Groats''.<ref name=\"burnaby\">{{cite book |last1=Burnaby |first1=Evelyn |title=A Ride from Land's End to John O' Groats |date=1893 |publisher=Sampson Low, Marston & co. |location=London |url=https://archive.org/stream/ridefromlandsen00burngoog#page/n6 |accessdate=11 September 2018}}</ref>\n\nCommunist John Richard Penistan rode his horse, Billy-a-Journey from Land's End to John o' Groats in 1948 (or 1930<ref name=\"penlee-penistan\">{{cite web |title=Lands End To John O Groats On Horseback |url=https://www.penleehouse.org.uk/collections/item/PEZPH:2001.120.1164 |website=Photography |publisher=Penlee House |accessdate=11 September 2018}}</ref>) taking him 56 days. He was the first person to do the journey with just one horse.\n\nArthur Elliott, a veteran of the Great War, rode his horse, Goldflake, from Land's End to John o' Groats in 1955.<ref name=\"elliott-times\">{{cite news |title=Ride from Land's End to John O'Groats |work=The Times |date=26 October 1955 |page=6 |quote=Mr George Elliott, aged 62, of St. Ives, Cornwall, riding his eight-year-old chestnut mare, completed yesterday a journey from Land's End to John o' Groat's.}}</ref>\n\nIn 2006 the mother-and-daughter team of Vyv and Elsie Wood-Gee rode from John o' Groats to Land's End. Elsie was 13 at the time.\n\nFormer army officer Grant Nicolle continued the tradition by travelling from John o' Groats to Land's End in 2007 with Marv (solo and unsupported), taking 11 and a half weeks. Grant has published a book called 'Long Trot' through Amazon, documenting the trip.<ref name=\"nicolle-scotsman\">{{cite news |last1=Nicolle |first1=Grant |title=A journey from John o' Groats to Land\u2019s End on a horse |url=https://www.scotsman.com/news/a-journey-from-john-o-groats-to-land-s-end-on-a-horse-1-3905755 |accessdate=11 September 2018 |work=[[The Scotsman]] |date=2 October 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== Swimming ===\n[[Sean Conway (swimmer)|Sean Conway]] swam the complete route from 30 June 2013 to 11 November 2013 (135 days). On 31 August 2018 this time was bested by British endurance athlete Ross Edgely, who swam the complete route from Land's End to John o' Groats in just 62 days as part of his effort to swim around the entirety of mainland Britain.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.granthamjournal.co.uk/news/grantham-strongman-ross-edgley-reaches-john-ogroats-9007397/|title=Grantham strongman Ross Edgley breaks yet another record|last=Greenwood|first=Darren|date=31 August 2018|website=Grantham Journal|access-date=22 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Stand-up paddleboarding===\nThe first person to [[Standup paddleboarding|stand-up paddleboard]] (SUP) Land's End to John o'Groats was Cal Major, between 4 May 2018 and 2 July 2018, a total of 59 days. Major completely the journey solo and without any boat support.<ref name=\"lo\">{{cite web |last1=Lo |first1=Janice |title=Cal Major completes Land\u2019s End to John o\u2019Groats paddleboarding expedition |url=https://palmequipmenteurope.com/blog/2018/07/02/cal-major-completes-lands-end-to-john-ogroats-paddleboarding-expedition/ |website=Gone Paddling |publisher=Palm Equipment |accessdate=12 January 2019 |date=2 July 2018}}</ref> Her route took her along the Cornish and Devon coast into the [[Bristol Channel]], up the [[River Severn]] and by canals to [[Blackpool]], by sea around [[Cumbria]] and the [[Mull of Galloway]], across the [[Firth of Clyde]] to  [[Isle of Arran|Arran]], along the whole of the [[Caledonian Canal]], and up the coast of north east Scotland.<ref name=\"paddle\">{{cite web |title=2018: Lands End to John O\u2019Groats |url=https://paddleagainstplastic.com/2018-lands-end-to-john-ogroats/ |publisher=Paddle Against Plastic |accessdate=12 January 2019}}</ref>\n\nFiona Quinn became the first person to [[Standup paddleboarding|stand up paddleboard]] (SUP) Land's End to John o'Groats on an inflatable board, between 21 April and 10 July 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://fionalquinn.com/sup-britain|title=SUP Britain|website=Fiona Quinn|language=en-US|access-date=2019-03-06}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://fionalquinn.com/|title=Fiona Quinn|website=Fiona Quinn}}</ref>  Over the 81 day expedition, she spent just 35 of those paddling, waiting out bad weather in between. Her mainly sea-based route took her up the Cornish coast, crossing the [[Bristol Channel]] to [[Lundy Island]] and on to Pembrokeshire before she paddled over to Ireland. Continuing up the east coast of Ireland she cross back over the [[Irish Sea]] to the [[Mull of Kintyre]], through the full length of the [[Caledonian Canal]] and up the north east coast of Scotland. She also became the first woman to SUP across the Irish Sea and the first woman to complete a LEJOG triathlon, having walked and cycled the route in 2017. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sungod.co/explore/stories/1-paddleboard-1-world-record|title=1 Paddleboard & 1 World Record - How one woman escaped the 9-5 {{!}} SunGod Stories|website=www.sungod.co|language=en|access-date=2019-03-06}}</ref>\n\n=== Wheelchair ===\nThe fastest time in a wheelchair was achieved in August 2009 by US Navy Pilot Rick Ryan: eight days, 10 hours and 9 minutes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rideforremembrance.org/Photos.html|title=Photos and Blogs|work=Ride for Remembrance|date=15 August 2009|quote=15 Aug. 2009; We did it! ... A new world record: Land's End to John o' Groats by hand-crank wheelchair in 8 days: 10 hours: 9 minutes: 10 seconds|accessdate=21 September 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160113095551/http://www.rideforremembrance.org/Photos.html|archive-date=13 January 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n=== Skateboard ===\nThe record time to complete the {{convert|980|mi|km|adj=on}} journey on a skateboard is 21 days, achieved by Matt Elver, Charlie Mason and Lee Renshaw, who traveled around {{convert|50|mi|km|sigfig=1}} per day to raise money for charity.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/local/cornwall/hi/people_and_places/newsid_8841000/8841915.stm|title=BBC \u2013 Skateboarding the UK|date=21 July 2010|work=[[BBC Online]]|accessdate=16 November 2011}}</ref>\n\n=== Triathlon ===\nSean Conway became the first person to complete a length of Britain triathlon in 2013. He traveled between Lands End and John o'Groats three times,  cycling, running and swimming the route.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.seanconway.com/successes.html|title=Successes|website=SEAN CONWAY|language=en|access-date=2019-03-06}}</ref> Fiona Quinn became the first woman to complete a length of Britain triathlon in 2018. She traveled between Lands End and John o'Groats three times, cycling, walking and stand up paddleboarding the route.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://fionalquinn.com/adventures|title=Past adventures|website=Fiona Quinn|language=en-US|access-date=2019-03-06}}</ref> \n\n=== Motoring ===\n[[File:Anthony Frederick Wilding on a motorcycle.jpg|thumb|[[Tony Wilding]] at Land's End off to John o' Groats]]\nMotoring events between the two extremities have been held since the first decade of the 20th century, when the [[Auto-Cycle Union]] organised a series of runs for motorcycles.  In 1911, Ivan B. Hart-Davies became the holder of the final Land's End to John o' Groats record for solo motorcycles. Riding his 3.5&nbsp;hp single-speed Triumph, he covered the {{convert|886|mi|km}} in 29 hours, 12 minutes. As his average speed exceeded the then-maximum of 20&nbsp;mph, further official record attempts were banned by the A. C. U.\n\nThe [[Motor Cycling Club]] (which had been running the London to Land's End Trial since 1908, still held today, at least in name) put on an annual Land's End to John o' Groats Run from 1923 to 1928 which included cars as well as motorcycles.  These events were also known as the End to End. In 2006, [[BBC Television]] ran a series of three programmes called ''[[The Lost World of Friese-Greene]]'' covering [[Claude Friese-Greene]]'s 1920s-era road trip from Land's End to John o' Groats.  The trip had originally been filmed using the Biocolour process, developed by Claude's father [[William Friese-Greene]] and the film had degraded. The original print of Claude's film was subjected to computer enhancement by the [[British Film Institute]] to remove the flickering problem inherent in the Biocolour process.\n\nIn September 1983 rally and trials driver Dennis Greenslade from Cornwall created a new sole driver non-stop record drive from Land's End to John O'Groats and return using the newly released Audi 80 Quattro. The time taken was 24hours 32 minutes. Following this record achievement which also raised \u00a310,000 for three charities he established The Land's End - John O'Groats Association formed to authenticate all journeys between these two iconic landmarks.\n\nIn 1984, Neal Champion covered {{convert|884|mi|km}} from John o' Groats to Land's End in 11 hours, 14 minutes, on a [[Kawasaki motorcycles|Kawasaki]] GPZ750 Turbo.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.champ.org.uk/bikes/endtoend.htm|title=End to End Run|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=|access-date=}}</ref>\nIn 1984, Christian Conzendorf-Mattner accompanied by Dennis Greenslade covered the route from Land's End to John O'Groats\u2014there and back non-stop other than for fuel\u2014in 31 hours 22 mins in a 1941 BMW 327/80.\nThe record run was monitored by a team of journalists from a motoring magazine and is the current record for prewar classic cars end to end, non-stop, two drivers. The Land's End - John O'Groats Association awards this trophy to new record holders.\n\nOn 17 September 1988, Andrew Frankel and Mark Connaughton drove from Land's End to John o' Groats in a standard production Alfa Romeo 164 in 12 hours 30 minutes, including stops for refuelling.\n\nIn 1993, John Brown initiated the Land's End to John o' Groats Historic Reliability Trial, a race for vintage road vehicles.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hero.org.uk/artman2/publish/info/Who_s_who_at_HERO.shtml|title=Who's Who at HERO: John Brown|date=27 December 2006|work=HERO: Historic Endurance Rallying Organisation|accessdate=27 May 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080411223357/http://www.hero.org.uk/artman2/publish/info/Who_s_who_at_HERO.shtml|archive-date=11 April 2008|url-status=dead}}</ref>  The race is held each December and is a tough, three-day rally for old and classic cars, built between the 1920s and 1970s.  The route takes a long {{convert|1400|mi|km|adj=on}} route, using remote upland roads of the west of England, Wales (during the night), the Pennines and Scotland.  Medals are awarded in gold, silver and bronze categories.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hero.org.uk/artman2/publish/techinfo/index.shtml|title=Historic Endurance Rallying Organisation Regulations & Eligibility|work=HERO: Historic Endurance Rallying Organisation|accessdate=16 December 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100101193846/http://www.hero.org.uk/artman2/publish/techinfo/index.shtml|archive-date=1 January 2010|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nOn 15\u201316 April 1997, Hugh Edeleanu drove the route in a [[J. C. Bamford|JCB]] excavator in a time of 22 hours, 10 minutes and 30 seconds.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/yesterday-was-a-1261628.html|title=yesterday was a ...|publisher=The Independent|date=17 May 1997}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2001, Wayne Booth became the first person to do the journey by motorcycle without stopping; the 37-year-old completed the historic trip in 14 hours and 52 minutes, averaging 57&nbsp;mph, on a modified 1,000cc Honda Varedero, complete with additional 74-litre petrol tank. The meticulously researched route of {{convert|854|mi|km}} passed through just two sets of traffic lights and was completed within all highway regulations, law and speed limits.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.endtoenders.co.uk/history_record_breakers.php|title=End to Enders \u2013 The End To End Challenge|work=endtoenders.co.uk|access-date=28 July 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140803082709/http://www.endtoenders.co.uk/history_record_breakers.php|archive-date=3 August 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/UK+top+to+bottom+non+stop.-a077042421|title=UK top to bottom non-stop.|work=thefreelibrary.com}}</ref> Booth and the dozen strong support team raised over \u00a31,000 for The [[National Childbirth Trust]] and [[Macmillan Cancer Support|Macmillan Cancer Relief]].\n\nOn 22 May 2011, Kevin Sharpe and David Peilow completed the first end-to-end run from John o' Groats to Land's End in an electric car over two days, using only [[charging station]]s available to the general public, in a [[Tesla Roadster (2008)|Tesla Roadster]] sports car.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thegreencarwebsite.co.uk/blog/index.php/2011/05/23/tesla-travels-from-lands-end-to-john-ogroats/|title=TheGreenCarWebsite.co.uk|work=thegreencarwebsite.co.uk|access-date=23 May 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120315131620/http://www.thegreencarwebsite.co.uk/blog/index.php/2011/05/23/tesla-travels-from-lands-end-to-john-ogroats/|archive-date=15 March 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n[[File:Nissan Leaf at lands End.jpeg|alt=Nissan Leaf at lands End|thumb|Jonathan Porterfield and Chris Ramsey at Land's End in a Nissan leaf]]\n\nOn 7 August 2011, Darren Whitehead & Tony Dwight travelled {{convert|1071|mi|km}} from John o' Groats to Land's End (including crossing the Welsh border) in 5 days using two ride-on [[Wheel Horse]] lawn mowers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nwlmra.org/pages/the-lawn-way-round.html|title=North West Lawn Mower Racing Association \u2013 The Lawn Way Round|last=|first=|date=|access-date=|work=nwlmra.org|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170607073803/http://nwlmra.org/pages/the-lawn-way-round.html|archive-date=7 June 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref> They also raised money for charity during the trip which was named The Lawn Way Down.\n\nOn 30 November 2013, Lucy Grogan, travelling on a BMW GS R1200 motorbike, and her father Martin Grogan, travelling in a Mini Cooper Works, travelled from Land's End to John o' Groats in 19 hours, leaving Land's End at 4:30am and arriving at John o' Groats at 11:30pm same day. This was in aid of Safe Haven Children's Trust and raised \u00a33,000 for the non-governmental organisation.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/the2550milechallenge|title=Facebook|work=facebook.com}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2015, Jonathan Porterfield and Chris Ramsey beat the record in a [[Nissan Leaf]] electric car, using the existing public rapid charger infrastructure to travel there and back. The route south took 28 hours and 38 minutes, and the return trip 27 hours and 46 minutes.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://driveev.net/2016/04/01/plugging-in-for-another-adventure/|title=Plugging in for another adventure|first=Stephen|last=Brown|date=1 April 2016|publisher=}}</ref> They submitted an application to Guinness World Records to have the quicker time recognised as a record.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-highlands-islands-34345863|title=Electric car trip from Land's End to John O'Groats 'a record'|work=BBC News}}</ref>\n[[File:Dr Jeff Allan and Ben Cottam-Allan at John o'Groats.jpg|alt= Dr Jeff Allan and his son Ben Cottam-Allan having completed their journey from Lands End to John o' Groats set off for the return journey in their Tesla electric car.|thumb|Dr Jeff Allan and his son Ben Cottam-Allan having completed their journey from Land's End to John o' Groats set off for the return journey.]]\n\nOn 7 October 2015, Jeff Allan and his son, Ben Cottam-Allan, beat the electric car record in a [[Tesla Model S]] completing the northbound route in 19 hours 45 minutes and the southbound route in 18 hours 53 minutes. Jeff prepared the route by cycling in May 2015. They hold the Guinness World Record for shortest charging time from John o' Groats to Land's End of 3 hours  44 minutes 33 seconds.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.autovolt-magazine.com/father-and-son-set-new-guinness-world-record-in-electric-car/|title=Father and Son Set New Guinness World Record in Electric Car|date=17 October 2016|newspaper=AutoVolt Magazine|language=en-US|access-date=30 January 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.theargus.co.uk/news/14682326.Record_breaking_electric_car_and_Europe__39_s_first_dragster_to_appear_at_Brighton_Speed_Trials/|title=Record-breaking electric car and Europe's first dragster to appear at Brighton Speed Trials|website=The Argus|language=en|access-date=30 January 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tesla.com/en_GB/customer-stories/lands-end-john-o-groats|title=Lands End to John O\u2019Groats|website=www.tesla.com|language=en-GB|access-date=30 January 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn 21 August 2017, John Chivers completed the first journey by electric motorcycle (a [[Zero Motorcycles|Zero]] DSR) from Land's End to John o' Groats, then continued his journey to [[Orkney]] and finally to [[Skaw,_Unst|Skaw]], on the island of [[Unst]], [[Shetland]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.johnchivers.com/lejogskaw/|title=Land's End to John o'Groats to Skaw by Electric Motorcycle|website=www.johnchivers.com}}</ref> The journey from Land's End to John o' Groats took him four days to complete, breaking the journey up into ten parts, each stop requiring a charge of at least three hours.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.shetnews.co.uk/newsbites/15101-fundraiser-completes-first-lands-end-to-unst-trip-on-electric-motorbike|title=Fundraiser from Land\u2019s End to Unst on electric motorbike|work=[[The Shetland News]]|accessdate=1 September 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn 30 July 2017 Andy Maxfield from [[Inskip, Lancashire|Inskip]] near Preston completed the journey from John O'Groats to Land's End on an unmodified [[List of John Deere tractors|John Deere X750]] ride on [[lawn tractor]]. The 874 mile journey was completed in a Guinness World Record time<ref name=\"breen\">{{cite news |last1=Breen |first1=Jim |title=Epic lawn tractor journey is officially a world record |url=https://www.agriland.co.uk/farming-news/epic-lawn-tractor-journey-is-officially-a-world-record/ |accessdate=9 August 2018 |work=AgriLand |date=8 August 2018}}</ref> of 5 days 8 hours 36 mins with an average speed of around 9mph. <ref>https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/av/uk-england-lancashire-45127295/lawnmower-man-andy-maxfield-breaks-uk-speed-record</ref> This journey was inspired by his father James Maxfield who suffered from [[Alzheimer's]] for 13 years with the challenge raising around \u00a310,000 for The [[Alzheimer's Society]]. The journey was completed with a support team from John Deere and his two daughters Kathryn and Kaitlyn Maxfield.<ref name=\"lancspost\">{{cite news |title=Andy\u2019s 400-mile trip \u2013 on a lawnmower |url=https://www.lep.co.uk/your-lancashire/preston/andy-s-400-mile-trip-on-a-lawnmower-1-8675651 |accessdate=30 July 2018 |work=Lancashire Post |date=28 July 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"johndeere\">{{cite web |title=Going the Distance: A Man, a Mower, and a Mission from the Heart |url=https://johndeerejournal.com/2017/09/going-the-distance-a-man-a-mower-and-a-mission-from-the-heart/ |website=John Deere Journal |publisher=John Deere |accessdate=30 July 2018 |date=11 September 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2017, Tommy Davies and Tom Harvey completed the 841 mile journey in 9 hours and 36 minutes, the fastest time ever recorded between the two points on land, with an overall average of 86.7 mph. They used a specially adapted Audi S5 with an additional fuel tank and an array of equipment to avoid detection from the police and speed cameras. The trip was allegedly tracked via a GPS tracker and filmed, although the footage and data has not been publicly released, presumably in an effort to avoid possible prosecution due to the excessive speed involved.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2018/05/28/record-breaking-driver-drove-length-britain-nine-hours-should/|title=Record-breaking driver who drove length of Britain in nine hours 'should be prosecuted for speeding'|last=Ellson|first=Andrew|date=29 May 2018|work=The Times|access-date=12 August 2018|language=en|issn=0140-0460}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.gizmodo.co.uk/2018/05/man-averages-90mph-in-illegal-but-impressive-country-race-run/|title=Man Averages 90mph in Illegal-But-Impressive Country Race Run|website=Gizmodo UK|language=en|access-date=12 August 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2018 the first hydrogen powered fuel cell electric vehicle, a [[Toyota Mirai]] completed the journey. <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.autocar.co.uk/car-news/features/john-o%E2%80%99groats-land%E2%80%99s-end-hydrogen-fuel-cell-car</ref> Driven by Richard Bremner and Luc Lacey from [[Autocar magazine]] and Jon Hunt from [[Toyota]] they started the journery from Kirkwall in the Orkney's. To reach the hydrogen refuelling infrastructure at the time they travelled via Aberdeen, Sunderland, <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/business/business-news/sunderland-firm-haskel-helps-toyota-14799017</ref>Rotherham and Beaconsfield covering 1,109 miles (1785 Km) at an average speed of 56 miles an hour.  The journey took 19 hours 40 minutes with hydrogen consumption of 0.9kg per 100Km (16.1 kg of hydrogen consumed). <ref>{{cite web|url=https://blog.toyota.co.uk/mirai-marathon-maps-uk-hydrogen-fuel-future</ref> \n [[File:Toyota Mirai John O'Groats.jpg|thumb|Richard Bremner with the Toyota Mirai the first JOG to LE Hydrogen Fuel Cell Car at  John O'Groats]]\n[[File:Toyota Mirai Lands End.jpg|thumb|Jon Hunt with the Toyota Mirai the first JOG to LE Hydrogen Fuel Cell Car at Land's End]]\n\n=== Public transport ===\nThe current fastest journey by bus and coach was set by John and Kirsty Boyd from Runcorn, Cheshire, who travelled from Land's End to John O' Groats in August 2017 using 20 buses/coaches, in three days, 2 hours and 47 minutes.<ref>{{cite web|url=\nhttps://m.facebook.com/story.php?story_fbid=403249583464974&id=330226477433952| title=Completion certificates issued by the Lands End \u2013 John o'Groats Association | date=27 January 2018 | accessdate=28 January 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe current fastest journey by local bus (defined as in section 3 of the Transport Act 1980 to be a stage carriage service with stops within 30 miles)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.legislation.gov.uk/ukpga/1980/34/pdfs/ukpga_19800034_en.pdf|title=Transport Act 1980|website=Legislation Gov Uk|access-date=22 May 2019}}</ref>  was set by Clive Burgess in September 2016. He travelled from Lands End to John O'Groats using 31 buses, in 3 days, 8 hours and 55 minutes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.retro-speed.co.uk/showfeature.asp?art=20605|title=\u2018Le Jog\u2019 \u2013 a magnet to the competitive spirit|access-date=22 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2014, to celebrate completing his GCSE exams, 16-year-old Adam Mugliston travelled from Land's End to John o' Groats on 36 buses in four days, 10 hours and 44 minutes.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/howaboutthat/10947507/Its-a-record-four-days-by-bus-from-Lands-End-to-John-OGroats.html|title=It's a record: four days by bus from Land's End to John O'Groats|date=4 July 2014|work=Telegraph.co.uk}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2011, James Aukett travelled from Land's End to John o' Groats on 31 buses in five days, 7 hours and 25 minutes. James undertook the trip to raise money for children's charity, [[The Children's Society]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lejogbuscountry.org.uk|title=Lejog Bus Country \u2013 Home|work=lejogbuscountry.org.uk|access-date=22 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130422212129/http://lejogbuscountry.org.uk/|archive-date=22 April 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Lands-end-richard-elloway-bus-trip.jpg|thumb|right|Richard Elloway, having completed the return trip using a senior bus-pass \"without paying a penny\".]]\nIn 2008, Richard Elloway of Somerset claims to be the first person to complete the journey from Land's End to John o' Groats and back free of charge by local buses, using the [[English National Concessionary Travel Scheme|English National Concessionary Pass]] (a [[free travel pass|free bus pass]] for people over 60, allowing free off-peak travel on local bus services throughout England) introduced on 1 April 2008, and the pre-existing equivalent concession for pensioners in Scotland. He completed the first leg of the trip in one week and six hours.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/scotland/highlands_and_islands/7340441.stm | title= 'Ultimate holiday' on a bus pass | author= BBC News | date=4 October 2008 | accessdate=10 April 2008}}</ref> The entire journey was completed in two weeks, 8 hours and 30 minutes.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.countygazette.co.uk/display.var.2201842.0.a_pensioners_twoweek_bus_journey.php | title= A pensioner's two-week bus journey | author= Rebecca Hehir (Somerset County Gazette) | date=16 April 2008 | accessdate=16 April 2008}}</ref>\n\nIn 1954, Gertrude Leather travelled by 17 local buses from Land's End to London, at a cost of \u00a31 19s 6d (\u00a31.97\u00bd), and the following year travelled from London to John o' Groats by 25 local buses at a cost of \u00a34 5s 9\u00bdd (\u00a34.29).<ref>Leather, G. and Parke, J (1986) ''Home with the Heather'' Ian Allan {{ISBN|0-7110-1550-3}}</ref>\n\nThe winter timetables offer a fastest route on land public transport of exactly 24 hours, departing Land's End car park  at 13:34 on day 1 and arriving at John O'Groats ferry terminal car park at 13:34 on day 2. This involves a First Kernow route A1 bus to Penzance, trains to Penzance, Tamworth and Crewe to meet the London\u2013Inverness sleeper train, then the following morning Stagecoach buses X98 and 77 via Wick to John O'Groats. On a Friday schooldays route 77 doesn't operate and instead there's a 177 which arrives John O'Groats nine minutes earlier at 1325 making it possible to do the overall trip in 23 hours 51 minutes. However, in the summer buses depart Lands End at 40 minutes past each hour (instead of 34 minutes every two hours) with an extended journey time to allow for traffic congestion making too tight a connection to the train in Penzance to be sure of completing the journey. <ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.transportdirect.info/TransportDirect/en/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=14 April 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080123154145/http://www.transportdirect.info/TransportDirect/en/ |archive-date=23 January 2008 |url-status=dead }} Sample journeys checked 16 June 2019</ref>\n\n===Hitchhiking===\nM. Clark and G. Beynon are the last hitchhikers recorded in the ''Guinness Book of Records'' for the Land's End to John o' Groats trip (17 hours 8 minutes).\n\n===Paramotor (motorised paraglider)===\nThe first recorded journey by [[paramotor]] was by Andy Phillips, supported by a team of British Royal Marines in September 2000. The trip took a little over six days and was completed from south to north.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.flight.firstnet.co.uk/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=9 May 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20121223220121/http://www.flight.firstnet.co.uk/ |archivedate=23 December 2012  }}</ref>\n\nThe first recorded trip from north to south was by John Caston, Brian Pushman, Alex Heron and Henry Glasse in September 2009 and took five days.\n\nIn July 2016 a group of four pilots completed the trip from north to south in 6.5 days. This included double amputee Cayle Royce, who became the first person to fly the route in a ParaTrike.\n\n=== Golf ===\nIn 2005 Surrey-based golfer and member of the Kent Golf Society David Sullivan walked from John o' Groats to Land's End hitting golf balls all the way. He travelled the {{convert|1100|mi|km}} in seven weeks to be eligible for the Guinness Book of Records as the longest golf hole. He raised money for the [[Variety Club]], the [[2004 Indian Ocean earthquake and tsunami]] Appeal, and the [[Orpheus Centre]], a residential arts and learning facility for the young and disabled in Surrey.\n\n=== Aeroplane ===\nThe fastest passage between the two points was made in 1988 by a [[McDonnell Douglas Phantom in UK service|McDonnell Douglas F-4K Phantom]] in a time of 46 minutes 44 seconds <ref>{{cite web|url=http://johneckersley.wordpress.com/tales/route-designer/|title=The Route Designer\u2019s Tale \u2013 Books by John and Nancy Eckersley|work=Books by John and Nancy Eckersley}}</ref>\n\n===In a straight line===\nOn 17 May 2014 a team of four set off to complete [[Beeline Britain]] \u2013 a journey from Land's End to John o' Groats in a straight line.  This never before attempted route was completed in 28 days and required the two biggest sea kayak crossings ever completed in UK waters.\n\n*The first crossing went direct from Land's End to Pembrokeshire \u2013 a distance of over 200&nbsp;km which took 34.5 hours to complete.\n*The second crossing went direct from Pembrokeshire to Anglesey \u2013 around 170&nbsp;km and taking 24.5 hours to complete.\n\nThe team then kayaked, biked and hiked the remainder of the route which went via:\nIsle of Man \u2013 Dalmellington \u2013 Glasgow \u2013 Crieff \u2013 traversing [[Ben Macdui]] the second highest mountain in the UK \u2013 Lossiemouth \u2013 across the Moray Firth \u2013 Lybster \u2013 John o' Groats.\n\nThe project was devised and managed by Ian O'Grady.  He recruited the Team GB Paralympian [[Nick Beighton]], Adam Harmer, a professional kayak coach and University Lecturer, [[Tori James]] who was the first Welsh woman to stand on the summit of [[Mount Everest]].  Beeline Britain's aim was to raise funds and awareness for [[Blesma, The Limbless Veterans|Blesma]], the limbless veterans charity.  The project gained full royal endorsement from the Royal Foundation of the [[Duke of Cambridge|Duke]] and [[Catherine, Duchess of Cambridge|Duchess]] of Cambridge and [[Prince Harry]], and has to date raised over \u00a320,000 for Blesma.\n\nThe whole journey was captured by filmmaker Ian Burton for the feature documentary ''As The Crow Flies'' <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reelhouse.org/imageimpossible/as-the-crow-flies|title=As The Crow Flies|work=reelhouse.org|access-date=28 January 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170704230411/https://www.reelhouse.org/imageimpossible/as-the-crow-flies|archive-date=4 July 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n== Youngest and oldest ==\n\nThe Land's End\u2013John o' Groats Association presents the Jack Adams/Richard Elloway Trophy annually to the youngest person to have completed the journey other than as a passenger in a motor vehicle. Henry Cole completed the journey in June 2006, at the age of four; he cycled over 31 days. He started school in the following September, and was presented with the Jack Adams/Richard Elloway Trophy in January 2007. Sophie George is currently the youngest recipient of the Jack Adams/Richard Elloway Trophy. She completed the journey by bus and train in August 2016 at the age of two years and 10 months and was awarded the trophy in January 2017.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.sloughobserver.co.uk/news/15096260.Three_year_old_girl_lands_prize_for_travelling_length_of_UK|title=Three-year-old lands prize as youngest to travel from Lands End to John O'Groats|publisher=Slough Observer|date=11 April 2008}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017 Amelia Sampson aged 22 months completed John o' Groats to Land's End in 14 days in her trailer towed by her parents riding a tandem.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.touchnote.com/2017/06/23/epic-family-journey/|title=Cycling the country end-to-end: Postcards from an epic family journey  |publisher=[[Touchnote]]|date=23 June 2017|accessdate=11 July 2017}}</ref>\n\nReg Savill is the oldest person to complete the journey on foot (although in the reverse direction from John o' Groats to Land's End), at the age of 74.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/cornwall/content/articles/2008/04/11/people_busholiday_feature.shtml|title=On the Buses|publisher=BBC|date=16 February 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Organisations ==\n\nThere are three organisations supporting people undertaking the journey.\n* The '''Land's End\u2013John o' Groats Association''' is a non-commercial organisation established in 1983 for \"those who have completed the epic journey from Land\u2019s End to John o' Groats, or vice versa, by any means in a single trip\".<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.lejog.org/ | title=The Land's End \u2013 John o' Groats Association | accessdate=28 January 2018}}</ref>\n* The '''Land's End John o' Groats Club''', which is sponsored by the company that operates facilities at Land's End and John o' Groats, the end points.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.endtoenders.co.uk/ | title=The Land's End John o' Groats Club | accessdate=25 March 2008 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080513045100/http://www.endtoenders.co.uk/ | archive-date=13 May 2008 | url-status=dead }}</ref> It holds an annual awards ceremony to select the most notable 'end-to-enders' each year.\n* '''Bike the UK for MS''' is a charity raising awareness for [[multiple sclerosis]] research and patients by running supported cycling trips including from Land's End to John o' Groats. They combine \"an important cause with an incredible experience to help fund treatment and research for a cure whilst addressing the challenges for those affected by MS\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.biketheukforms.org|title=Bike the UK for MS {{!}} Welcome!|website=www.biketheukforms.org|language=en-US|access-date=11 February 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Scottish equivalent ==\n\nUntil [[Acts of Union 1707|Union with England]] in 1707, [[Scotland]]'s equivalent of the phrase was often \"John o' Groats to Maidenkirk\", as [[Maidenkirk]] (Kirkmaiden) was traditionally considered Scotland's southernmost point, a {{convert|388|mi|km|adj=on}} trip. This can be found in [[Robert Burns]]' poem ''On [[Francis Grose|Captain Grose]]'s Peregrinations thro' Scotland''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.robertburns.org/works/275.shtml|title=Robert Burns Country: On The Late Captain Grose's Peregrinations Thro' Scotland: Collecting The Antiquities Of That Kingdom|website=www.robertburns.org}}</ref> and the song, ''The Lady of Kenmure'':\n\n:From John o' Groats to Maidenkirk\n:You'll never find a truer\n:For loyal faith and dauntless deeds,\n:Than the Lady of Kenmure.\n\nThe southernmost village in Scotland is actually nearby [[Drummore]].<ref>''Drummore \u2013 most southerly village'', Visit South West Scotland, https://www.visitsouthwestscotland.com/towns/drummore/</ref>\n\n==English equivalent==\n\nThe length of the [[England|English mainland]] is delineated by the distance between [[Land's End]] and [[Marshall Meadows Bay]] in [[Northumberland]]. The distance is {{convert|556|mi|km}} by road or {{convert|426|mi|km}} [[as the crow flies]]. The traversal of the length of England is sometimes used to define charity events such as walks and cycle-rides.\n\n== See also ==\n*[[Malin to Mizen]]\n*[[Du battant des lames au sommet des montagnes]]\n\n*[[Israel National Trail]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n'''Road walking'''\n* Smailes, B. (2004) ''John o' Groats to Land's End: the Official Challenge Guide'' Challenge Publications {{ISBN|978-1-903568-18-7}}\n\n'''Offroad walking'''\n* Robinson, A. (2007) ''The End to End Trail: Land's End to John o' Groats on Foot'' Cicerone {{ISBN|978-1-85284-512-4}}\n* McCloy, A. (2001) ''The Land's End to John o' Groats Walk'' Cordee {{ISBN|1-871890-59-4}}\n* Salter, M. (2006) ''Land's End to John o' Groats \u2013 a Thousand Mile Walking Route'' Folly Publications {{ISBN|978-1-871731-71-2}}\n\n'''Cycling'''\n* Mitchell, N (2012) End to End Cycle Route: Land's End to John o' Groats (Cicerone Press) {{ISBN|978-1-85284-670-1}}\n* Smailes Brian (2009) ''Land's End to John o' Groats Cycle Guide \u2013 The Official Challenge Guide'' Challenge Publications {{ISBN|978-1-903568-59-0}}\n* Brown, Simon (1995) ''Land's End to John o' Groats Cycle Guide'', Cicerone {{ISBN|978-1-85284-188-1}}\n* Salter, P. (2002) ''Bike Britain: Cycling from Land's End to John o' Groats'' Epic New Zealand {{ISBN|978-0-9582256-1-8}}\n* Lewis, D. (2005) \"[https://www.amazon.co.uk/gp/product/B0154XW9SS/ Land's End to John o' Groats\", On a beer mat] Publish and Print\n\n== External links ==\n*[http://www.ukendtoend.com/ Comprehensive Free Journal \"Walking the length of Britain\" Includes detailed preparation tools.]\n*[http://www.longwalks.org.uk/bibliographytop.html A bibliography of LEJOG/JOGLE published reports and guidebooks, and links to relevant websites]\n*[http://www.ldwa.org.uk/ldp/members/show_path.php?path_name=Land%27s+End+to+John+O%27Groats Land's End to John o' Groats on the Long Distance Walkers' Association website]\n*[http://www.beelinebritain.com Land's End to John o' Groats in a straight line \u2013 one of the last Great British adventures.]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Land's End To John O' Groats}}\n[[Category:Geography of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Long-distance footpaths in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Scenic routes in the United Kingdom]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2019}}\n{{EngvarB|date=October 2015}}\n{{Unreliable sources|date=October 2015}}\n[[File:Landsendsignpost.jpg|Signpost at Land's End|thumb]]\n[[File:John o' Groats.JPG|Signpost at John o' Groats|thumb]]\n{{OSM Location map\n| lat=54.6\n| lon=-3.1\n| zoom=5\n| float = right\n| width = 230\n| height = 420\n|scalemark =120\n\n| mark-lat=58.644115\n| mark-lon=-3.069552\n| label = John o' Groats\n| label-size=15\n| label-pos = right\n| mark-title=John o' Groats\n| mark-image=John o' Groats.JPG\n| mark-description=The north-easterly tip of Scotland\n\n| mark-lat1=50.06811\n| mark-lon1=-5.71526\n| label1 = Land's End\n| label-pos1 = bottom\n| label-size1=12\n| mark-title1=Land's End\n| mark-image1=Signpost at Land's End.JPG\n| mark-description1=The south-western tip of Cornwall\n}}\n'''Land's End to John o' Groats''' is the traversal of the whole length of the island of [[Great Britain]] between two [[List of extreme points of the United Kingdom#Extreme points within the UK|extremities]], in the southwest and northeast.  The traditional distance by road is {{convert|874|mi|km}} and takes most cyclists 10 to 14 days; the record for running the route is nine days. Off-road walkers typically walk about {{convert|1200|mi|km}} and take two or three months for the expedition.  Two much-photographed signposts indicate the traditional distance at each end.\n\n* [[Land's End]] is the traditionally acknowledged extreme southern point of mainland England. It is in western Cornwall at the end of the Penwith peninsula. The O.S. Grid Reference of the road end is SW342250, Post Code TR19 7AA. In fact it, or strictly speaking Dr Syntax's Head, SW341253, a few hundred yards NW of the road end, is mainland England's most ''westerly'' point.<ref>Streetmap http://www.streetmap.co.uk/map.srf?x=134150&y=25450&z=0&sv=SW341254&st=5&mapp=map.srf&searchp=ids.srf</ref> The most southerly point is [[Lizard Point, Cornwall|Lizard Point]], about {{convert|9|mi|km|0}} further south. Land's End  is sometimes reckoned incorrectly as mainland England's most southwesterly point. This accolade belongs to Gwennap Head, SW365215, which is at least {{convert|2|mi|km|1}} further south than Dr Syntax's Head but only about {{convert|1.5|mi|km|1}} less west.<ref>Streetmap http://www.streetmap.co.uk/map.srf?x=136650&y=21550&z=0&sv=SW366215&st=5&mapp=map.srf&searchp=ids.srf</ref>\n* [[John o' Groats]] is the traditionally acknowledged extreme northern point of mainland Scotland, in northeastern [[Caithness]], O.S. Grid Reference ND380735, Post Code KW1 4YR. The actual northernmost point is [[Dunnet Head]] about {{convert|2|mi|km|0}} further north. The point that is farthest by road from Land's End is [[Duncansby Head]], about {{convert|2|mi|km|0}} east of John o' Groats. Duncansby Head is also the most northeasterly point of the Scottish mainland.<ref>Streetmap http://www.streetmap.co.uk/map.srf?x=340568&y=973320&z=120&sv=340568,973320&st=4&ar=y&mapp=map.srf&searchp=ids.srf&dn=639&ax=340568&ay=973320&lm=0</ref>\n\nThe straight-line distance from Land's End to John o' Groats is {{convert|603|mi|km}} as determined from O.S. Grid References, but such a route passes over a series of stretches of water in the [[Irish Sea]].  Google Earth reports a distance of 602.70 miles between the two iconic marker points.\n\nAccording to a 1964 road atlas, the shortest route using classified roads was {{convert|847|mi|km}} but in a 2008 road atlas, the shortest route using classified roads was {{convert|838|mi|km}}. An online route planner in 2011 also calculated the quickest route by road as {{convert|838|mi|km}}, estimating a time of 15 hours 48 minutes for the journey (this uses the [[A30 road|A30]], [[M5 motorway|M5]], [[M6 motorway|M6]], [[A74(M) and M74 motorways|A74(M), M74]], [[M73 motorway|M73]], [[M80 motorway|M80]], [[M9 motorway (Scotland)|M9]], [[A9 road (Scotland)|A9]] & [[A99 road|A99]]) but the overall shortest route by road, using minor roads in numerous places and utilising modern bridges, is only about {{convert|814|mi|km}}.  This route is roughly as follows: Land's End, [[Bodmin]], [[Okehampton]], [[Tiverton, Devon|Tiverton]], [[Taunton]], [[Bridgwater]], [[Avonmouth Bridge|the M5 Avon Bridge]], the [[M48 motorway|M48]] [[Severn Bridge]], [[Monmouth]], [[Hereford]], [[Shrewsbury]], [[Tarporley]], [[St Helens, Merseyside|St Helens]], [[Preston, Lancashire|Preston]], [[Carlisle, Cumbria|Carlisle]], [[Beattock]], [[Carstairs, South Lanarkshire|Carstairs]], [[Whitburn, West Lothian|Whitburn]], [[Falkirk]], [[Stirling]], [[Crieff]], [[Kenmore, Perth and Kinross|Kenmore]], Dalchalloch, A9, [[Inverness]], [[Kessock Bridge]], [[Cromarty Bridge]], [[Dornoch Firth Bridge]], [[Latheron]], [[Wick, Highland|Wick]], John o' Groats.\n\n[[Google Maps]], on 2 August 2017, calculated the fastest route by car, from the Land's End Visitor Centre to John o' Groats as being 837 miles and taking 14 hours 40 minutes.  It also showed a walking route of 811 miles, which it suggested would take 268 hours, and involve an elevation gain of 30,148 ft and an elevation fall of 30,272 ft.\n\n== Methods ==\n\nThere are many ways to go from Land's End to John o' Groats. Traditionally considered to be a walk, the route is now traversed in a number of ways, with cycling and multi-modal expeditions being particularly popular in recent years.\n\nMost trips are done by individuals or small groups for personal fulfilment. Some expeditions are organised as charity fundraisers, sometimes involving celebrities: examples include cricketer [[Ian Botham]]'s 1985 walk and athlete [[Jane Tomlinson]] in 2003. In recent history the route has been used as a rite of passage by cyclists taking on the most iconic cycling challenge in Britain.\n\n=== Walking ===\nThe first recorded end-to-end walk (actually from John o' Groats to Land's End) was undertaken by the brothers John and Robert Naylor in 1871.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gutenberg.org/etext/14415 |title=Naylor, J. and R. (1916) '&#39;From John o' Groats to Land's End'&#39; on Project Gutenberg |publisher=Gutenberg.org |date=22 December 2004 |accessdate=29 April 2010}}</ref>  Since then the walk has been undertaken many times, more particularly since 1960, after a well-publicised road walk by [[Barbara Moore (vegetarian)|Dr Barbara Moore]].  In 1960 the entrepreneur [[Billy Butlin]] organised a road walking race, which gave further impetus to the idea.\n\nSince the 1960s, walkers have mostly chosen off-road routes, using the growing network of [[long-distance footpaths in the United Kingdom|long-distance footpaths]].  A classic account is from 1966 by the travel writer [[John Hillaby]].<ref>Hillaby, J. (1966) ''Journey Through Britain'' Republished by Constable in 1995 {{ISBN|978-0-09-474990-0}}</ref> Off-road walkers usually complete the journey in two to three months. There is a considerable choice of off-road routes, but all are much longer than the shortest road distance, usually {{convert|1200|mi|km}} or more.  The walk is still undertaken by road walkers, often doing the walk, like [[Sir Ian Botham]], for charity, or as a \"challenge walk\".  They typically take a month or even less.\n\nSome walkers aim to complete the route piecemeal, perhaps over several years, to achieve the walk within the time constraints of a working life and before the possible health problems of retirement.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Drake|first1=John|title=End to end in bits : a story of a walk from Lands End to John O'Groats|date=2011|publisher=Alewords|location=Leeds|isbn=0951904760|url=https://www.scribd.com/document/163212607/Final-Version-of-End-to-End}}</ref>\n\n==== Routes ====\n\nThere is no continuous long-distance path from Land's End to John o' Groats.  There are long-distance paths for substantial sections of the route, and where they do not exist walkers connect them by [[Rights of way in England and Wales|rights of way]] and minor roads. Most walkers broadly follow these routes:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hockeylejog.co.uk/Links.htm#Otherwebsites |title=Annotated list of walkers routes, with links to websites |publisher=Hockeylejog.co.uk |date= |accessdate=29 April 2010}}</ref>\n*from Land's End to [[Exmoor]] by the [[South West Coast Path]]; or by a shorter inland route through [[Cornwall]] and [[Devon]] by minor roads and paths, the [[Two Castles Trail]] and the towpath of the [[Grand Western Canal]]\n*across [[Somerset]] by parts of the [[Macmillan Way West]], the [[Samaritans Way South West]] or the [[Limestone Link]]\n*to the [[Peak District]] either by\n**an eastern route using the [[Cotswold Way]], the [[Heart of England Way]] (or the [[Severn Way]]), the [[Staffordshire Way]] and the [[Limestone Way]]; or\n**a western route across the [[Severn Bridge]] then by the [[Offa's Dyke Path]], the [[Maelor Way]] and the [[South Cheshire Way]]\n*to the [[Scottish Borders]] by the [[Pennine Way]]\n*by [[St. Cuthbert's Way]] and a section of the [[Southern Upland Way]] to the [[Pentland Hills]], then by\n** a western route using the towpaths of the [[Union Canal (Scotland)|Union Canal]] and the [[Forth and Clyde Canal]], then by the [[West Highland Way]] and the [[Great Glen Way]] to [[Inverness]]; or\n** an eastern route across the [[Forth Road Bridge]] to [[Perth, Scotland|Perth]] and [[Pitlochry]], then by [[Glen Tilt]] and the [[Lairig Ghru]] to [[Strathspey, Scotland|Speyside]] and the old [[Wade road]] to Inverness.\n*from Inverness to John o' Groats, either by\n**the [[John o' Groats Trail]], a mostly coastal long distance route that is rough but walkable; \n**a route that is mostly on roads with a few stretches of coast walking; or \n**some walkers head north west from the end of the West Highland Way at [[Fort William, Scotland|Fort William]] using parts of the [[Cape Wrath Trail]], then head northeast through the [[Flow Country]] of [[Caithness]].  However, this route is through remote country and requires wild camping.\n\n=== Cycling ===\nThe official [[Road Records Association]] record for a rider on a conventional bicycle is 43 hours, 25 minutes and 13 seconds, set by 40 year old [[Michael Broadwith]] on 17 June 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cyclingtimetrials.org.uk/articles/view/349|title=Inside the 2018 End to End record attempt, words by Paul Jones|work=Cyclingtimetrials.org|accessdate=26 June 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe official [[Road Records Association]] Women's record: Lynne Taylor (Lynne Biddulph), 2002, 52 hours, 45 minutes and 11 seconds. <ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|title=Records Place to Place|url=http://www.rra.org.uk/|website=Road Records Association|accessdate=26 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe official [[Road Records Association]] Mixed Tandem Record: A Wilkinson & L E A Taylor (Lynne Biddulph), 2000, 51h 19m 23s.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\nMen's tandem bicycle. 5\u20137 May 2015 Riders: Dominic Irvine and Charlie Mitchell. Time: 1 day 21 hours 11 minutes.<ref>{{cite web|title=Records Place to Place|url=http://www.rra.org.uk/|website=Road Records Association|accessdate=30 June 2015}}</ref> The previous record held for 49 years.\n\nThe record for cycling from Land's End to John o' Groats is held by Andy Wilkinson, who completed the journey in 41 hours, 4 minutes and 22 seconds on a Windcheetah recumbent [[tricycle]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.windcheetah.co.uk/record.htm|title=Windcheetah recumbent tricycle scrapbook|work=windcheetah.co.uk|access-date=5 March 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100918234801/http://www.windcheetah.co.uk/record.htm|archive-date=18 September 2010|url-status=dead}}</ref> A typical cycling time when not attempting shortest time is 10 to 14 days. James MacDonald set a record in September 2017 for cycling from John o' Groats to Land's End and back again in five days, 18 hours and 3 minutes.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.projectkansas.org |title=Fastest return journey from John o' Groats to Land's End by bicycle |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170912132237/https://www.projectkansas.org/ |archive-date=12 September 2017 |url-status=live |website=Project Kansas}} {{As of|2017|10|17}} the success of the attempt had not been confirmed by Guinness. {{cite web|url=http://www.guinnessworldrecords.com/search/applicationrecordsearch?term=return+journey+Land%27s+end+to+John+o%27+Groats+bicycle&contentType=record |title=search for return journey Land's End to John o' Groats bicycle |website=www.guinnessworldrecords.com |access-date=17 October 2017}} {{registration required}}</ref> From 1 to 4 March 2010, [[David Walliams]], [[Jimmy Carr]], [[Fearne Cotton]], [[Miranda Hart]], [[Patrick Kielty]], [[Davina McCall]] and [[Russell Howard]] cycled in a team relay from John o' Groats to Land's End to raise money for [[Sport Relief]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/local/cornwall/hi/people_and_places/newsid_8551000/8551112.stm |title=Sport Relief celebrities reach Land's End |publisher=BBC News|accessdate=5 March 2010 | date=5 March 2010}}</ref>\n\nThe first tricyclist to complete the route was Alfred Nixon, champion of the London Tricycle Club, who in 1882 made \"the first, and at present only, tricycle journey from John o' Groats to Land's End, a distance of 1007 miles, in a fortnight\".<ref>Lincolnshire Chronicle 25 September 1883 p4.</ref> The current [[Road Records Association]] record on a non-recumbent tricycle is two days, 5 hours and 29 minutes ridden by [[Ralph Dadswell]] in 1992. \n\nMen's quadricycle. In the summer of 2012. Riders: Hugo Catchpole, George Unwin, Tom Bethell and Richard Nicholls. Time 10 days 15 hours. On a four-man recumbent bike weighing 114&nbsp;kg.\n\nSeveral cyclists have completed the route on folding bicycles. The fastest reported completion of LEJOG on 16-inch wheel Brompton bicycles is currently that of Si Trickett and Stephen Brindle, between 22-29 April 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://forum.cyclinguk.org/viewtopic.php?t=50504|title=Brompton Lejog - Cycling UK Forum|website=forum.cyclinguk.org}}</ref>\n\nThere have been several [[unicycle]] completions of the journey. The [[Guinness World Record]] for the fastest completion by unicycle is held by Roger Davies and Sam Wakeling, who rode {{convert|862|mi|km}} (Land's End to John o' Groats) from 12 to 18 September 2009 in 6 days, 8 hours and 43 minutes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.guinnessworldrecords.com/records/fastest-journey-from-land-s-end-to-john-o--groats-by-unicycle-(male)|title=Guinness World Records entry for Fastest journey o' Groats by unicycle (male)}}</ref> They rode large {{convert|36|in|mm|adj=mid|-wheeled}} unicycles equipped with two-speed Schlumpf geared hubs.<ref>[http://www.redwelly.co.uk/end2end/wordpress/ Event blog with details of the trip and certificates from LEJOG Association] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101125212929/http://www.redwelly.co.uk/end2end/wordpress/ |date=25 November 2010 }}, Redwelly.co.uk</ref>\n\nThe record for riding from Land's End to John o' Groats on a [[penny-farthing]] had not been broken since 1886, when Victorian cyclist [[George Pilkington Mills]] set it with a time of five days and one hour. Richard Thoday broke the then 133-year old record by completing his ride in four days, eleven hours and fifty-two minutes.( [[Guinness World Record]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.guinnessworldrecords.com/world-records/469573-fastest-journey-from-lands-end-to-john-o-groats-by-penny-farthing-male Guinness World Record|title=Fastest Journey from Land's End to John-O'-Groats by penny farthing (male)|publisher=}}</ref>) He averaged around 200 miles a day. He had undertaken the challenge to help raise \u00a310,000 for the charity [[Children in Need|BBC Children in Need]]. <ref>{{cite web |title=Cyclist Richard Thoday breaks penny farthing record |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-derbyshire-50451465 |website=BBC}}</ref>\n\nThe oldest person to cycle from Land's End to John o' Groats is Tony Rathbone (UK, b. 10 December 1932) who was aged 81 years and 162 days when he completed the journey on 21 May 2014. Roger Anthony \"Tony\" Rathbone started his journey from Land's End to John o' Groats on 7 May 2014 with his friend, William \"Billy\" Skipper. They cycled a total of 1,526.46&nbsp;km (948.5 miles) and were riding for a total of 79 hours 34 minutes. [[Guinness World Record]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.guinnessworldrecords.com/world-records/oldest-person-to-cycle-from-lands-end-to-john-o-groats|title=Oldest person to cycle from Land's End to John-O'-Groats|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017 Amelia Sampson aged 22 months completed John o' Groats to Land's End in 14 days in her trailer towed by her parents riding a tandem.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.touchnote.com/2017/06/23/epic-family-journey/|title=Cycling the country end-to-end: Postcards from an epic family journey  |publisher=[[Touchnote]]|date=23 June 2017|accessdate=11 July 2017}}</ref>\n\nAt the age of 4 years and 4 months, Rhoda Jones is believed to have become the youngest to cycle Land's End \u2013 John o' Groats on 2 September 2018<ref>{{cite web |title='Famous' cyclist, 4, in record ride bid |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-northamptonshire-45399394 |accessdate=15 April 2019 |date=3 September 2018}}</ref>. Cycling on a trailerbike with her parents Katie and Tom Jones<ref>{{cite web |title=Cyclists aged 83 years apart complete Land\u2019s End-John O\u2019 Groats within days of each other |url=https://road.cc/content/news/247861-cyclists-aged-83-years-apart-complete-lands-end-john-ogroats-within-days-each |website=road.cc |accessdate=15 April 2019 |language=en |date=4 September 2018}}</ref> she completed the ride in 22 days, 3 hours, 26 minutes. Her sister Ruth Jones, aged 5, completed the journey before her and became the fastest on a trailerbike.{{cn|date=April 2019}}\n\nOn 3 August 2018, Joshua Moisey, aged 7 years and 2 months, became the youngest Land's End \u2013 John o' Groats cyclist on a standard bicycle, riding his own bike alongside brother Reuben (10) and parents Alvin and Hiroko, and raising money for [[Alzheimer's Society]].<ref name=\"mcinerney\">{{cite news |last1=McInerney |first1=Liam |title=Penge boy, 7, becomes the youngest person to ever cycle the length of Britain |url=https://www.newsshopper.co.uk/news/16415254.penge-boy-7-becomes-the-youngest-person-to-ever-cycle-the-length-of-britain/ |accessdate=7 September 2018 |work=[[News Shopper]] |date=13 August 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | work=Bromley Times | page=6|date=16 August 2018 | url=http://edition.pagesuite-professional.co.uk/html5/reader/production/default.aspx?pubname=&edid=52e0fe25-5fbd-4af0-84d2-a4d552d448f5| access-date=8 September 2018 | title=Cycling family make history on musical ride out| last=Gantzer | first=Olivia}}</ref>\n\nThere are several annual mass participation cycle rides that go from Land's End to John o' Groats, the biggest of which is the Deloitte Ride Across Britain,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rideacrossbritain.com|title=Land's End to John O'Groats \u2013 Deloitte Ride Across Britain|work=Deloitte Ride Across Britain}}</ref> run by Threshold Sports. The Ride Across Britain takes over 800 riders the full length of Britain, taking nine days and covering {{convert|969|mi}}, with each rider covering an average of {{convert|107|mi}} per day. Previous celebrity participants include GB rower and Olympic gold medallist [[James Cracknell]] and former England Rugby captain [[Lewis Moody]].\n\n=== Running ===\nThe record time for a runner to complete the route, as reported by the Land's End John o' Groats Club, is nine days and 2 hours, by Andi Rivett.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.endtoenders.co.uk/transport.php | title=Methods of Transport | author=Land's End and John o' Groats Club | accessdate=25 March 2008 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080518014331/http://www.endtoenders.co.uk/transport.php | archive-date=18 May 2008 | url-status=dead }}</ref> In July 2008, Dan Driver became the first to run the route solo, meaning he carried all his equipment with him whilst he ran it.  He completed the run in just over 17 days.<ref name=\"devon\">{{cite news|title=Dan's the first to run the length of Britain without back-up team|url=http://www.devonlive.com/dan-s-run-length-britain-team/story-11806590-detail/story.html|accessdate=6 June 2017|work=devonlive.com|date=27 July 2008}}{{Dead link|date=February 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nThe current women's record of 12 days, 15 hours and 46 minutes was set by Marina (Mimi) Anderson from 16-28 July 2008<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.guinnessworldrecords.com/world-records/fastest-journey-from-lands-end-to-john-o-groats-on-foot-(female)|title=Fastest journey from Land's End to John-O'-Groats on foot (female)|website=Guinness World Records}}</ref>. In August 2019 the BBC reported that Sharon Gayter had completed the run four hours faster, in 12 days 11 hours 6 minutes, still to be verified by Guinness.<ref>{{cite news|title= Woman, 55, sets John O'Groats to Land's End running record|URL=https://www-bbc-co-uk.cdn.ampproject.org/v/s/www.bbc.co.uk/news/amp/uk-49212792?amp_js_v=a2&amp_gsa=1&usqp=mq331AQEKAFwAQ%3D%3D |work=BBC News|date=2 August 2019|access-date=4 August 2019| last=Agerholm|first=Harriet}}</ref>\n\nFred Hicks was an early record holder. He ran the journey between 20 and 30 May 1977 in 10 days 3 hours and 30 minutes. He ran this for charity, not aiming to set any records, and it was only later, when he was approached by the Road Running association asking if they could pursue the record with Guinness, that he became aware he had set a new record.{{cn|date=October 2017}} \n\nOn 12 July 2009 British [[ultramarathon]] runner Kevin Carr successfully completed the first ever attempt to run the route off-road, becoming the first athlete to run the length of the UK as a fell/trail run. Like Driver, Carr ran unsupported and solo\u2014a format commonly known amongst fell runners as a mountain marathon. Carr ran the challenge as part of an event organised by Benumber1,<ref>http://benumber1.co.uk/lejog.htm{{Dead link|date=February 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> an event that saw several top-level British athletes (mainly Olympians) completing the challenge. The event was designed to encourage school students to participate in sport and to realise the benefits of a healthy lifestyle, whilst raising funds for the [[British Heart Foundation]]. The run covered {{convert|1254|mi|km}} over footpaths, bridleways, canal paths, river banks, national trails, fields, moorland and mountains. Over 80% of the route was off-road, the route resorting to tarmac only when necessary to link two trails, or where a trail passed through a village/town. The run took 6 weeks 3 days and 17 hours (including three rest days). Factoring in the rest days, this run called for an average effort of just under {{convert|30|mi|km|sigfig=1}} a day, every day, for more than six weeks.{{Citation needed|date=June 2017}}\n\nIn July 2011, a team of runners from [[Calday Grange Grammar School]], Wirral completed a relay from Land's End to John o' Groats, becoming the first school to do so.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wirralnews.co.uk/news/local-news/calday-grange-grammer-school-runners-6570939|title=Wirral|work=liverpoolecho}}</ref> They raised \u00a3200,000<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.caldaygrangegrammarschool.co.uk/news/?pid=10&nid=1&storyid=42|title=Calday Grange Grammar School|work=caldaygrangegrammarschool.co.uk}}</ref> for [[Alder Hey Children's Hospital]], Liverpool.\n\nIn mid summer of 2011 Anthony Band from Surrey ran 1000 miles barefoot, all in aid for Help for heroes. Band took 29 days, running on average 36 miles per day.{{Citation needed|date=June 2017}}\n\nOn 3 August 2014, Marie-Claire Oziem became the first female runner to complete the distance unsupported and solo.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.triblogs.com/blog/1000miles/about-me?pid=2907|title=About Me|work=triblogs.com}}</ref> She pushed all her provisions in a pram and camped along the way. Her route consisted of both on and off-road sections. Oziem ran for the charity [[Mind (charity)|Mind]], based in Taunton for its project Go Wild, Stay Well, which aims to support those with mental illness through the use of various green therapy schemes. She started her run on 23 June and finished on 3 August 2014, regularly running distances of over 32 miles daily.{{Better source|reason=Source is an 'about me' page. A disinterested source is necessary.|date=June 2017}}\n\n=== By horse ===\n{{refimprove section|date=June 2017}}\nThe journey with a horse is generally completed north to south, starting in April to avoid the midges in the Highlands but also to benefit from warmer weather.{{cn|date=September 2018}}\n\nEvelyn Burnaby was the younger brother of the famous English Long Rider Colonel [[Frederick Burnaby]]. Whereas the elder brother was famous for having ridden across Central Asia and the Ottoman Empire, Evelyn decided to keep his equestrian adventures closer to home. He set off in 1892 to ride from Land's End, Cornwall to John o' Groats, Scotland. Evelyn's journey was soon serialised in a popular publication, ''[[The Country Gentleman]]'', and was published in book form the following year as ''A Ride from Land's End to John O' Groats''.<ref name=\"burnaby\">{{cite book |last1=Burnaby |first1=Evelyn |title=A Ride from Land's End to John O' Groats |date=1893 |publisher=Sampson Low, Marston & co. |location=London |url=https://archive.org/stream/ridefromlandsen00burngoog#page/n6 |accessdate=11 September 2018}}</ref>\n\nCommunist John Richard Penistan rode his horse, Billy-a-Journey from Land's End to John o' Groats in 1948 (or 1930<ref name=\"penlee-penistan\">{{cite web |title=Lands End To John O Groats On Horseback |url=https://www.penleehouse.org.uk/collections/item/PEZPH:2001.120.1164 |website=Photography |publisher=Penlee House |accessdate=11 September 2018}}</ref>) taking him 56 days. He was the first person to do the journey with just one horse.\n\nArthur Elliott, a veteran of the Great War, rode his horse, Goldflake, from Land's End to John o' Groats in 1955.<ref name=\"elliott-times\">{{cite news |title=Ride from Land's End to John O'Groats |work=The Times |date=26 October 1955 |page=6 |quote=Mr George Elliott, aged 62, of St. Ives, Cornwall, riding his eight-year-old chestnut mare, completed yesterday a journey from Land's End to John o' Groat's.}}</ref>\n\nIn 2006 the mother-and-daughter team of Vyv and Elsie Wood-Gee rode from John o' Groats to Land's End. Elsie was 13 at the time.\n\nFormer army officer Grant Nicolle continued the tradition by travelling from John o' Groats to Land's End in 2007 with Marv (solo and unsupported), taking 11 and a half weeks. Grant has published a book called 'Long Trot' through Amazon, documenting the trip.<ref name=\"nicolle-scotsman\">{{cite news |last1=Nicolle |first1=Grant |title=A journey from John o' Groats to Land\u2019s End on a horse |url=https://www.scotsman.com/news/a-journey-from-john-o-groats-to-land-s-end-on-a-horse-1-3905755 |accessdate=11 September 2018 |work=[[The Scotsman]] |date=2 October 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== Swimming ===\n[[Sean Conway (swimmer)|Sean Conway]] swam the complete route from 30 June 2013 to 11 November 2013 (135 days). On 31 August 2018 this time was bested by British endurance athlete Ross Edgely, who swam the complete route from Land's End to John o' Groats in just 62 days as part of his effort to swim around the entirety of mainland Britain<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.granthamjournal.co.uk/news/grantham-strongman-ross-edgley-reaches-john-ogroats-9007397/|title=Grantham strongman Ross Edgley breaks yet another record|last=Greenwood|first=Darren|date=31 August 2018|website=Grantham Journal|access-date=22 May 2019}}</ref>.\n\n===Stand-up paddleboarding===\nThe first person to [[Standup paddleboarding|stand-up paddleboard]] (SUP) Land's End to John o'Groats was Cal Major, between 4 May 2018 and 2 July 2018, a total of 59 days. Major completely the journey solo and without any boat support.<ref name=\"lo\">{{cite web |last1=Lo |first1=Janice |title=Cal Major completes Land\u2019s End to John o\u2019Groats paddleboarding expedition |url=https://palmequipmenteurope.com/blog/2018/07/02/cal-major-completes-lands-end-to-john-ogroats-paddleboarding-expedition/ |website=Gone Paddling |publisher=Palm Equipment |accessdate=12 January 2019 |date=2 July 2018}}</ref> Her route took her along the Cornish and Devon coast into the [[Bristol Channel]], up the [[River Severn]] and by canals to [[Blackpool]], by sea around [[Cumbria]] and the [[Mull of Galloway]], across the [[Firth of Clyde]] to  [[Isle of Arran|Arran]], along the whole of the [[Caledonian Canal]], and up the coast of north east Scotland.<ref name=\"paddle\">{{cite web |title=2018: Lands End to John O\u2019Groats |url=https://paddleagainstplastic.com/2018-lands-end-to-john-ogroats/ |publisher=Paddle Against Plastic |accessdate=12 January 2019}}</ref>\n\nFiona Quinn became the first person to [[Standup paddleboarding|stand up paddleboard]] (SUP) Land's End to John o'Groats on an inflatable board, between 21 April and 10 July 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://fionalquinn.com/sup-britain|title=SUP Britain|website=Fiona Quinn|language=en-US|access-date=2019-03-06}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://fionalquinn.com/|title=Fiona Quinn|website=Fiona Quinn}}</ref>  Over the 81 day expedition, she spent just 35 of those paddling, waiting out bad weather in between. Her mainly sea-based route took her up the Cornish coast, crossing the [[Bristol Channel]] to [[Lundy Island]] and on to Pembrokeshire before she paddled over to Ireland. Continuing up the east coast of Ireland she cross back over the [[Irish Sea]] to the [[Mull of Kintyre]], through the full length of the [[Caledonian Canal]] and up the north east coast of Scotland. She also became the first woman to SUP across the Irish Sea and the first woman to complete a LEJOG triathlon, having walked and cycled the route in 2017. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sungod.co/explore/stories/1-paddleboard-1-world-record|title=1 Paddleboard & 1 World Record - How one woman escaped the 9-5 {{!}} SunGod Stories|website=www.sungod.co|language=en|access-date=2019-03-06}}</ref>\n\n=== Wheelchair ===\nThe fastest time in a wheelchair was achieved in August 2009 by US Navy Pilot Rick Ryan: eight days, 10 hours and 9 minutes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rideforremembrance.org/Photos.html|title=Photos and Blogs|work=Ride for Remembrance|date=15 August 2009|quote=15 Aug. 2009; We did it! ... A new world record: Land's End to John o' Groats by hand-crank wheelchair in 8 days: 10 hours: 9 minutes: 10 seconds|accessdate=21 September 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160113095551/http://www.rideforremembrance.org/Photos.html|archive-date=13 January 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n=== Skateboard ===\nThe record time to complete the {{convert|980|mi|km|adj=on}} journey on a skateboard is 21 days, achieved by Matt Elver, Charlie Mason and Lee Renshaw, who traveled around {{convert|50|mi|km|sigfig=1}} per day to raise money for charity.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/local/cornwall/hi/people_and_places/newsid_8841000/8841915.stm|title=BBC \u2013 Skateboarding the UK|date=21 July 2010|work=[[BBC Online]]|accessdate=16 November 2011}}</ref>\n\n=== Triathlon ===\nSean Conway became the first person to complete a length of Britain triathlon in 2013. He traveled between Lands End and John o'Groats three times,  cycling, running and swimming the route.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.seanconway.com/successes.html|title=Successes|website=SEAN CONWAY|language=en|access-date=2019-03-06}}</ref> Fiona Quinn became the first woman to complete a length of Britain triathlon in 2018. She traveled between Lands End and John o'Groats three times, cycling, walking and stand up paddleboarding the route.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://fionalquinn.com/adventures|title=Past adventures|website=Fiona Quinn|language=en-US|access-date=2019-03-06}}</ref> \n\n=== Motoring ===\n[[File:Anthony Frederick Wilding on a motorcycle.jpg|thumb|[[Tony Wilding]] at Land's End off to John o' Groats]]\nMotoring events between the two extremities have been held since the first decade of the 20th century, when the [[Auto-Cycle Union]] organised a series of runs for motorcycles.  In 1911, Ivan B. Hart-Davies became the holder of the final Land's End to John o' Groats record for solo motorcycles. Riding his 3.5&nbsp;hp single-speed Triumph, he covered the {{convert|886|mi|km}} in 29 hours, 12 minutes. As his average speed exceeded the then-maximum of 20&nbsp;mph, further official record attempts were banned by the A. C. U.\n\nThe [[Motor Cycling Club]] (which had been running the London to Land's End Trial since 1908, still held today, at least in name) put on an annual Land's End to John o' Groats Run from 1923 to 1928 which included cars as well as motorcycles.  These events were also known as the End to End. In 2006, [[BBC Television]] ran a series of three programmes called ''[[The Lost World of Friese-Greene]]'' covering [[Claude Friese-Greene]]'s 1920s-era road trip from Land's End to John o' Groats.  The trip had originally been filmed using the Biocolour process, developed by Claude's father [[William Friese-Greene]] and the film had degraded. The original print of Claude's film was subjected to computer enhancement by the [[British Film Institute]] to remove the flickering problem inherent in the Biocolour process.\n\nIn September 1983 rally and trials driver Dennis Greenslade from Cornwall created a new sole driver non-stop record drive from Land's End to John O'Groats and return using the newly released Audi 80 Quattro. The time taken was 24hours 32 minutes. Following this record achievement which also raised \u00a310,000 for three charities he established The Land's End - John O'Groats Association formed to authenticate all journeys between these two iconic landmarks.\n\nIn 1984, Neal Champion covered {{convert|884|mi|km}} from John o' Groats to Land's End in 11 hours, 14 minutes, on a [[Kawasaki motorcycles|Kawasaki]] GPZ750 Turbo.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.champ.org.uk/bikes/endtoend.htm|title=End to End Run|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=|access-date=}}</ref>\nIn 1984, Christian Conzendorf-Mattner accompanied by Dennis Greenslade covered the route from Land's End to John O'Groats\u2014there and back non-stop other than for fuel\u2014in 31 hours 22 mins in a 1941 BMW 327/80.\nThe record run was monitored by a team of journalists from a motoring magazine and is the current record for prewar classic cars end to end, non-stop, two drivers. The Land's End - John O'Groats Association awards this trophy to new record holders.\n\nOn 17 September 1988, Andrew Frankel and Mark Connaughton drove from Land's End to John o' Groats in a standard production Alfa Romeo 164 in 12 hours 30 minutes, including stops for refuelling.\n\nIn 1993, John Brown initiated the Land's End to John o' Groats Historic Reliability Trial, a race for vintage road vehicles.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hero.org.uk/artman2/publish/info/Who_s_who_at_HERO.shtml|title=Who's Who at HERO: John Brown|date=27 December 2006|work=HERO: Historic Endurance Rallying Organisation|accessdate=27 May 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080411223357/http://www.hero.org.uk/artman2/publish/info/Who_s_who_at_HERO.shtml|archive-date=11 April 2008|url-status=dead}}</ref>  The race is held each December and is a tough, three-day rally for old and classic cars, built between the 1920s and 1970s.  The route takes a long {{convert|1400|mi|km|adj=on}} route, using remote upland roads of the west of England, Wales (during the night), the Pennines and Scotland.  Medals are awarded in gold, silver and bronze categories.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hero.org.uk/artman2/publish/techinfo/index.shtml|title=Historic Endurance Rallying Organisation Regulations & Eligibility|work=HERO: Historic Endurance Rallying Organisation|accessdate=16 December 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100101193846/http://www.hero.org.uk/artman2/publish/techinfo/index.shtml|archive-date=1 January 2010|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nOn 15\u201316 April 1997, Hugh Edeleanu drove the route in a [[J. C. Bamford|JCB]] excavator in a time of 22 hours, 10 minutes and 30 seconds.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/yesterday-was-a-1261628.html|title=yesterday was a ...|publisher=The Independent|date=17 May 1997}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2001, Wayne Booth became the first person to do the journey by motorcycle without stopping; the 37-year-old completed the historic trip in 14 hours and 52 minutes, averaging 57&nbsp;mph, on a modified 1,000cc Honda Varedero, complete with additional 74-litre petrol tank. The meticulously researched route of {{convert|854|mi|km}} passed through just two sets of traffic lights and was completed within all highway regulations, law and speed limits.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.endtoenders.co.uk/history_record_breakers.php|title=End to Enders \u2013 The End To End Challenge|work=endtoenders.co.uk|access-date=28 July 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140803082709/http://www.endtoenders.co.uk/history_record_breakers.php|archive-date=3 August 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/UK+top+to+bottom+non+stop.-a077042421|title=UK top to bottom non-stop.|work=thefreelibrary.com}}</ref> Booth and the dozen strong support team raised over \u00a31,000 for The [[National Childbirth Trust]] and [[Macmillan Cancer Support|Macmillan Cancer Relief]].\n\nOn 22 May 2011, Kevin Sharpe and David Peilow completed the first end-to-end run from John o' Groats to Land's End in an electric car over two days, using only [[charging station]]s available to the general public, in a [[Tesla Roadster (2008)|Tesla Roadster]] sports car.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thegreencarwebsite.co.uk/blog/index.php/2011/05/23/tesla-travels-from-lands-end-to-john-ogroats/|title=TheGreenCarWebsite.co.uk|work=thegreencarwebsite.co.uk|access-date=23 May 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120315131620/http://www.thegreencarwebsite.co.uk/blog/index.php/2011/05/23/tesla-travels-from-lands-end-to-john-ogroats/|archive-date=15 March 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n[[File:Nissan Leaf at lands End.jpeg|alt=Nissan Leaf at lands End|thumb|Jonathan Porterfield and Chris Ramsey at Land's End in a Nissan leaf]]\n\nOn 7 August 2011, Darren Whitehead & Tony Dwight travelled {{convert|1071|mi|km}} from John o' Groats to Land's End (including crossing the Welsh border) in 5 days using two ride-on [[Wheel Horse]] lawn mowers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nwlmra.org/pages/the-lawn-way-round.html|title=North West Lawn Mower Racing Association \u2013 The Lawn Way Round|last=|first=|date=|access-date=|work=nwlmra.org|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170607073803/http://nwlmra.org/pages/the-lawn-way-round.html|archive-date=7 June 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref> They also raised money for charity during the trip which was named The Lawn Way Down.\n\nOn 30 November 2013, Lucy Grogan, travelling on a BMW GS R1200 motorbike, and her father Martin Grogan, travelling in a Mini Cooper Works, travelled from Land's End to John o' Groats in 19 hours, leaving Land's End at 4:30am and arriving at John o' Groats at 11:30pm same day. This was in aid of Safe Haven Children's Trust and raised \u00a33,000 for the non-governmental organisation.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/the2550milechallenge|title=Facebook|work=facebook.com}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2015, Jonathan Porterfield and Chris Ramsey beat the record in a [[Nissan Leaf]] electric car, using the existing public rapid charger infrastructure to travel there and back. The route south took 28 hours and 38 minutes, and the return trip 27 hours and 46 minutes.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://driveev.net/2016/04/01/plugging-in-for-another-adventure/|title=Plugging in for another adventure|first=Stephen|last=Brown|date=1 April 2016|publisher=}}</ref> They submitted an application to Guinness World Records to have the quicker time recognised as a record.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-highlands-islands-34345863|title=Electric car trip from Land's End to John O'Groats 'a record'|work=BBC News}}</ref>\n[[File:Dr Jeff Allan and Ben Cottam-Allan at John o'Groats.jpg|alt= Dr Jeff Allan and his son Ben Cottam-Allan having completed their journey from Lands End to John o' Groats set off for the return journey in their Tesla electric car.|thumb|Dr Jeff Allan and his son Ben Cottam-Allan having completed their journey from Land's End to John o' Groats set off for the return journey.]]\n\nOn 7 October 2015, Jeff Allan and his son, Ben Cottam-Allan, beat the electric car record in a [[Tesla Model S]] completing the northbound route in 19 hours 45 minutes and the southbound route in 18 hours 53 minutes. Jeff prepared the route by cycling in May 2015. They hold the Guinness World Record for shortest charging time from John o' Groats to Land's End of 3 hours  44 minutes 33 seconds.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.autovolt-magazine.com/father-and-son-set-new-guinness-world-record-in-electric-car/|title=Father and Son Set New Guinness World Record in Electric Car|date=17 October 2016|newspaper=AutoVolt Magazine|language=en-US|access-date=30 January 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.theargus.co.uk/news/14682326.Record_breaking_electric_car_and_Europe__39_s_first_dragster_to_appear_at_Brighton_Speed_Trials/|title=Record-breaking electric car and Europe's first dragster to appear at Brighton Speed Trials|website=The Argus|language=en|access-date=30 January 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tesla.com/en_GB/customer-stories/lands-end-john-o-groats|title=Lands End to John O\u2019Groats|website=www.tesla.com|language=en-GB|access-date=30 January 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn 21 August 2017, John Chivers completed the first journey by electric motorcycle (a [[Zero Motorcycles|Zero]] DSR) from Land's End to John o' Groats, then continued his journey to [[Orkney]] and finally to [[Skaw,_Unst|Skaw]], on the island of [[Unst]], [[Shetland]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.johnchivers.com/lejogskaw/|title=Land's End to John o'Groats to Skaw by Electric Motorcycle|website=www.johnchivers.com}}</ref> The journey from Land's End to John o' Groats took him four days to complete, breaking the journey up into ten parts, each stop requiring a charge of at least three hours.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.shetnews.co.uk/newsbites/15101-fundraiser-completes-first-lands-end-to-unst-trip-on-electric-motorbike|title=Fundraiser from Land\u2019s End to Unst on electric motorbike|work=[[The Shetland News]]|accessdate=1 September 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn 30 July 2017 Andy Maxfield from [[Inskip, Lancashire|Inskip]] near Preston completed the journey from John O'Groats to Land's End on an unmodified [[List of John Deere tractors|John Deere X750]] ride on [[lawn tractor]]. The 874 mile journey was completed in a Guinness World Record time<ref name=\"breen\">{{cite news |last1=Breen |first1=Jim |title=Epic lawn tractor journey is officially a world record |url=https://www.agriland.co.uk/farming-news/epic-lawn-tractor-journey-is-officially-a-world-record/ |accessdate=9 August 2018 |work=AgriLand |date=8 August 2018}}</ref> of 5 days 8 hours 36 mins with an average speed of around 9mph. <ref>https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/av/uk-england-lancashire-45127295/lawnmower-man-andy-maxfield-breaks-uk-speed-record</ref> This journey was inspired by his father James Maxfield who suffered from [[Alzheimer's]] for 13 years with the challenge raising around \u00a310,000 for The [[Alzheimer's Society]]. The journey was completed with a support team from John Deere and his two daughters Kathryn and Kaitlyn Maxfield.<ref name=\"lancspost\">{{cite news |title=Andy\u2019s 400-mile trip \u2013 on a lawnmower |url=https://www.lep.co.uk/your-lancashire/preston/andy-s-400-mile-trip-on-a-lawnmower-1-8675651 |accessdate=30 July 2018 |work=Lancashire Post |date=28 July 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"johndeere\">{{cite web |title=Going the Distance: A Man, a Mower, and a Mission from the Heart |url=https://johndeerejournal.com/2017/09/going-the-distance-a-man-a-mower-and-a-mission-from-the-heart/ |website=John Deere Journal |publisher=John Deere |accessdate=30 July 2018 |date=11 September 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2017, Tommy Davies and Tom Harvey completed the 841 mile journey in 9 hours and 36 minutes, the fastest time ever recorded between the two points on land, with an overall average of 86.7 mph. They used a specially adapted Audi S5 with an additional fuel tank and an array of equipment to avoid detection from the police and speed cameras. The trip was allegedly tracked via a GPS tracker and filmed, although the footage and data has not been publicly released, presumably in an effort to avoid possible prosecution due to the excessive speed involved.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2018/05/28/record-breaking-driver-drove-length-britain-nine-hours-should/|title=Record-breaking driver who drove length of Britain in nine hours 'should be prosecuted for speeding'|last=Ellson|first=Andrew|date=29 May 2018|work=The Times|access-date=12 August 2018|language=en|issn=0140-0460}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.gizmodo.co.uk/2018/05/man-averages-90mph-in-illegal-but-impressive-country-race-run/|title=Man Averages 90mph in Illegal-But-Impressive Country Race Run|website=Gizmodo UK|language=en|access-date=12 August 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2018 the first hydrogen powered fuel cell electric vehicle, a [[Toyota Mirai]] completed the journey. <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.autocar.co.uk/car-news/features/john-o%E2%80%99groats-land%E2%80%99s-end-hydrogen-fuel-cell-car</ref> Driven by Richard Bremner and Luc Lacey from [[Autocar magazine]] and Jon Hunt from [[Toyota]] they started the journery from Kirkwall in the Orkney's. To reach the hydrogen refuelling infrastructure at the time they travelled via Aberdeen, Sunderland, <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/business/business-news/sunderland-firm-haskel-helps-toyota-14799017</ref>Rotherham and Beaconsfield covering 1,109 miles (1785 Km) at an average speed of 56 miles an hour.  The journey took 19 hours 40 minutes with hydrogen consumption of 0.9kg per 100Km (16.1 kg of hydrogen consumed). <ref>{{cite web|url=https://blog.toyota.co.uk/mirai-marathon-maps-uk-hydrogen-fuel-future</ref> \n [[File:Toyota Mirai John O'Groats.jpg|thumb|Richard Bremner with the Toyota Mirai the first JOG to LE Hydrogen Fuel Cell Car at  John O'Groats]]\n[[File:Toyota Mirai Lands End.jpg|thumb|Jon Hunt with the Toyota Mirai the first JOG to LE Hydrogen Fuel Cell Car at Land's End]]\n\n=== Public transport ===\nThe current fastest journey by bus and coach was set by John and Kirsty Boyd from Runcorn, Cheshire, who travelled from Land's End to John O' Groats in August 2017 using 20 buses/coaches, in three days, 2 hours and 47 minutes.<ref>{{cite web|url=\nhttps://m.facebook.com/story.php?story_fbid=403249583464974&id=330226477433952| title=Completion certificates issued by the Lands End \u2013 John o'Groats Association | date=27 January 2018 | accessdate=28 January 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe current fastest journey by local bus (defined as in section 3 of the Transport Act 1980 to be a stage carriage service with stops within 30 miles)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.legislation.gov.uk/ukpga/1980/34/pdfs/ukpga_19800034_en.pdf|title=Transport Act 1980|website=Legislation Gov Uk|access-date=22 May 2019}}</ref>  was set by Clive Burgess in September 2016. He travelled from Lands End to John O'Groats using 31 buses, in 3 days, 8 hours and 55 minutes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.retro-speed.co.uk/showfeature.asp?art=20605|title=\u2018Le Jog\u2019 \u2013 a magnet to the competitive spirit|access-date=22 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2014, to celebrate completing his GCSE exams, 16-year-old Adam Mugliston travelled from Land's End to John o' Groats on 36 buses in four days, 10 hours and 44 minutes.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/howaboutthat/10947507/Its-a-record-four-days-by-bus-from-Lands-End-to-John-OGroats.html|title=It's a record: four days by bus from Land's End to John O'Groats|date=4 July 2014|work=Telegraph.co.uk}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2011, James Aukett travelled from Land's End to John o' Groats on 31 buses in five days, 7 hours and 25 minutes. James undertook the trip to raise money for children's charity, [[The Children's Society]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lejogbuscountry.org.uk|title=Lejog Bus Country \u2013 Home|work=lejogbuscountry.org.uk|access-date=22 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130422212129/http://lejogbuscountry.org.uk/|archive-date=22 April 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Lands-end-richard-elloway-bus-trip.jpg|thumb|right|Richard Elloway, having completed the return trip using a senior bus-pass \"without paying a penny\".]]\nIn 2008, Richard Elloway of Somerset claims to be the first person to complete the journey from Land's End to John o' Groats and back free of charge by local buses, using the [[English National Concessionary Travel Scheme|English National Concessionary Pass]] (a [[free travel pass|free bus pass]] for people over 60, allowing free off-peak travel on local bus services throughout England) introduced on 1 April 2008, and the pre-existing equivalent concession for pensioners in Scotland. He completed the first leg of the trip in one week and six hours.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/scotland/highlands_and_islands/7340441.stm | title= 'Ultimate holiday' on a bus pass | author= BBC News | date=4 October 2008 | accessdate=10 April 2008}}</ref> The entire journey was completed in two weeks, 8 hours and 30 minutes.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.countygazette.co.uk/display.var.2201842.0.a_pensioners_twoweek_bus_journey.php | title= A pensioner's two-week bus journey | author= Rebecca Hehir (Somerset County Gazette) | date=16 April 2008 | accessdate=16 April 2008}}</ref>\n\nIn 1954, Gertrude Leather travelled by 17 local buses from Land's End to London, at a cost of \u00a31 19s 6d (\u00a31.97\u00bd), and the following year travelled from London to John o' Groats by 25 local buses at a cost of \u00a34 5s 9\u00bdd (\u00a34.29).<ref>Leather, G. and Parke, J (1986) ''Home with the Heather'' Ian Allan {{ISBN|0-7110-1550-3}}</ref>\n\nThe winter timetables offer a fastest route on land public transport of exactly 24 hours, departing Land's End car park  at 13:34 on day 1 and arriving at John O'Groats ferry terminal car park at 13:34 on day 2. This involves a First Kernow route A1 bus to Penzance, trains to Penzance, Tamworth and Crewe to meet the London\u2013Inverness sleeper train, then the following morning Stagecoach buses X98 and 77 via Wick to John O'Groats. On a Friday schooldays route 77 doesn't operate and instead there's a 177 which arrives John O'Groats nine minutes earlier at 1325 making it possible to do the overall trip in 23 hours 51 minutes. However, in the summer buses depart Lands End at 40 minutes past each hour (instead of 34 minutes every two hours) with an extended journey time to allow for traffic congestion making too tight a connection to the train in Penzance to be sure of completing the journey. <ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.transportdirect.info/TransportDirect/en/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=14 April 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080123154145/http://www.transportdirect.info/TransportDirect/en/ |archive-date=23 January 2008 |url-status=dead }} Sample journeys checked 16 June 2019</ref>\n\n===Hitchhiking===\nM. Clark and G. Beynon are the last hitchhikers recorded in the ''Guinness Book of Records'' for the Land's End to John o' Groats trip (17 hours 8 minutes).\n\n===Paramotor (motorised paraglider)===\nThe first recorded journey by [[paramotor]] was by Andy Phillips, supported by a team of British Royal Marines in September 2000. The trip took a little over six days and was completed from south to north.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.flight.firstnet.co.uk/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=9 May 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20121223220121/http://www.flight.firstnet.co.uk/ |archivedate=23 December 2012  }}</ref>\n\nThe first recorded trip from north to south was by John Caston, Brian Pushman, Alex Heron and Henry Glasse in September 2009 and took five days.\n\nIn July 2016 a group of four pilots completed the trip from north to south in 6.5 days. This included double amputee Cayle Royce, who became the first person to fly the route in a ParaTrike.\n\n=== Golf ===\nIn 2005 Surrey-based golfer and member of the Kent Golf Society David Sullivan walked from John o' Groats to Land's End hitting golf balls all the way. He travelled the {{convert|1100|mi|km}} in seven weeks to be eligible for the Guinness Book of Records as the longest golf hole. He raised money for the [[Variety Club]], the [[2004 Indian Ocean earthquake and tsunami]] Appeal, and the [[Orpheus Centre]], a residential arts and learning facility for the young and disabled in Surrey.\n\n=== Aeroplane ===\nThe fastest passage between the two points was made in 1988 by a [[McDonnell Douglas Phantom in UK service|McDonnell Douglas F-4K Phantom]] in a time of 46 minutes 44 seconds <ref>{{cite web|url=http://johneckersley.wordpress.com/tales/route-designer/|title=The Route Designer\u2019s Tale \u2013 Books by John and Nancy Eckersley|work=Books by John and Nancy Eckersley}}</ref>\n\n===In a straight line===\nOn 17 May 2014 a team of four set off to complete [[Beeline Britain]] \u2013 a journey from Land's End to John o' Groats in a straight line.  This never before attempted route was completed in 28 days and required the two biggest sea kayak crossings ever completed in UK waters.\n\n*The first crossing went direct from Land's End to Pembrokeshire \u2013 a distance of over 200&nbsp;km which took 34.5 hours to complete.\n*The second crossing went direct from Pembrokeshire to Anglesey \u2013 around 170&nbsp;km and taking 24.5 hours to complete.\n\nThe team then kayaked, biked and hiked the remainder of the route which went via:\nIsle of Man \u2013 Dalmellington \u2013 Glasgow \u2013 Crieff \u2013 traversing [[Ben Macdui]] the second highest mountain in the UK \u2013 Lossiemouth \u2013 across the Moray Firth \u2013 Lybster \u2013 John o' Groats.\n\nThe project was devised and managed by Ian O'Grady.  He recruited the Team GB Paralympian [[Nick Beighton]], Adam Harmer, a professional kayak coach and University Lecturer, [[Tori James]] who was the first Welsh woman to stand on the summit of [[Mount Everest]].  Beeline Britain's aim was to raise funds and awareness for [[Blesma, The Limbless Veterans|Blesma]], the limbless veterans charity.  The project gained full royal endorsement from the Royal Foundation of the [[Duke of Cambridge|Duke]] and [[Catherine, Duchess of Cambridge|Duchess]] of Cambridge and [[Prince Harry]], and has to date raised over \u00a320,000 for Blesma.\n\nThe whole journey was captured by filmmaker Ian Burton for the feature documentary ''As The Crow Flies'' <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reelhouse.org/imageimpossible/as-the-crow-flies|title=As The Crow Flies|work=reelhouse.org|access-date=28 January 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170704230411/https://www.reelhouse.org/imageimpossible/as-the-crow-flies|archive-date=4 July 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n== Youngest and oldest ==\n\nThe Land's End\u2013John o' Groats Association presents the Jack Adams/Richard Elloway Trophy annually to the youngest person to have completed the journey other than as a passenger in a motor vehicle. Henry Cole completed the journey in June 2006, at the age of four; he cycled over 31 days. He started school in the following September, and was presented with the Jack Adams/Richard Elloway Trophy in January 2007. Sophie George is currently the youngest recipient of the Jack Adams/Richard Elloway Trophy. She completed the journey by bus and train in August 2016 at the age of two years and 10 months and was awarded the trophy in January 2017.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.sloughobserver.co.uk/news/15096260.Three_year_old_girl_lands_prize_for_travelling_length_of_UK|title=Three-year-old lands prize as youngest to travel from Lands End to John O'Groats|publisher=Slough Observer|date=11 April 2008}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017 Amelia Sampson aged 22 months completed John o' Groats to Land's End in 14 days in her trailer towed by her parents riding a tandem.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.touchnote.com/2017/06/23/epic-family-journey/|title=Cycling the country end-to-end: Postcards from an epic family journey  |publisher=[[Touchnote]]|date=23 June 2017|accessdate=11 July 2017}}</ref>\n\nReg Savill is the oldest person to complete the journey on foot (although in the reverse direction from John o' Groats to Land's End), at the age of 74.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/cornwall/content/articles/2008/04/11/people_busholiday_feature.shtml|title=On the Buses|publisher=BBC|date=16 February 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Organisations ==\n\nThere are three organisations supporting people undertaking the journey.\n* The '''Land's End\u2013John o' Groats Association''' is a non-commercial organisation established in 1983 for \"those who have completed the epic journey from Land\u2019s End to John o' Groats, or vice versa, by any means in a single trip\".<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.lejog.org/ | title=The Land's End \u2013 John o' Groats Association | accessdate=28 January 2018}}</ref>\n* The '''Land's End John o' Groats Club''', which is sponsored by the company that operates facilities at Land's End and John o' Groats, the end points.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.endtoenders.co.uk/ | title=The Land's End John o' Groats Club | accessdate=25 March 2008 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080513045100/http://www.endtoenders.co.uk/ | archive-date=13 May 2008 | url-status=dead }}</ref> It holds an annual awards ceremony to select the most notable 'end-to-enders' each year.\n* '''Bike the UK for MS''' is a charity raising awareness for [[multiple sclerosis]] research and patients by running supported cycling trips including from Land's End to John o' Groats. They combine \"an important cause with an incredible experience to help fund treatment and research for a cure whilst addressing the challenges for those affected by MS\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.biketheukforms.org|title=Bike the UK for MS {{!}} Welcome!|website=www.biketheukforms.org|language=en-US|access-date=11 February 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Scottish equivalent ==\n\nUntil [[Acts of Union 1707|Union with England]] in 1707, [[Scotland]]'s equivalent of the phrase was often \"John o' Groats to Maidenkirk\", as [[Maidenkirk]] (Kirkmaiden) was traditionally considered Scotland's southernmost point, a {{convert|388|mi|km|adj=on}} trip. This can be found in [[Robert Burns]]' poem ''On [[Francis Grose|Captain Grose]]'s Peregrinations thro' Scotland''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.robertburns.org/works/275.shtml|title=Robert Burns Country: On The Late Captain Grose's Peregrinations Thro' Scotland: Collecting The Antiquities Of That Kingdom|website=www.robertburns.org}}</ref> and the song, ''The Lady of Kenmure'':\n\n:From John o' Groats to Maidenkirk\n:You'll never find a truer\n:For loyal faith and dauntless deeds,\n:Than the Lady of Kenmure.\n\nThe southernmost village in Scotland is actually nearby [[Drummore]].<ref>''Drummore \u2013 most southerly village'', Visit South West Scotland, https://www.visitsouthwestscotland.com/towns/drummore/</ref>\n\n==English equivalent==\n\nThe length of the [[England|English mainland]] is delineated by the distance between [[Land's End]] and [[Marshall Meadows Bay]] in [[Northumberland]]. The distance is {{convert|556|mi|km}} by road or {{convert|426|mi|km}} [[as the crow flies]]. The traversal of the length of England is sometimes used to define charity events such as walks and cycle-rides.\n\n== See also ==\n*[[Malin to Mizen]]\n*[[Du battant des lames au sommet des montagnes]]\n\n*[[Israel National Trail]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n'''Road walking'''\n* Smailes, B. (2004) ''John o' Groats to Land's End: the Official Challenge Guide'' Challenge Publications {{ISBN|978-1-903568-18-7}}\n\n'''Offroad walking'''\n* Robinson, A. (2007) ''The End to End Trail: Land's End to John o' Groats on Foot'' Cicerone {{ISBN|978-1-85284-512-4}}\n* McCloy, A. (2001) ''The Land's End to John o' Groats Walk'' Cordee {{ISBN|1-871890-59-4}}\n* Salter, M. (2006) ''Land's End to John o' Groats \u2013 a Thousand Mile Walking Route'' Folly Publications {{ISBN|978-1-871731-71-2}}\n\n'''Cycling'''\n* Mitchell, N (2012) End to End Cycle Route: Land's End to John o' Groats (Cicerone Press) {{ISBN|978-1-85284-670-1}}\n* Smailes Brian (2009) ''Land's End to John o' Groats Cycle Guide \u2013 The Official Challenge Guide'' Challenge Publications {{ISBN|978-1-903568-59-0}}\n* Brown, Simon (1995) ''Land's End to John o' Groats Cycle Guide'', Cicerone {{ISBN|978-1-85284-188-1}}\n* Salter, P. (2002) ''Bike Britain: Cycling from Land's End to John o' Groats'' Epic New Zealand {{ISBN|978-0-9582256-1-8}}\n* Lewis, D. (2005) \"[https://www.amazon.co.uk/gp/product/B0154XW9SS/ Land's End to John o' Groats\", On a beer mat] Publish and Print\n\n== External links ==\n*[http://www.ukendtoend.com/ Comprehensive Free Journal \"Walking the length of Britain\" Includes detailed preparation tools.]\n*[http://www.longwalks.org.uk/bibliographytop.html A bibliography of LEJOG/JOGLE published reports and guidebooks, and links to relevant websites]\n*[http://www.ldwa.org.uk/ldp/members/show_path.php?path_name=Land%27s+End+to+John+O%27Groats Land's End to John o' Groats on the Long Distance Walkers' Association website]\n*[http://www.beelinebritain.com Land's End to John o' Groats in a straight line \u2013 one of the last Great British adventures.]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Land's End To John O' Groats}}\n[[Category:Geography of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Long-distance footpaths in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Scenic routes in the United Kingdom]]\n", "name_user": "DannyS712", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fixing the location of periods / full stops", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Land%27s_End_to_John_o%27_Groats"}
{"title_page": "Hammer and sickle", "text_new": "{{Other uses}}\n{{short description|Communist symbol}}\n{{More citations needed|date=July 2019}}\n{{use dmy dates|date=October 2015}}\n[[File:Hammer and sickle red on transparent.svg|thumb|150px|A red hammer and sickle]] \nThe '''hammer and sickle''' ([[Unicode]]: \"soviet symbol\"){{efn|{{lang-ru|\u0441\u0435\u0440\u043f \u0438 \u043c\u043e\u0301\u043b\u043e\u0442|lit=sickle and hammer|translit=serp i m\u00f3lot}}<br>{{lang-zh|\u9524\u5b50\u548c\u9570\u5200}}, ''Chu\u00edzi h\u00e9 li\u00e1nd\u0101o''}} is a symbol meant to represent proletarian solidarity \u2013 a union between the peasantry and working-class. It was first adapted during the [[Russian Revolution]], the hammer representing the workers and the [[sickle]] representing the [[peasants]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.britannica.com/topic/flag-of-Union-of-Soviet-Socialist-Republics|title=Flag of Union of Soviet Socialist Republics|last=|first=|date=|website=[[Encyclopedia Britannica]]|language=en|access-date=2019-11-30}}</ref>\n\nAfter [[World War I]] (from which [[Russian Empire|Russia]] withdrew in the year 1917) and the [[Russian Civil War]], the hammer and sickle became more widely used as a symbol for labor within the [[Soviet Union]] and for [[Proletarian internationalism|international proletarian unity]]. It was taken up by many [[History of communism|communist movements]] around the world, some with local variations. Today, even after the [[dissolution of the Soviet Union]], the hammer and sickle remains commonplace in [[Russia]] and other [[Post-Soviet states|former union republics]], but its display is [[Decommunization|prohibited]] in some other former [[communist countries]] as well as in countries where [[communism]] is [[Bans on Communist symbols|banned]] by law. The hammer and sickle also remains commonplace in countries like [[Vietnam]] and [[China]] which are still officially communist states.\n\n== History ==\n[[File:Peso_Chileno_1933.jpg|thumb|400px|The [[chilean peso]] used the hammer and sickle symbol between 1895 and 1940]]\n\n=== Worker symbolism ===\nFarm and worker instruments and tools have long been used as symbols for [[Proletariat|proletarian]] struggle.\n\nThe combination of hammer and sickle symbolised the combination of farmers and construction workers. One example of use prior to its political instrumentalisation by the Soviet Union is found in [[Chilean peso|Chilean currency]] circulating since 1895.<ref>{{cite web|title=Chilean peso design, 1894|url=http://www.moneta-coins.com/photopost/showphoto.php?photo=598&title=chile-1894-pattern|accessdate=7 May 2018}}</ref>\n\nAn alternative example is the combination of a hammer and a [[plough]], with the same meaning (unity of peasants and workers). In Ireland, the symbol of the plough remains in use. The [[Starry Plough (flag)|Starry Plough]] banner was originally used by the [[Irish Citizen Army]], a socialist republican workers' militia. [[James Connolly]], co-founder of the Irish Citizen Army with [[Jack White (trade unionist)|Jack White]], said the significance of the banner was that a free Ireland would control its own destiny from the plough to the stars. A sword is forged into the plough to symbolise the end of war with the establishment of a Socialist International. This was unveiled in 1914 and flown by the Irish Citizen Army during the 1916 [[Easter Rising]].\n\n[[File:Starry Plough flag (1914).svg|thumb|150px|The [[Starry Plough (flag)|Plough flag]] from 1914 and flown during the [[Easter Rising]]]]\n\n=== Inception ===\nIn 1917, [[Vladimir Lenin]] and [[Anatoly Lunacharsky]] held a competition to create a Soviet emblem. The winning design was a hammer and sickle on top of a globe in rays of the sun, surrounded by a wreath of grain and under a five-pointed star, with the inscription \"[[Workers of the world, unite!|proletariats of the world, unite!]]\" in six languages ([[Russian language|Russian]], [[Ukrainian language|Ukrainian]], [[Belarusian language|Belarusian]], [[Georgian language|Georgian]], [[Armenian language|Armenian]] and [[Azerbaijani language|Azerbaijani]]). It originally featured a sword, but Lenin strongly objected, disliking the violent connotations.<ref name=\"HS Role and Symbolism\">{{cite web|title=The Hammer and Sickle: The Role of Symbolism and Rituals in the Russian Revolution|url=https://www.westminstercollege.edu/myriad/?parent=2514&detail=4475&content=4797|accessdate=3 August 2014}}</ref> The winning designer was [[Yevgeny Ivanovich Kamzolkin]] (1885\u20131957).<ref>[http://1965tribunal.org/the-spectre-of-hammer-and-sickle/ International People's Tribunal 1965, \"The Spectre of Hammer and Sickle\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150914194725/http://1965tribunal.org/the-spectre-of-hammer-and-sickle/ |date=14 September 2015 }}. {{retrieved|accessdate=6 November 2015}}</ref><ref>[http://www.picture-russia.com/en/painter/582 International Gallery of Contemporary Artists] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160816163416/http://www.picture-russia.com/en/painter/582|date=16 August 2016}}. {{retrieved|accessdate=6 November 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn 6 July 1923, the 2nd session of the [[Central Executive Committee of the Soviet Union|Central Executive Committee]] (CIK) adopted this emblem.<ref name=\"HS Role and Symbolism\"/>\n\n=== Usage in the Soviet Union ===\n* The [[Coat of Arms of the Soviet Union]] and the [[Coats of Arms of the Soviet Republics]] showed the hammer and sickle, which also appeared on the [[red star]] badge on the uniform cap of the [[Red Army]] uniform and in many other places.\n* ''Serp i Molot'' ([[Romanization of Russian|transliteration]] of {{lang-ru|c\u0435\u0440\u043f \u0438 \u043c\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0442}}, \"sickle and hammer\") is the name of the [[Moscow Metallurgical Plant]].\n* ''Serp i Molot'' is also the name of a stop on the [[electric railway]] line from Kurski [[railway station]] in [[Moscow]] to [[Nizhny Novgorod|Gorky]], featured in [[Venedikt Yerofeyev]]'s novel, ''[[Moscow-Petushki]]''.\n\n[[File:Coat of arms of the Soviet Union 1923\u20131936.svg|thumb|150px|The first [[State Emblem of the Soviet Union]] (1923\u20131936)]]\n\n== Meaning ==\nAt the time of creation, the hammer and sickle stood for worker-peasant alliance, with the hammer a traditional symbol of the industrial proletariat (who dominated the proletariat of Russia) and the sickle a traditional symbol for the peasantry, but the meaning has since broadened to a globally recognizable symbol for [[Marxism]], [[Communist party|Marxist parties]], or [[socialist state]]s.<ref name=\"HS Role and Symbolism\"/>\n\nIn the Soviet Union, the hammer and sickle came to take on a gendered meaning, with the sickle coming to be associated with women and the hammer men.<ref name=\"HS Role and Symbolism\"/>\n\nContrary to the popular belief, the symbol is also widely used as a [[World War II]] resistance symbol against Nazism in which the Soviet soldiers and citizens died during the war.\n\n== Current usage ==\n=== Post-Soviet states ===\n[[File:Flag of Transnistria (state).svg|thumb|The flag of [[Transnistria]] is based on the flag formerly used by the [[Moldavian Soviet Socialist Republic]]]]\n[[File:Flag of Oryol (city).svg|thumb|The flag of [[Oryol]] incorporates the flag formerly used by the [[Russian Soviet Federative Socialist Republic]]]]\nTwo federal subjects of the post-Soviet Russian Federation use the hammer and sickle in their symbols: the [[Vladimir Oblast]] has them on its flag and the [[Bryansk Oblast]] has them on its flag and coat of arms, which is also the central element of its flag. In addition, the Russian city of [[Oryol]] also uses the hammer and sickle on its flag.\n\nThe former Soviet (now Russian) national airline, [[Aeroflot]], continues to use the hammer and sickle in its symbol.\n\nThe hammer and sickle can be found as a logo on most [[ushanka]] hats, usually the Soviet-styled ones.\n\nThe ''de facto'' government of [[Transnistria]] uses (with minor modifications) the flag and the emblem of the former [[Moldavian SSR]], which includes the hammer and sickle. The flag can also appear without the hammer and sickle in some circumstances, for example on Transnistrian-issued [[Vehicle registration plate|license plates]].\n\n=== Communist parties ===\nThree out of the five currently ruling Communist parties use a hammer and sickle as the party symbol: the [[Communist Party of China]], the [[Communist Party of Vietnam]] and the [[Lao People's Revolutionary Party]]. All of these use the yellow-on-red colour scheme. In Laos and Vietnam, the hammer and sickle party flags can often be seen flying side-by-side with their respective national flags.\n\nMany communist parties around the world also use it, including the [[Communist Party of Greece]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kke.gr/|title=KKE - \u0391\u03c1\u03c7\u03b9\u03ba\u03ae|work=kke.gr}}</ref>, the [[Communist Party of Chile]], the [[Communist Party of Brazil]], the [[Purba Banglar Sarbahara Party]] from Bangladesh, the [[Communist Party of Sri Lanka]], the [[Communist Party of India (Marxist)]], the [[Communist Party of India (Marxist\u2013Leninist) Liberation]], the [[Communist Party of India]], the [[Communist Party of India (Maoist)]], the Indian [[Communist Marxist Party]], the [[Socialist Unity Centre of India (Communist)]], the [[Egyptian Communist Party]], the [[Communist Party of Pakistan]], the [[Communist Party of Spain (main)|Communist Party of Spain]], the [[Communist Party of Denmark]], the [[Nepal Communist Party]], the [[Communist Party of Norway]], the [[Romanian Communist Party]], the [[Lebanese Communist Party]], the [[Communist Party of the Philippines]] and the [[Shining Path]]. The [[Communist Party (Sweden)|Communist Party of Sweden]], the [[Portuguese Communist Party]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pcp.pt/estatutos-do-pcp#cap_13|title=Estatutos do PCP, art. 72|work=pcp.pt/estatutos-do-pcp}}</ref>  and the [[Mexican Communist Party]] use the hammer and sickle imposed on the red star. The hammer and sickle accompanied by the yellow star is used by the [[Communist Refoundation Party]], the main communist party in Italy.\n\n== Variations ==\nMany symbols having similar structures and messages to the original have been designed. For example, the [[flag of Angola|Angolan flag]] shows a segment of a [[gear|cog]], crossed by a [[machete]] and crowned with a [[red star|socialist star]] while the [[flag of Mozambique]] features an [[AK-47]] crossed by a [[hoe (tool)|hoe]]. In the logo of the [[Communist Party USA]], a circle is formed by a half cog and a [[Semicircle|semicircular]] sickle-blade. A hammer is laid directly over the sickle's handle with the hammer's [[Hammer#Designs and variations|head]] at the logo's center. The logo of the [[Communist Party of Turkey (current)|Communist Party of Turkey]] consists of half a cog wheel crossed by a hammer, with a star on the top.\n\nTools represented in other designs include: the [[Ink brush|brush]], sickle and hammer of the [[Workers' Party of Korea]]; the [[spade]], [[torch|flaming torch]] and [[quill]] used prior to 1984 by the British [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] (which is a socialist and not a communist party); the [[pickaxe]] and [[rifle]] used in [[Socialist People's Republic of Albania|communist Albania]]; and the hammer and [[Compass (drafting)|compasses]] of the [[East Germany|East German]] emblem and flag. The [[Far Eastern Republic]] of Russia used an [[anchor]] crossed over a spade or pickaxe, symbolising the union of the fishermen and miners. The [[Fourth International]], founded by [[Leon Trotsky]], uses a hammer and sickle symbol on which the number 4 is superimposed. The hammer and sickle in the Fourth International symbol are the opposite of other hammer and sickle symbols in that the head of the hammer is on the right side and the sickle end tip on the left. The [[Trotskyism|Trotskyist]] [[League for the Fifth International]] merges a hammer with the number 5, using the number's lower arch to form the sickle. A sickle with a rifle is also used by the Marxist and Islamist group [[People's Mojahedin of Iran]].\n\nThe [[Communist Party of Britain]] (CGB) uses the hammer and [[Peace symbol#The dove and olive branch|dove symbol]]. Designed in 1988 by Michal Boncza, it is intended to highlight the party's connection to the peace movement. It is usually used in conjunction with the hammer and sickle and it appears on all of the CPB's publications. Some members of the CPB prefer one symbol over the other, although the party's 1994 congress reaffirmed the hammer and dove's position as the official emblem of the party. Similarly, the [[Communist Party of Israel]] uses a dove over the hammer and sickle as its symbol. The flag of the [[Guadeloupe Communist Party]] uses a sickle, turned to look like a [[capital letters|majuscule G]], to represent [[Guadeloupe]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://flagspot.net/flags/gp%7Dpcg.html|title=Parti Communiste Guadeloup\u00e9en|work=flagspot.net}}</ref>\n\nThe flag of the [[Black Front]], a [[Strasserism|Strasserist]] group founded by early Nazi Party members and expelled around the time of the [[Night of the Long Knives]] purge, along with his supporters and the [[Sturmabteilung]] and originator of the ideology and the Black Front himself [[Otto Strasser]], featured a crossed hammer and sword, symbolizing the unity of the workers and military.\n\nThe [[flag of Burma]] (from 1974\u20132010) featured a bushel of [[rice]] superimposed on a [[cogwheel]].\n\nThe flag of [[Chama Cha Mapinduzi]] (CCM, Party of the Revolution in [[Swahili language|Swahili]]), currently the ruling political party of [[Tanzania]], has a slightly different symbol with a hammer and a [[Hoe (tool)|hoe]] (''jembe'') instead of a sickle to represent the most common farm tool in Africa.\n\nThe [[National Bolshevik Party]] used the hammer and sickle in their flag, but colored black instead of gold and in a design similar to the [[Nazi flag]], a brighter red flag than the USSR, with a black hammer and sickle on a white disk in the center.\n\n== Art ==\nThe hammer and sickle has long been a common theme in socialist realism, but it has also seen some depiction in non-Marxist popular culture. [[Andy Warhol]] who created many drawings and photographs of the hammer and sickle is the most famous example of this.\n<gallery class=\"center\">\nFile:Lenpl_06.jpg|The metro station, ''Ploshchad Lenina'', [[Minsk]]\nFile:BWHammerSickle.jpg|S\u00e1ndor Pinczehelyi, ''Hammer and Sickle''\nFile:Hammer and Sickle - Kerala.jpg|A [[Tableau vivant|tableau]] in a communist rally in [[Kerala]], [[India]]\nFile:Moscow_Statue_-_panoramio.jpg|''[[Worker and Kolkhoz Woman]]'', [[Moscow]]\n</gallery>\n\n== Legal status ==\n{{see also|Red star#Legal status|l1=Red star \u00a7 Legal status|Bans on Communist symbols}}\nIn several countries in the former [[Eastern Bloc]], there are laws that define the hammer and sickle as the symbol of a \"[[totalitarian]] and criminal ideology\" and the public display of the hammer and sickle and other Communist symbols such as the red star is considered a criminal offence. [[Georgia (country)|Georgia]],<ref name=\"Communist symbols to be banned in Georgia\">{{citation|title=Communist symbols to be banned in Georgia|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-27272993|publisher=BBC News|date=4 May 2014|accessdate=13 May 2014}}</ref> [[Hungary]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Act C of 2012 on the Criminal Code, Section 335: Use of Symbols of Totalitarianism|url=http://thb.kormany.hu/download/a/46/11000/Btk_EN.pdf|page=97|website=Ministry of Interior of Hungary|accessdate=21 February 2017|quote=Any person who: a) distributes, b) uses before the public at large, or c) publicly exhibits, the swastika, the insignia of the SS, the arrow cross, the sickle and hammer, the five-pointed red star or any symbol depicting the above so as to breach public peace \u2013 specifically in a way to offend the dignity of victims of totalitarian regimes and their right to sanctity \u2013 is guilty of a misdemeanor punishable by custodial arrest, insofar as they did not result in a more serious criminal offense.}}</ref> [[Latvia]],<ref name=\"Latvia Bans Soviet, Nazi Symbols\">{{citation|title=Latvia Bans Soviet, Nazi Symbols|url=http://en.ria.ru/russia/20130621/181788657/Latvia-Bans-Soviet-Nazi-Symbols.html|publisher=RIA Novosti|date=21 June 2013|accessdate=14 September 2014}}</ref> [[Lithuania]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/low/europe/7459976.stm|work=BBC News|title=Lithuanian ban on Soviet symbols|date=17 June 2008}}</ref> [[Moldova]] (1 October 2012 \u2013 4 June 2013)<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.rferl.org/content/moldova-bans-communist-symbols/24643461.html|work=Radio Free Europe|title=Moldovan Parliament Bans Communist Symbols|date=12 July 2012}}</ref> and [[Decommunization in Ukraine|Ukraine]]<ref>{{citation|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/ukraine-bans-soviet-era-symbols-1428606171|title=Ukraine Bans Soviet-Era Symbols}}</ref><ref>{{citation|url=http://www.memory.gov.ua/laws/law-ukraine-condemnation-communist-and-national-socialist-nazi-regimes-and-prohibition-propagan|title=LAW OF UKRAINE. On the condemnation of the communist and national socialist (Nazi) regimes, and prohibition of propaganda of their symbols}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://zakon4.rada.gov.ua/laws/show/317-viii|title=\u041f\u0440\u043e \u0437\u0430\u0441\u0443\u0434\u0436\u0435\u043d\u043d\u044f \u043a\u043e\u043c\u0443\u043d\u0456\u0441\u0442\u0438\u0447\u043d\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0442\u0430 \u043d\u0430\u0446\u0456\u043e\u043d\u0430\u043b-\u0441\u043e\u0446\u0456\u0430\u043b\u0456\u0441\u0442\u0438\u0447\u043d\u043e\u0433\u043e ... -  \u0432\u0456\u0434 09.04.2015 \u2116 317-VIII|work=rada.gov.ua}}</ref> have [[banned communist symbols]] including this one. A similar law was considered in [[Estonia]], but it eventually failed in a parliamentary committee.\n\nThe foreign ministers of [[Lithuania]], [[Latvia]], [[Bulgaria]], [[Hungary]], [[Romania]] and the [[Czech Republic]] called for a [[European Union]]-wide ban on communist symbols in 2010, urging the European Union \"to criminalize the approval, denial or belittling of communist crimes\" and stating that \"the denial of such crimes should be treated the same way as the denial of the Holocaust and must be banned by law\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://rt.com/politics/european-commission-communist-crimes/|title=EU refuses to ban denial of communist crimes|work=RT English}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2013, the [[Constitutional Court of Hungary]] annulled the ban on the use of symbols of fascist and communist dictatorships, including the hammer and sickle, the red star and the swastika, saying the ban was too broad and imprecise. The court also pointed to a judgement of the [[European Court of Human Rights]] in which Hungary was found guilty of violation of [[Article 10 of the European Convention on Human Rights|article 10]], the right to [[freedom of expression]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Hungary, hammer and sickle ban declared illegal|url=http://www.ansa.it/nuova_europa/en/news/sections/news/2013/02/24/visualizza_new.html_1844118137.html|publisher=[[Agenzia Nazionale Stampa Associata|ANSA]]|date=27 February 2013|accessdate=12 November 2013}}</ref> In June 2013, the [[Constitutional Court of Moldova]] ruled that the [[Moldovan Communist Party]]\u2019s symbols\u2014the hammer and sickle\u2014are legal and can be used.<ref>{{cite news|title=Constitutional Court rules that 'hammer and sickle' can be used|url=http://www.allmoldova.com/en/moldova-news/1249056313.html|work=allmoldova.com|date=5 June 2013|accessdate=12 November 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131112194049/http://www.allmoldova.com/en/moldova-news/1249056313.html|archivedate=12 November 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn [[Indonesia]], the display of communist symbols, and the country's Communist party was banned by decree of United-States supported<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/9bb9815e-b2e8-11e7-aa26-bb002965bce8|archive-url=https://archive.today/20171029180853/https://www.ft.com/content/9bb9815e-b2e8-11e7-aa26-bb002965bce8|url-status=dead|archive-date=2017-10-29|title=Declassified files outline US support for 1965 Indonesia massacre|date=2017-10-29|website=archive.is|access-date=2019-02-16}}</ref> dictator [[Suharto]], following the [[Indonesian mass killings of 1965\u20131966|1965\u20131966 killings of communists]] in which over 500,000 people were killed<ref name=\":0\" />, with the United States providing financial support and targets for assassination to the Suharto dictatorship.<ref>{{cite news|title=Artists summoned over communist symbol exhibition|url=http://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2008/10/20/artists-summoned-over-communist-symbol-exhibition.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081026114133/http://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2008/10/20/artists-summoned-over-communist-symbol-exhibition.html|archivedate=26 October 2008|url-status=dead|author=Dickie Christanto|publisher=[[The Jakarta Post]]|date=20 October 2008|accessdate=12 November 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In January 2018, an activist protesting against [[Bumi Resources]] displayed the hammer and sickle, was accused of spreading communism and later jailed. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ucanews.com/news/indonesian-activist-jailed-for-advocating-communism/81355|title=Indonesian activist jailed for advocating communism|website=ucanews.com|language=en|access-date=2019-02-16}}</ref>\n\nIn [[Poland]], dissemination of items which are \"mediums of fascist, communist or other totalitarian symbolism\" was criminalized in 1997. However, the [[Constitutional Tribunal (Poland)|Constitutional Tribunal]] found this sanction to be unconstitutional in 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://trybunal.gov.pl/rozprawy/komunikaty-prasowe/komunikaty-po/art/2628-nowelizacja-kodeksu-karnego/s/k-1110/|title=Nowelizacja kodeksu karnego.|language=pl|date=19 July 2011|accessdate=8 April 2015}}</ref> In contrast to this treatment of the symbolism, promotion of fascist, communist and other ideology deemed totalitarian remains illegal.\n\nA ban on the Hammer and sickle and other Communist symbols is currently also being considered in [[Brazil]], the bill was introduced in 2016 but it has yet to be voted in Congress.\n\n== Usage ==\n=== Flags ===\n<gallery class=\"center\">\nFile:Flag of the Soviet Union.svg|[[Flag of the Soviet Union]] from 19 August 1955 to 26 December 1991\nFile:USSR, Jack and fortress flag of naval fortresses 1964.svg|[[List of USSR navy flags|Naval Jack of the Soviet Union]] from 16 November 1950 to 12 July 1992\nFile:Naval Ensign of the Soviet Union.svg|Naval ensign of the Soviet Union from 16 November 1950 to 27 July 1992\nFile:Flag of the Communist Party of Vietnam.svg|Flag of the [[Communist Party of Vietnam]]\nFile:Flag of the Chinese Communist Party.svg|Flag of the [[Communist Party of China]]\nFile:Flag of the Chinese Communist Party (Pre-1996).svg|Flag of the [[Communist Party of China]] (before 1996)\nFile:Flag of the Workers' Party of Korea.svg|Flag of [[Workers' Party of Korea]]\nFile:Flag of the Lebanese Communist Party.svg|Flag of the [[Lebanese Communist Party]]\nFile:\u4e2d\u570b\u5de5\u8fb2\u7d05\u8ecd\u8ecd\u65d7.svg|Flag of [[Chinese Workers' and Peasants' Red Army]]\nFile:Flag of PCR.svg|Flag of the [[Romanian Communist Party]]\nFile:KPRF Flag.png|Flag of the [[Communist Party of the Russian Federation]]\nFile:Flag of Bryansk Oblast.svg|Flag of [[Bryansk Oblast]] (Russia)\nFile:Flag of Vladimirskaya Oblast.svg|Flag of [[Vladimir Oblast]] (Russia)\nFile:Flag of Oryol (Oryol oblast).svg|Flag of [[Oryol]] (Russia)\nFile:Partito Comunista Italiano.png|Flag of the [[Italian Communist Party]]\nFile:Flag of Kurdistan Workers' Party 1978.svg|Flag of the [[Kurdistan Workers' Party]] (1978\u20131995)\nFile:National_Bolshevik_Party.svg|The flag of the [[National Bolshevik Party]], and by extension, [[National Bolshevism]]\nFile:Dhkp.svg|The flag of the [[Revolutionary People's Liberation Party\u2013Front]] (Turkey)\nFile:CPI-M-flag.svg|Flag of [[Communist Party of India]]\nFile:Flag of the Communist Party of Indonesia.svg|Flag of [[Communist_Party_of_Indonesia|PKI]] (Indonesia)\nFile:Flag of LPRP.svg|Flag of [[Lao People's Revolutionary Party]]\nFile:Flag of the Portuguese Communist Party.svg|Flag of the [[Portuguese Communist Party]]\nFile:Flag of the KSC.svg|Flag of [[Communist Party of Czechoslovakia]]\nFile:Banner of the Communist Party of Kampuchea.svg|Flag of [[Communist Party of Kampuchea|Communist Party of Cambodia]]\nFile:League of Communists of Yugoslavia Flag.svg|Flag of [[League of Communists of Yugoslavia]]\nFile:Flag of the Communist Party of Malaya.png|Flag of the [[Malayan Communist Party]] from 30 April 1930 to 2 December 1989\n</gallery>\n\n=== State emblems ===\n==== Soviet Union (in the constitutional order) ====<!--- Placed in the constitutional order. --->\n<gallery class=\"center\">\nFile:State Emblem of the Soviet Union.svg|[[State Emblem of the Soviet Union|State emblem]] of the [[Soviet Union|Union of Soviet Socialist Republics]]'''\nFile:Emblem of the Russian SFSR.svg|[[Emblem of the Russia Soviet Socialist Republic|Emblem]] of the [[Russian Soviet Federative Socialist Republic]]\nFile:Coat of arms of the Russian Federation (1992-1993).svg|[[Coat of arms of Russia|Emblem]] of the [[Russian Federation]] (1992-1993)\nFile:Emblem of the Ukrainian SSR.svg|[[Emblem of the Ukrainian Soviet Socialist Republic|Emblem]] of the [[Ukrainian Soviet Socialist Republic]]\nFile:Emblem of the Byelorussian SSR (1981-1991).svg|[[Emblem of the Byelorussian Soviet Socialist Republic|Emblem]] of the [[Byelorussian Soviet Socialist Republic]]\nFile:Emblem of the Uzbek SSR.svg|[[Emblem of the Uzbek Soviet Socialist Republic|Emblem]] of the [[Uzbek Soviet Socialist Republic]]\nFile:Emblem of Kazakh SSR.svg|[[Emblem of the Kazakh Soviet Socialist Republic|Emblem]] of the [[Kazakh Soviet Socialist Republic]]\nFile:Emblem of the Georgian SSR.svg|[[Emblem of the Georgian Soviet Socialist Republic|Emblem]] of the [[Georgian Soviet Socialist Republic]]\nFile:Emblem of the Azerbaijan SSR.svg|[[Emblem of the Azerbaijan Soviet Socialist Republic|Emblem]] of the [[Azerbaijan Soviet Socialist Republic]]\nFile:Emblem of the Lithuanian SSR.svg|[[Emblem of the Lithuanian Soviet Socialist Republic|Emblem]] of the [[Lithuanian Soviet Socialist Republic]]\nFile:Emblem of the Moldavian SSR (1981-1990).svg|[[Emblem of the Moldavian Soviet Socialist Republic|Emblem]] of the [[Moldavian Soviet Socialist Republic]]\nFile:Emblem of the Latvian SSR.svg|[[Emblem of the Latvian Soviet Socialist Republic|Emblem]] of the [[Latvian Soviet Socialist Republic]]\nFile:Emblem of the Kirghiz SSR.svg|[[Emblem of the Kirghiz Soviet Socialist Republic|Emblem]] of the [[Kirghiz Soviet Socialist Republic]]\nFile:Emblem of the Tajik SSR.svg|[[Emblem of the Tajik Soviet Socialist Republic|Emblem]] of the [[Tajik Soviet Socialist Republic]]\nFile:Emblem of the Armenian SSR.svg|[[Emblem of the Armenian Soviet Socialist Republic|Emblem]] of the [[Armenian Soviet Socialist Republic]]\nFile:Emblem of the Turkmen SSR.svg|[[Emblem of the Turkmen Soviet Socialist Republic|Emblem]] of the [[Turkmen Soviet Socialist Republic]]\nFile:Emblem of the Estonian SSR.svg|[[Emblem of the Estonian Soviet Socialist Republic|Emblem]] of the [[Estonian Soviet Socialist Republic]]\nFile:Emblem_of_the_Transcaucasian_SFSR_(1930-1936).svg|[[Emblem of the Transcaucasian Socialist Federative Soviet Republic|Emblem]] of the [[Transcaucasian Socialist Federative Soviet Republic]] (1923\u20121936)\nFile:Emblem_of_the_Karelo-Finnish_SSR.svg|[[Emblem of the Karelo-Finnish Soviet Socialist Republic|Emblem]] of the [[Karelo-Finnish Soviet Socialist Republic]] (1941\u20121956)\n</gallery>\n\n==== Other ====\n<gallery class=\"center\">\nFile:Emblem_of_the_Tuvan_People%27s_Republic_(1943-1944).svg|[[Coat of arms of the Tuva Republic|State emblem]] of the [[Tuvan People's Republic]] (1943\u20121944)\nFile:Coat of arms of Transnistria.svg|[[Coat of Arms of Transnistria|Emblem]] of the self-proclaimed [[Transnistria|Pridnestrovian Moldavian Republic]]\nFile:Emblem of Laos 1975-1991.svg|[[Emblem of Laos|State emblem]] of the [[Laos|Lao People's Democratic Republic]] (1975\u20121991)\n</gallery>\n\n=== Logos ===\n<gallery class=\"center\" classes=\"center\">\nFile:Hammer and sickle transparent.svg|Emblem of the [[Soviet Union]]\nFile:Communist Party of Vietnam flag logo.svg|Emblem of the [[Communist Party of Vietnam]]\nFile:Danghui.svg|[[Emblem of the Communist Party of China|Emblem]] of the [[Communist Party of China]]\nFile:Ministry of State Security of the People's Republic of China.svg|Logo of the [[Ministry of State Security (China)|Ministry of State Security]]\nFile:WPK symbol.svg|Emblem of [[Workers' Party of Korea]]\nFile:Emblem of the Communist Party of Czechoslovakia.svg|Emblem of the [[Communist Party of Czechoslovakia]]\nFile:Emblem of the SKJ.svg|Emblem of the [[League of Communists of Yugoslavia]]\nFile:Coat of arms of PCR.svg|Emblem of the [[Romanian Communist Party]]\nFile:Logo Italian Communist Party.png|Logo of the [[Italian Communist Party]]\nFile:Kommunistiska Partiet.svg|Logo of the [[Communist Party (Sweden)]]\nFile:KPD-logo.svg|Logo of the [[Communist Party of Germany]].\nFile:Emblema PCM Mexico.svg|Logo of the [[Mexican Communist Party]]\nFile:Logo of the Ethiopian Peoples Revolutionary Party.svg|Logo of the [[Ethiopian People's Revolutionary Party]]\nFile:Pce 2014.svg|Logo of the [[Communist Party of Spain]]\nFile:Aeroflot.svg|Logo of [[Aeroflot]]\nFile:Partido Comunista de Chile.svg|Logo of the [[Communist Party of Chile]]\nFile:Logo of the Communist Party of Greece.svg|Logo of the [[Communist Party of Greece]]\nFile:Partito comunista logo.png|Logo of the Italian [[Communist Party (Italy)|Communist Party]]\nFile:Partido Comunista de los Pueblos de Espa\u00f1a (logo).jpg|Emblem of the [[Communist Party of the Peoples of Spain]]\nFile:Communist Party of Ireland.svg|Logo of the [[Communist Party of Ireland]]\nFile:Ncpnlogo-2016.png|Logo of the [[New Communist Party of the Netherlands]]\nFile:Portuguese Communist Party logo.svg|Logo of the [[Portuguese Communist Party]]\nFile:PCB logo.svg|Logo of the [[Brazilian Communist Party]]\nFile:PCdoB.gif|Logo of the [[Communist Party of Brazil]]\nFile:Communist Party of Indonesia.png|Symbol of the [[Communist Party of Indonesia]] (1914\u20121966)\nFile:CPUSA logo.svg|Emblem of the [[Communist Party USA]] \n</gallery>\n\n== Unicode ==\nIn [[Unicode]], the \"hammer and sickle\" symbol is U+262D (\u262d). It is part of the [[Miscellaneous Symbols]] (2600\u201326FF) code block. On systems where [[Compose key]] is available, it could be written as <code>[Compose]+CCCP</code>. It was added to Unicode 1.1 in 1993.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://emojipedia.org/hammer-and-sickle/|title=\u262d Hammer and Sickle Emoji|website=emojipedia.org|language=en|access-date=2019-10-11}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n{{portal|Communism|Soviet Union}}\n* [[Arm and hammer]]\n* [[Communist symbolism]]\n* [[Hammer and pick]] (<big>\u2692</big>)\n* [[National Emblem of East Germany]] (\"hammer and compass\")\n* [[Red flag (politics)|Red flag]] (<big><span style=\"color: red\">\u2691</span></big>)\n* [[Red star]] (<big><span style=\"color: red\">\u2605</span></big>)\n* [[Transport and Map Symbols]] Unicode block (contains <big>\ud83d\udee0</big> \"hammer and wrench\" as U+1F6E0)\n\n== Notes ==\n{{notelist}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{commonscat-inline|Hammer and sickle}}\n* {{commonscat-inline|Hammer and sickle in heraldry}}\n\n[[Category:Hammer and sickle| ]]\n[[Category:Symbols of communism]]\n[[Category:National symbols of Armenia]]\n[[Category:National symbols of Azerbaijan]]\n[[Category:National symbols of Belarus]]\n[[Category:National symbols of Georgia (country)]]\n[[Category:National symbols of Kazakhstan]]\n[[Category:National symbols of Kyrgyzstan]]\n[[Category:National symbols of Moldova]]\n[[Category:National symbols of Russia]]\n[[Category:National symbols of the Soviet Union]]\n[[Category:National symbols of Tajikistan]]\n[[Category:National symbols of Turkmenistan]]\n[[Category:National symbols of Ukraine]]\n[[Category:National symbols of Uzbekistan]]\n[[Category:Heraldic charges]]\n[[Category:National symbols of Laos]]\n[[Category:National symbols of the People's Republic of China]]\n", "text_old": "{{Other uses}}\n{{short description|Communist symbol}}\n{{More citations needed|date=July 2019}}\n{{use dmy dates|date=October 2015}}\n[[File:Hammer and sickle red on transparent.svg|thumb|150px|A red hammer and sickle]] \nThe '''hammer and sickle''' ([[Unicode]]: \"\u262d\"){{efn|{{lang-ru|\u0441\u0435\u0440\u043f \u0438 \u043c\u043e\u0301\u043b\u043e\u0442|lit=sickle and hammer|translit=serp i m\u00f3lot}}<br>{{lang-zh|\u9524\u5b50\u548c\u9570\u5200}}, ''Chu\u00edzi h\u00e9 li\u00e1nd\u0101o''}} is a symbol meant to represent proletarian solidarity \u2013 a union between the peasantry and working-class. It was first adapted during the [[Russian Revolution]], the hammer representing the workers and the [[sickle]] representing the [[peasants]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.britannica.com/topic/flag-of-Union-of-Soviet-Socialist-Republics|title=Flag of Union of Soviet Socialist Republics|last=|first=|date=|website=[[Encyclopedia Britannica]]|language=en|access-date=2019-11-30}}</ref>\n\nAfter [[World War I]] (from which [[Russian Empire|Russia]] withdrew in the year 1917) and the [[Russian Civil War]], the hammer and sickle became more widely used as a symbol for labor within the [[Soviet Union]] and for [[Proletarian internationalism|international proletarian unity]]. It was taken up by many [[History of communism|communist movements]] around the world, some with local variations. Today, even after the [[dissolution of the Soviet Union]], the hammer and sickle remains commonplace in [[Russia]] and other [[Post-Soviet states|former union republics]], but its display is [[Decommunization|prohibited]] in some other former [[communist countries]] as well as in countries where [[communism]] is [[Bans on Communist symbols|banned]] by law. The hammer and sickle also remains commonplace in countries like [[Vietnam]] and [[China]] which are still officially communist states.\n\n== History ==\n[[File:Peso_Chileno_1933.jpg|thumb|400px|The [[chilean peso]] used the hammer and sickle symbol between 1895 and 1940]]\n\n=== Worker symbolism ===\nFarm and worker instruments and tools have long been used as symbols for [[Proletariat|proletarian]] struggle.\n\nThe combination of hammer and sickle symbolised the combination of farmers and construction workers. One example of use prior to its political instrumentalisation by the Soviet Union is found in [[Chilean peso|Chilean currency]] circulating since 1895.<ref>{{cite web|title=Chilean peso design, 1894|url=http://www.moneta-coins.com/photopost/showphoto.php?photo=598&title=chile-1894-pattern|accessdate=7 May 2018}}</ref>\n\nAn alternative example is the combination of a hammer and a [[plough]], with the same meaning (unity of peasants and workers). In Ireland, the symbol of the plough remains in use. The [[Starry Plough (flag)|Starry Plough]] banner was originally used by the [[Irish Citizen Army]], a socialist republican workers' militia. [[James Connolly]], co-founder of the Irish Citizen Army with [[Jack White (trade unionist)|Jack White]], said the significance of the banner was that a free Ireland would control its own destiny from the plough to the stars. A sword is forged into the plough to symbolise the end of war with the establishment of a Socialist International. This was unveiled in 1914 and flown by the Irish Citizen Army during the 1916 [[Easter Rising]].\n\n[[File:Starry Plough flag (1914).svg|thumb|150px|The [[Starry Plough (flag)|Plough flag]] from 1914 and flown during the [[Easter Rising]]]]\n\n=== Inception ===\nIn 1917, [[Vladimir Lenin]] and [[Anatoly Lunacharsky]] held a competition to create a Soviet emblem. The winning design was a hammer and sickle on top of a globe in rays of the sun, surrounded by a wreath of grain and under a five-pointed star, with the inscription \"[[Workers of the world, unite!|proletariats of the world, unite!]]\" in six languages ([[Russian language|Russian]], [[Ukrainian language|Ukrainian]], [[Belarusian language|Belarusian]], [[Georgian language|Georgian]], [[Armenian language|Armenian]] and [[Azerbaijani language|Azerbaijani]]). It originally featured a sword, but Lenin strongly objected, disliking the violent connotations.<ref name=\"HS Role and Symbolism\">{{cite web|title=The Hammer and Sickle: The Role of Symbolism and Rituals in the Russian Revolution|url=https://www.westminstercollege.edu/myriad/?parent=2514&detail=4475&content=4797|accessdate=3 August 2014}}</ref> The winning designer was [[Yevgeny Ivanovich Kamzolkin]] (1885\u20131957).<ref>[http://1965tribunal.org/the-spectre-of-hammer-and-sickle/ International People's Tribunal 1965, \"The Spectre of Hammer and Sickle\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150914194725/http://1965tribunal.org/the-spectre-of-hammer-and-sickle/ |date=14 September 2015 }}. {{retrieved|accessdate=6 November 2015}}</ref><ref>[http://www.picture-russia.com/en/painter/582 International Gallery of Contemporary Artists] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160816163416/http://www.picture-russia.com/en/painter/582|date=16 August 2016}}. {{retrieved|accessdate=6 November 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn 6 July 1923, the 2nd session of the [[Central Executive Committee of the Soviet Union|Central Executive Committee]] (CIK) adopted this emblem.<ref name=\"HS Role and Symbolism\"/>\n\n=== Usage in the Soviet Union ===\n* The [[Coat of Arms of the Soviet Union]] and the [[Coats of Arms of the Soviet Republics]] showed the hammer and sickle, which also appeared on the [[red star]] badge on the uniform cap of the [[Red Army]] uniform and in many other places.\n* ''Serp i Molot'' ([[Romanization of Russian|transliteration]] of {{lang-ru|c\u0435\u0440\u043f \u0438 \u043c\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0442}}, \"sickle and hammer\") is the name of the [[Moscow Metallurgical Plant]].\n* ''Serp i Molot'' is also the name of a stop on the [[electric railway]] line from Kurski [[railway station]] in [[Moscow]] to [[Nizhny Novgorod|Gorky]], featured in [[Venedikt Yerofeyev]]'s novel, ''[[Moscow-Petushki]]''.\n\n[[File:Coat of arms of the Soviet Union 1923\u20131936.svg|thumb|150px|The first [[State Emblem of the Soviet Union]] (1923\u20131936)]]\n\n== Meaning ==\nAt the time of creation, the hammer and sickle stood for worker-peasant alliance, with the hammer a traditional symbol of the industrial proletariat (who dominated the proletariat of Russia) and the sickle a traditional symbol for the peasantry, but the meaning has since broadened to a globally recognizable symbol for [[Marxism]], [[Communist party|Marxist parties]], or [[socialist state]]s.<ref name=\"HS Role and Symbolism\"/>\n\nIn the Soviet Union, the hammer and sickle came to take on a gendered meaning, with the sickle coming to be associated with women and the hammer men.<ref name=\"HS Role and Symbolism\"/>\n\nContrary to the popular belief, the symbol is also widely used as a [[World War II]] resistance symbol against Nazism in which the Soviet soldiers and citizens died during the war.\n\n== Current usage ==\n=== Post-Soviet states ===\n[[File:Flag of Transnistria (state).svg|thumb|The flag of [[Transnistria]] is based on the flag formerly used by the [[Moldavian Soviet Socialist Republic]]]]\n[[File:Flag of Oryol (city).svg|thumb|The flag of [[Oryol]] incorporates the flag formerly used by the [[Russian Soviet Federative Socialist Republic]]]]\nTwo federal subjects of the post-Soviet Russian Federation use the hammer and sickle in their symbols: the [[Vladimir Oblast]] has them on its flag and the [[Bryansk Oblast]] has them on its flag and coat of arms, which is also the central element of its flag. In addition, the Russian city of [[Oryol]] also uses the hammer and sickle on its flag.\n\nThe former Soviet (now Russian) national airline, [[Aeroflot]], continues to use the hammer and sickle in its symbol.\n\nThe hammer and sickle can be found as a logo on most [[ushanka]] hats, usually the Soviet-styled ones.\n\nThe ''de facto'' government of [[Transnistria]] uses (with minor modifications) the flag and the emblem of the former [[Moldavian SSR]], which includes the hammer and sickle. The flag can also appear without the hammer and sickle in some circumstances, for example on Transnistrian-issued [[Vehicle registration plate|license plates]].\n\n=== Communist parties ===\nThree out of the five currently ruling Communist parties use a hammer and sickle as the party symbol: the [[Communist Party of China]], the [[Communist Party of Vietnam]] and the [[Lao People's Revolutionary Party]]. All of these use the yellow-on-red colour scheme. In Laos and Vietnam, the hammer and sickle party flags can often be seen flying side-by-side with their respective national flags.\n\nMany communist parties around the world also use it, including the [[Communist Party of Greece]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kke.gr/|title=KKE - \u0391\u03c1\u03c7\u03b9\u03ba\u03ae|work=kke.gr}}</ref>, the [[Communist Party of Chile]], the [[Communist Party of Brazil]], the [[Purba Banglar Sarbahara Party]] from Bangladesh, the [[Communist Party of Sri Lanka]], the [[Communist Party of India (Marxist)]], the [[Communist Party of India (Marxist\u2013Leninist) Liberation]], the [[Communist Party of India]], the [[Communist Party of India (Maoist)]], the Indian [[Communist Marxist Party]], the [[Socialist Unity Centre of India (Communist)]], the [[Egyptian Communist Party]], the [[Communist Party of Pakistan]], the [[Communist Party of Spain (main)|Communist Party of Spain]], the [[Communist Party of Denmark]], the [[Nepal Communist Party]], the [[Communist Party of Norway]], the [[Romanian Communist Party]], the [[Lebanese Communist Party]], the [[Communist Party of the Philippines]] and the [[Shining Path]]. The [[Communist Party (Sweden)|Communist Party of Sweden]], the [[Portuguese Communist Party]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pcp.pt/estatutos-do-pcp#cap_13|title=Estatutos do PCP, art. 72|work=pcp.pt/estatutos-do-pcp}}</ref>  and the [[Mexican Communist Party]] use the hammer and sickle imposed on the red star. The hammer and sickle accompanied by the yellow star is used by the [[Communist Refoundation Party]], the main communist party in Italy.\n\n== Variations ==\nMany symbols having similar structures and messages to the original have been designed. For example, the [[flag of Angola|Angolan flag]] shows a segment of a [[gear|cog]], crossed by a [[machete]] and crowned with a [[red star|socialist star]] while the [[flag of Mozambique]] features an [[AK-47]] crossed by a [[hoe (tool)|hoe]]. In the logo of the [[Communist Party USA]], a circle is formed by a half cog and a [[Semicircle|semicircular]] sickle-blade. A hammer is laid directly over the sickle's handle with the hammer's [[Hammer#Designs and variations|head]] at the logo's center. The logo of the [[Communist Party of Turkey (current)|Communist Party of Turkey]] consists of half a cog wheel crossed by a hammer, with a star on the top.\n\nTools represented in other designs include: the [[Ink brush|brush]], sickle and hammer of the [[Workers' Party of Korea]]; the [[spade]], [[torch|flaming torch]] and [[quill]] used prior to 1984 by the British [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] (which is a socialist and not a communist party); the [[pickaxe]] and [[rifle]] used in [[Socialist People's Republic of Albania|communist Albania]]; and the hammer and [[Compass (drafting)|compasses]] of the [[East Germany|East German]] emblem and flag. The [[Far Eastern Republic]] of Russia used an [[anchor]] crossed over a spade or pickaxe, symbolising the union of the fishermen and miners. The [[Fourth International]], founded by [[Leon Trotsky]], uses a hammer and sickle symbol on which the number 4 is superimposed. The hammer and sickle in the Fourth International symbol are the opposite of other hammer and sickle symbols in that the head of the hammer is on the right side and the sickle end tip on the left. The [[Trotskyism|Trotskyist]] [[League for the Fifth International]] merges a hammer with the number 5, using the number's lower arch to form the sickle. A sickle with a rifle is also used by the Marxist and Islamist group [[People's Mojahedin of Iran]].\n\nThe [[Communist Party of Britain]] (CGB) uses the hammer and [[Peace symbol#The dove and olive branch|dove symbol]]. Designed in 1988 by Michal Boncza, it is intended to highlight the party's connection to the peace movement. It is usually used in conjunction with the hammer and sickle and it appears on all of the CPB's publications. Some members of the CPB prefer one symbol over the other, although the party's 1994 congress reaffirmed the hammer and dove's position as the official emblem of the party. Similarly, the [[Communist Party of Israel]] uses a dove over the hammer and sickle as its symbol. The flag of the [[Guadeloupe Communist Party]] uses a sickle, turned to look like a [[capital letters|majuscule G]], to represent [[Guadeloupe]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://flagspot.net/flags/gp%7Dpcg.html|title=Parti Communiste Guadeloup\u00e9en|work=flagspot.net}}</ref>\n\nThe flag of the [[Black Front]], a [[Strasserism|Strasserist]] group founded by early Nazi Party members and expelled around the time of the [[Night of the Long Knives]] purge, along with his supporters and the [[Sturmabteilung]] and originator of the ideology and the Black Front himself [[Otto Strasser]], featured a crossed hammer and sword, symbolizing the unity of the workers and military.\n\nThe [[flag of Burma]] (from 1974\u20132010) featured a bushel of [[rice]] superimposed on a [[cogwheel]].\n\nThe flag of [[Chama Cha Mapinduzi]] (CCM, Party of the Revolution in [[Swahili language|Swahili]]), currently the ruling political party of [[Tanzania]], has a slightly different symbol with a hammer and a [[Hoe (tool)|hoe]] (''jembe'') instead of a sickle to represent the most common farm tool in Africa.\n\nThe [[National Bolshevik Party]] used the hammer and sickle in their flag, but colored black instead of gold and in a design similar to the [[Nazi flag]], a brighter red flag than the USSR, with a black hammer and sickle on a white disk in the center.\n\n== Art ==\nThe hammer and sickle has long been a common theme in socialist realism, but it has also seen some depiction in non-Marxist popular culture. [[Andy Warhol]] who created many drawings and photographs of the hammer and sickle is the most famous example of this.\n<gallery class=\"center\">\nFile:Lenpl_06.jpg|The metro station, ''Ploshchad Lenina'', [[Minsk]]\nFile:BWHammerSickle.jpg|S\u00e1ndor Pinczehelyi, ''Hammer and Sickle''\nFile:Hammer and Sickle - Kerala.jpg|A [[Tableau vivant|tableau]] in a communist rally in [[Kerala]], [[India]]\nFile:Moscow_Statue_-_panoramio.jpg|''[[Worker and Kolkhoz Woman]]'', [[Moscow]]\n</gallery>\n\n== Legal status ==\n{{see also|Red star#Legal status|l1=Red star \u00a7 Legal status|Bans on Communist symbols}}\nIn several countries in the former [[Eastern Bloc]], there are laws that define the hammer and sickle as the symbol of a \"[[totalitarian]] and criminal ideology\" and the public display of the hammer and sickle and other Communist symbols such as the red star is considered a criminal offence. [[Georgia (country)|Georgia]],<ref name=\"Communist symbols to be banned in Georgia\">{{citation|title=Communist symbols to be banned in Georgia|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-27272993|publisher=BBC News|date=4 May 2014|accessdate=13 May 2014}}</ref> [[Hungary]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Act C of 2012 on the Criminal Code, Section 335: Use of Symbols of Totalitarianism|url=http://thb.kormany.hu/download/a/46/11000/Btk_EN.pdf|page=97|website=Ministry of Interior of Hungary|accessdate=21 February 2017|quote=Any person who: a) distributes, b) uses before the public at large, or c) publicly exhibits, the swastika, the insignia of the SS, the arrow cross, the sickle and hammer, the five-pointed red star or any symbol depicting the above so as to breach public peace \u2013 specifically in a way to offend the dignity of victims of totalitarian regimes and their right to sanctity \u2013 is guilty of a misdemeanor punishable by custodial arrest, insofar as they did not result in a more serious criminal offense.}}</ref> [[Latvia]],<ref name=\"Latvia Bans Soviet, Nazi Symbols\">{{citation|title=Latvia Bans Soviet, Nazi Symbols|url=http://en.ria.ru/russia/20130621/181788657/Latvia-Bans-Soviet-Nazi-Symbols.html|publisher=RIA Novosti|date=21 June 2013|accessdate=14 September 2014}}</ref> [[Lithuania]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/low/europe/7459976.stm|work=BBC News|title=Lithuanian ban on Soviet symbols|date=17 June 2008}}</ref> [[Moldova]] (1 October 2012 \u2013 4 June 2013)<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.rferl.org/content/moldova-bans-communist-symbols/24643461.html|work=Radio Free Europe|title=Moldovan Parliament Bans Communist Symbols|date=12 July 2012}}</ref> and [[Decommunization in Ukraine|Ukraine]]<ref>{{citation|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/ukraine-bans-soviet-era-symbols-1428606171|title=Ukraine Bans Soviet-Era Symbols}}</ref><ref>{{citation|url=http://www.memory.gov.ua/laws/law-ukraine-condemnation-communist-and-national-socialist-nazi-regimes-and-prohibition-propagan|title=LAW OF UKRAINE. On the condemnation of the communist and national socialist (Nazi) regimes, and prohibition of propaganda of their symbols}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://zakon4.rada.gov.ua/laws/show/317-viii|title=\u041f\u0440\u043e \u0437\u0430\u0441\u0443\u0434\u0436\u0435\u043d\u043d\u044f \u043a\u043e\u043c\u0443\u043d\u0456\u0441\u0442\u0438\u0447\u043d\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0442\u0430 \u043d\u0430\u0446\u0456\u043e\u043d\u0430\u043b-\u0441\u043e\u0446\u0456\u0430\u043b\u0456\u0441\u0442\u0438\u0447\u043d\u043e\u0433\u043e ... -  \u0432\u0456\u0434 09.04.2015 \u2116 317-VIII|work=rada.gov.ua}}</ref> have [[banned communist symbols]] including this one. A similar law was considered in [[Estonia]], but it eventually failed in a parliamentary committee.\n\nThe foreign ministers of [[Lithuania]], [[Latvia]], [[Bulgaria]], [[Hungary]], [[Romania]] and the [[Czech Republic]] called for a [[European Union]]-wide ban on communist symbols in 2010, urging the European Union \"to criminalize the approval, denial or belittling of communist crimes\" and stating that \"the denial of such crimes should be treated the same way as the denial of the Holocaust and must be banned by law\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://rt.com/politics/european-commission-communist-crimes/|title=EU refuses to ban denial of communist crimes|work=RT English}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2013, the [[Constitutional Court of Hungary]] annulled the ban on the use of symbols of fascist and communist dictatorships, including the hammer and sickle, the red star and the swastika, saying the ban was too broad and imprecise. The court also pointed to a judgement of the [[European Court of Human Rights]] in which Hungary was found guilty of violation of [[Article 10 of the European Convention on Human Rights|article 10]], the right to [[freedom of expression]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Hungary, hammer and sickle ban declared illegal|url=http://www.ansa.it/nuova_europa/en/news/sections/news/2013/02/24/visualizza_new.html_1844118137.html|publisher=[[Agenzia Nazionale Stampa Associata|ANSA]]|date=27 February 2013|accessdate=12 November 2013}}</ref> In June 2013, the [[Constitutional Court of Moldova]] ruled that the [[Moldovan Communist Party]]\u2019s symbols\u2014the hammer and sickle\u2014are legal and can be used.<ref>{{cite news|title=Constitutional Court rules that 'hammer and sickle' can be used|url=http://www.allmoldova.com/en/moldova-news/1249056313.html|work=allmoldova.com|date=5 June 2013|accessdate=12 November 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131112194049/http://www.allmoldova.com/en/moldova-news/1249056313.html|archivedate=12 November 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn [[Indonesia]], the display of communist symbols, and the country's Communist party was banned by decree of United-States supported<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/9bb9815e-b2e8-11e7-aa26-bb002965bce8|archive-url=https://archive.today/20171029180853/https://www.ft.com/content/9bb9815e-b2e8-11e7-aa26-bb002965bce8|url-status=dead|archive-date=2017-10-29|title=Declassified files outline US support for 1965 Indonesia massacre|date=2017-10-29|website=archive.is|access-date=2019-02-16}}</ref> dictator [[Suharto]], following the [[Indonesian mass killings of 1965\u20131966|1965\u20131966 killings of communists]] in which over 500,000 people were killed<ref name=\":0\" />, with the United States providing financial support and targets for assassination to the Suharto dictatorship.<ref>{{cite news|title=Artists summoned over communist symbol exhibition|url=http://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2008/10/20/artists-summoned-over-communist-symbol-exhibition.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081026114133/http://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2008/10/20/artists-summoned-over-communist-symbol-exhibition.html|archivedate=26 October 2008|url-status=dead|author=Dickie Christanto|publisher=[[The Jakarta Post]]|date=20 October 2008|accessdate=12 November 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In January 2018, an activist protesting against [[Bumi Resources]] displayed the hammer and sickle, was accused of spreading communism and later jailed. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ucanews.com/news/indonesian-activist-jailed-for-advocating-communism/81355|title=Indonesian activist jailed for advocating communism|website=ucanews.com|language=en|access-date=2019-02-16}}</ref>\n\nIn [[Poland]], dissemination of items which are \"mediums of fascist, communist or other totalitarian symbolism\" was criminalized in 1997. However, the [[Constitutional Tribunal (Poland)|Constitutional Tribunal]] found this sanction to be unconstitutional in 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://trybunal.gov.pl/rozprawy/komunikaty-prasowe/komunikaty-po/art/2628-nowelizacja-kodeksu-karnego/s/k-1110/|title=Nowelizacja kodeksu karnego.|language=pl|date=19 July 2011|accessdate=8 April 2015}}</ref> In contrast to this treatment of the symbolism, promotion of fascist, communist and other ideology deemed totalitarian remains illegal.\n\nA ban on the Hammer and sickle and other Communist symbols is currently also being considered in [[Brazil]], the bill was introduced in 2016 but it has yet to be voted in Congress.\n\n== Usage ==\n=== Flags ===\n<gallery class=\"center\">\nFile:Flag of the Soviet Union.svg|[[Flag of the Soviet Union]] from 19 August 1955 to 26 December 1991\nFile:USSR, Jack and fortress flag of naval fortresses 1964.svg|[[List of USSR navy flags|Naval Jack of the Soviet Union]] from 16 November 1950 to 12 July 1992\nFile:Naval Ensign of the Soviet Union.svg|Naval ensign of the Soviet Union from 16 November 1950 to 27 July 1992\nFile:Flag of the Communist Party of Vietnam.svg|Flag of the [[Communist Party of Vietnam]]\nFile:Flag of the Chinese Communist Party.svg|Flag of the [[Communist Party of China]]\nFile:Flag of the Chinese Communist Party (Pre-1996).svg|Flag of the [[Communist Party of China]] (before 1996)\nFile:Flag of the Workers' Party of Korea.svg|Flag of [[Workers' Party of Korea]]\nFile:Flag of the Lebanese Communist Party.svg|Flag of the [[Lebanese Communist Part