f the [[Italian Communist Party]]\nFile:Kommunistiska Partiet.svg|Logo of the [[Communist Party (Sweden)]]\nFile:KPD-logo.svg|Logo of the [[Communist Party of Germany]].\nFile:Emblema PCM Mexico.svg|Logo of the [[Mexican Communist Party]]\nFile:Logo of the Ethiopian Peoples Revolutionary Party.svg|Logo of the [[Ethiopian People's Revolutionary Party]]\nFile:Pce 2014.svg|Logo of the [[Communist Party of Spain]]\nFile:Aeroflot.svg|Logo of [[Aeroflot]]\nFile:Partido Comunista de Chile.svg|Logo of the [[Communist Party of Chile]]\nFile:Logo of the Communist Party of Greece.svg|Logo of the [[Communist Party of Greece]]\nFile:Partito comunista logo.png|Logo of the Italian [[Communist Party (Italy)|Communist Party]]\nFile:Partido Comunista de los Pueblos de Espa\u00f1a (logo).jpg|Emblem of the [[Communist Party of the Peoples of Spain]]\nFile:Communist Party of Ireland.svg|Logo of the [[Communist Party of Ireland]]\nFile:Ncpnlogo-2016.png|Logo of the [[New Communist Party of the Netherlands]]\nFile:Portuguese Communist Party logo.svg|Logo of the [[Portuguese Communist Party]]\nFile:PCB logo.svg|Logo of the [[Brazilian Communist Party]]\nFile:PCdoB.gif|Logo of the [[Communist Party of Brazil]]\nFile:Communist Party of Indonesia.png|Symbol of the [[Communist Party of Indonesia]] (1914\u20121966)\nFile:CPUSA logo.svg|Emblem of the [[Communist Party USA]] \n</gallery>\n\n== Unicode ==\nIn [[Unicode]], the \"hammer and sickle\" symbol is U+262D (\u262d). It is part of the [[Miscellaneous Symbols]] (2600\u201326FF) code block. On systems where [[Compose key]] is available, it could be written as <code>[Compose]+CCCP</code>. It was added to Unicode 1.1 in 1993.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://emojipedia.org/hammer-and-sickle/|title=\u262d Hammer and Sickle Emoji|website=emojipedia.org|language=en|access-date=2019-10-11}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n{{portal|Communism|Soviet Union}}\n* [[Arm and hammer]]\n* [[Communist symbolism]]\n* [[Hammer and pick]] (<big>\u2692</big>)\n* [[National Emblem of East Germany]] (\"hammer and compass\")\n* [[Red flag (politics)|Red flag]] (<big><span style=\"color: red\">\u2691</span></big>)\n* [[Red star]] (<big><span style=\"color: red\">\u2605</span></big>)\n* [[Transport and Map Symbols]] Unicode block (contains <big>\ud83d\udee0</big> \"hammer and wrench\" as U+1F6E0)\n\n== Notes ==\n{{notelist}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{commonscat-inline|Hammer and sickle}}\n* {{commonscat-inline|Hammer and sickle in heraldry}}\n\n[[Category:Hammer and sickle| ]]\n[[Category:Symbols of communism]]\n[[Category:National symbols of Armenia]]\n[[Category:National symbols of Azerbaijan]]\n[[Category:National symbols of Belarus]]\n[[Category:National symbols of Georgia (country)]]\n[[Category:National symbols of Kazakhstan]]\n[[Category:National symbols of Kyrgyzstan]]\n[[Category:National symbols of Moldova]]\n[[Category:National symbols of Russia]]\n[[Category:National symbols of the Soviet Union]]\n[[Category:National symbols of Tajikistan]]\n[[Category:National symbols of Turkmenistan]]\n[[Category:National symbols of Ukraine]]\n[[Category:National symbols of Uzbekistan]]\n[[Category:Heraldic charges]]\n[[Category:National symbols of Laos]]\n[[Category:National symbols of the People's Republic of China]]\n", "name_user": "89.211.105.10", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hammer_and_sickle"}
{"title_page": "Land consumption", "text_new": "[[File:Oil_palm_forest_fragment_Costa_Rica.JPG|thumb|Tropical forest [[deforestation]] for [[oil palm]] plantations in [[Costa Rica]]]]\n\n'''Land consumption''' as part of human [[resource consumption]] is the [[land development|conversion of land]] with [[soil health|healthy soil]] and intact [[habitat|habitats]] into areas for [[intensive farming|industrial agriculture]], traffic ([[road|road building]]) and especially [[urbanization|urban]] [[human settlement|human settlements]]. More formally, the [[European Environment Agency|EEA]] <ref>{{cite web|publisher=[[European Environment Agency]] EEA|year=1997|title=The concept of environmental space|url=http://glossary.eea.europa.eu/terminology/concept_html?term=land%20consumption}}</ref> has identified three [[land]] consuming activities:\n#The expansion of [[built-up area]] which can be directly measured;\n#the absolute extent of land that is subject to exploitation by [[agriculture]], [[forestry]] or other economic activities; and\n#the [[overexploitation|over-intensive exploitation]] of land that is used for agriculture and forestry.\nIn all of those respects, land consumption is equivalent to typical [[land use]] in [[industrialized]] regions and civilizations.\n\n[[File:2007 Belwerder 003.JPG|thumb|Building construction in [[Olsztyn]], Poland]]\n[[File:Popie\u0142uszki Olsztyn 2007.JPG|thumb|Road construction in [[Olsztyn]], Poland]]\nSince often aforementioned conversion activities are virtually [[irreversible process|irreversible]], the term '''land loss''' is also used. From 1990 to 2000, [[orders of magnitude (area)#108_to_1014_square_metres|{{convert|1.4|e6ha}}]] of open space were consumed in the U.S..<ref name=mcdonald>{{cite journal|journal=PLOS ONE|volume=5|issue=3: e9509\n|pages=e9509|date=2010-03-03\n|quote=Nationally, 1.4 million ha of open space was lost, and the amount lost in a given city was correlated with [[population growth]]\n|doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0009509\n|pmid=20209082|pmc=2831069\n|title=Open Space Loss and Land Inequality in United States' Cities, 1990\u20132000\n|author=Robert I. McDonald, Richard T. T. Forman, and Peter Kareiva|bibcode=2010PLoSO...5.9509M}}</ref> In Germany, land is being consumed at a rate of more than {{convert|70|ha}} every day (~{{convert|250|e3ha}} per 10 years).<ref name=soilatlas2015>{{cite web|title=\"Limit land consumption worldwide!\" The Soil Atlas 2015 has been released |year=2015|url=http://www.iass-potsdam.de/en/news-media/news/limit-land-consumption-worldwide-soil-atlas-2015-has-been-released|quote=About 60 per cent of the land used to meet European demand is located outside the EU. This makes Europe the continent that is most dependent on land beyond its borders to sustain its [[Lifestyle (sociology)|lifestyle]], its [[agricultural industry]] and its [[energy demand|hunger for energy]].}}</ref> In European Union, land take is estimated approximately about to 1.2 million hectares in 21 EU countries over the period 1990-2006.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Gardi|first=Ciro|last2=Panagos|first2=Panos|last3=Liedekerke|first3=Marc Van|last4=Bosco|first4=Claudio|last5=Brogniez|first5=Delphine De|date=2015-05-04|title=Land take and food security: assessment of land take on the agricultural production in Europe|journal=Journal of Environmental Planning and Management|volume=58|issue=5|pages=898\u2013912|doi=10.1080/09640568.2014.899490|issn=0964-0568}}</ref> \n\n{{quote|[[Urban growth]] reduces [[Public space|open space]] in and around [[cities]], impacting [[biodiversity]] and [[ecosystem services]]|McDonald et al.<ref name=mcdonald/>}}\n\nLand loss can also happen due to natural factors, like [[erosion]] or [[desertification]] - nevertheless most of those can also eventually be tracked back to [[human impact on the environment|human activities]]. Another slightly different interpretation of the term is the forced displacement or [[compulsory acquisition]] of a native people or settlers from their original land due to [[land grabbing]], etc.. Again, in most cases, this will be due to economic reasons like search for [[profitable]] [[investment]] and [[commodification of nature|commodification of natural resources]].\n\nEven though global land loss progresses at an alarming rate, the [[land footprint]], the area required by some Western countries can a lot larger than the land actually used or even available in the country itself.<ref name=soilatlas2015/><ref>{{cite web|publisher=[[Friends of the Earth|FOE]] Europe|url=http://www.foeeurope.org/sites/default/files/resource_use/2016/foee-true-cost-consumption-land-footprint.pdf|title=The true cost of consumption - The EU's land footprint|year=2016|quote=The European Union uses more than its fair share of global land. In 2010, the amount of land used to satisfy our [[consumption (economics)|consumption]], solely of agricultural goods and services, amounted to 269 million hectares \u2013 that\u2019s 43% more agricultural land than is available within the EU itself and an area almost the size of France and Italy used outside of our borders.}}</ref>\n\nWhile [[land price]]s have surged in the first few years of the 21st century, land consumption economy still lacks [[environmental full-cost accounting]] to add the long-term costs of [[environmental degradation]].\n\n==Consequences of land consumption==\nThe major effects of land conversion for [[economic growth]] are:\n*[[Land degradation]]\n*[[Habitat loss]] - built-up areas support only particularly adapted species\n*[[Soil degradation]] - loss or [[soil contamination|contamination]] of [[top soil]] by civilization [[waste]] and general [[pollution]]\n*[[Soil compaction]] - buildings, heavy machinery and vehicle traffic compact the soil to a degree that [[Macrobiology|macrobiotic]] [[soil life]] is eradicated\n*[[Impervious surface]]s - [[asphalt]] and [[concrete]] seal of the soil from the atmosphere and disrupt natural [[water cycle|water]] and [[biogeochemical cycle]]s\n\n==See also==\n{{colbegin}}\n*[[Land restoration]]\n*[[Land rehabilitation]]\n*[[Land reclamation]]\n* [[Land use]]\n{{colend}}\n[[File:Woerrstadt-Industriegebiet-2008-01-18.jpg|thumb|900px|Land conversion in [[W\u00f6rrstadt]], Germany]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Land use}}\n{{authority control}}\n[[Category:Land use]]\n[[Category:Ecology]]\n[[Category:Environmental issues with soil]]\n[[Category:Human impact on the environment]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Oil_palm_forest_fragment_Costa_Rica.JPG|thumb|Tropical forest [[deforestation]] for [[oil palm]] plantations in [[Costa Rica]]]]\n\n'''Land consumption''' as part of human [[resource consumption]] is the [[land development|conversion of land]] with [[soil health|healthy soil]] and intact [[habitat|habitats]] into areas for [[intensive farming|industrial agriculture]], traffic ([[road|road building]]) and especially [[urbanization|urban]] [[human settlement|human settlements]]. More formally, the [[European Environment Agency|EEA]] <ref>{{cite web|publisher=[[European Environment Agency]] EEA|year=1997|title=The concept of environmental space|url=http://glossary.eea.europa.eu/terminology/concept_html?term=land%20consumption}}</ref> has identified three [[land]] consuming activities:\n#The expansion of [[built-up area]] which can be directly measured;\n#the absolute extent of land that is subject to exploitation by [[agriculture]], [[forestry]] or other economic activities; and\n#the [[overexploitation|over-intensive exploitation]] of land that is used for agriculture and forestry.\nIn all of those respects, land consumption is equivalent to typical [[land use]] in [[industrialized]] regions and civilizations.\n\n[[File:2007 Belwerder 003.JPG|thumb|Building construction in [[Olsztyn]], Poland]]\n[[File:Popie\u0142uszki Olsztyn 2007.JPG|thumb|Road construction in [[Olsztyn]], Poland]]\nSince often aforementioned conversion activities are virtually [[irreversible process|irreversible]], the term '''land loss''' is also used. From 1990 to 2000, [[orders of magnitude (area)#108_to_1014_square_metres|{{convert|1.4|e6ha}}]] of open space were consumed in the U.S..<ref name=mcdonald>{{cite journal|journal=PLOS ONE|volume=5|issue=3: e9509\n|pages=e9509|date=2010-03-03\n|quote=Nationally, 1.4 million ha of open space was lost, and the amount lost in a given city was correlated with [[population growth]]\n|doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0009509\n|pmid=20209082|pmc=2831069\n|title=Open Space Loss and Land Inequality in United States' Cities, 1990\u20132000\n|author=Robert I. McDonald, Richard T. T. Forman, and Peter Kareiva|bibcode=2010PLoSO...5.9509M}}</ref> In Germany, land is being consumed at a rate of more than {{convert|70|ha}} every day (~{{convert|250|e3ha}} per 10 years).<ref name=soilatlas2015>{{cite web|title=\"Limit land consumption worldwide!\" The Soil Atlas 2015 has been released |year=2015|url=http://www.iass-potsdam.de/en/news-media/news/limit-land-consumption-worldwide-soil-atlas-2015-has-been-released|quote=About 60 per cent of the land used to meet European demand is located outside the EU. This makes Europe the continent that is most dependent on land beyond its borders to sustain its [[Lifestyle (sociology)|lifestyle]], its [[agricultural industry]] and its [[energy demand|hunger for energy]].}}</ref> In European Union, land take is estimated approximately about to 1.2 million hectares in 21 EU countries over the period 1990-2006<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Gardi|first=Ciro|last2=Panagos|first2=Panos|last3=Liedekerke|first3=Marc Van|last4=Bosco|first4=Claudio|last5=Brogniez|first5=Delphine De|date=2015-05-04|title=Land take and food security: assessment of land take on the agricultural production in Europe|journal=Journal of Environmental Planning and Management|volume=58|issue=5|pages=898\u2013912|doi=10.1080/09640568.2014.899490|issn=0964-0568}}</ref>. \n\n{{quote|[[Urban growth]] reduces [[Public space|open space]] in and around [[cities]], impacting [[biodiversity]] and [[ecosystem services]]|McDonald et al.<ref name=mcdonald/>}}\n\nLand loss can also happen due to natural factors, like [[erosion]] or [[desertification]] - nevertheless most of those can also eventually be tracked back to [[human impact on the environment|human activities]]. Another slightly different interpretation of the term is the forced displacement or [[compulsory acquisition]] of a native people or settlers from their original land due to [[land grabbing]], etc.. Again, in most cases, this will be due to economic reasons like search for [[profitable]] [[investment]] and [[commodification of nature|commodification of natural resources]].\n\nEven though global land loss progresses at an alarming rate, the [[land footprint]], the area required by some Western countries can a lot larger than the land actually used or even available in the country itself.<ref name=soilatlas2015/><ref>{{cite web|publisher=[[Friends of the Earth|FOE]] Europe|url=http://www.foeeurope.org/sites/default/files/resource_use/2016/foee-true-cost-consumption-land-footprint.pdf|title=The true cost of consumption - The EU's land footprint|year=2016|quote=The European Union uses more than its fair share of global land. In 2010, the amount of land used to satisfy our [[consumption (economics)|consumption]], solely of agricultural goods and services, amounted to 269 million hectares \u2013 that\u2019s 43% more agricultural land than is available within the EU itself and an area almost the size of France and Italy used outside of our borders.}}</ref>\n\nWhile [[land price]]s have surged in the first few years of the 21st century, land consumption economy still lacks [[environmental full-cost accounting]] to add the long-term costs of [[environmental degradation]].\n\n==Consequences of land consumption==\nThe major effects of land conversion for [[economic growth]] are:\n*[[Land degradation]]\n*[[Habitat loss]] - built-up areas support only particularly adapted species\n*[[Soil degradation]] - loss or [[soil contamination|contamination]] of [[top soil]] by civilization [[waste]] and general [[pollution]]\n*[[Soil compaction]] - buildings, heavy machinery and vehicle traffic compact the soil to a degree that [[Macrobiology|macrobiotic]] [[soil life]] is eradicated\n*[[Impervious surface]]s - [[asphalt]] and [[concrete]] seal of the soil from the atmosphere and disrupt natural [[water cycle|water]] and [[biogeochemical cycle]]s\n\n==See also==\n{{colbegin}}\n*[[Land restoration]]\n*[[Land rehabilitation]]\n*[[Land reclamation]]\n* [[Land use]]\n{{colend}}\n[[File:Woerrstadt-Industriegebiet-2008-01-18.jpg|thumb|900px|Land conversion in [[W\u00f6rrstadt]], Germany]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Land use}}\n{{authority control}}\n[[Category:Land use]]\n[[Category:Ecology]]\n[[Category:Environmental issues with soil]]\n[[Category:Human impact on the environment]]\n", "name_user": "DannyS712", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fixing the location of periods / full stops", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Land_consumption"}
{"title_page": "Lambada (song)", "text_new": "{{short description|1988 song recorded by Kaoma with Loalwa Braz}}\n{{other uses|Lambada (disambiguation)}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2012}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Lambada\n| cover      = Lambada_(cover).jpg\n| alt        =\n| caption    = \"Lambada\" artwork\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Kaoma]]\n| album      = [[Worldbeat (album)|Worldbeat]]\n| released   = July 1988\n| format     = [[Gramophone record|7\" vinyl]], [[Gramophone record|12\" vinyl]], [[Compact disc|CD single]], [[CD maxi]]\n| recorded   =\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Lambada]]\n| length     = 3:28\n| label      =\n| writer     = Chico de Oliveira, Gonzalo Hermosa-Gonzales\n| producer   = Jean-Claude Bonaventure\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title = [[Dan\u00e7ando Lambada]]\n| next_year  = 1988\n}}\n\n\"'''Lambada'''\", also known as \"'''Chorando Se Foi (Lambada)'''\" or \"'''Llorando se fue (Lambada)'''\" (both meaning \"Crying [he/she] went away\" in Portuguese and Spanish, respectively), is a song recorded by French-Brazilian pop group [[Kaoma]]. It features guest vocals by [[Brazil]]ian vocalist [[Loalwa Braz]]. It was released as the first single from Kaoma's debut album ''[[Worldbeat (album)|Worldbeat]]''. The video, filmed on Cocos beach in the city of [[Trancoso, Bahia|Trancoso]], in the state of [[Bahia]], Brazil, features the Brazilian child duo [[Chico & Roberta]].\n\nThe song in [[Portuguese language|Portuguese]] is a mix cover of M\u00e1rcia Ferreira's 1986 hit \"Chorando se foi\" (lyrics translated to Portuguese) and the Cuarteto Continental hit \"Llorando se fue\" (first upbeat version of the song introducing the [[accordion]]), released in 1984 through the Peruvian record label INFOPESA and produced by Alberto Maravi;<ref name=\"facebook.com\">{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/photo.php?fbid=156206137774718&set=a.125312210864111.19181.125280644200601&theater|title=Infopesa - Timeline Photos &#124; Facebook|publisher=facebook.com|accessdate=November 30, 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"google\">{{cite book|title=The Latin Beat: The Rhythms And Roots Of Latin Music From Bossa Nova To Salsa And Beyond|author=Morales, E.|publisher=Da Capo Press|isbn=9780786730209|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Lpv25quOSnwC|page=30|accessdate=November 30, 2014}}</ref> both songs were adapted from the 1981 [[Bolivia]]n song [[Llorando se fue]] by [[Los Kjarkas]].\n\nAt the time of release, the song was regarded as the most successful European single in the history of CBS records with sales of 1.8&nbsp;million copies in France and more than 4&nbsp;million across Europe. It is one of the [[List of best-selling singles|greatest-selling singles of all time]], having sold more than 5 million copies worldwide.<ref>{{cite news|title=The 10 best-selling singles since the mid-\u201950s are:|newspaper= [[Coeur d'Alene Press]] |date= 23 February 2017 |accessdate= 19 December 2017 |url=http://www.cdapress.com/article/20170223/ARTICLE/170229764}}</ref>\n\n==Song information==\nThe lyrics and music of Kaoma's \"Chorando se foi (Lambada)\" are an unauthorized translation of the song \"[[Llorando se fue]]\", originally composed, performed  and recorded by the [[Bolivia]]n [[Andean music|Andean pop]] group [[Los Kjarkas]] in 1981.<ref name=\"elpais.com\">{{cite web|title=Kjarkas: La lambada es un dolor|first= Nacho|last= Saenz de Tejada|work=El Pais |url=http://www.elpais.com/articulo/cultura/Kjarkas/lambada/dolor/elpepicul/19900529elpepicul_17/Tes/|date=May 29, 1990|accessdate= February 22, 2010}}</ref><ref>Album: ''Canto A La Mujer De Mi Pueblo'', Los Kjarkas, 1981.</ref> The song's lyrics and music had been lawfully registered in 1985 by the founding members of Los Kjarkas \u2013 Gonzalo and Ulises Hermosa \u2013 in Germany's Music and Authors Society (GEMA). The unauthorized copy by Kaoma led to a successful 1990 lawsuit by Los Kjarkas against Kaoma's producer Jean-Claude Bonaventure.<ref name=\"elpais.com\"/>\n\nAccording to Gonzalo Hermosa, Los Kjarkas had based \"Llorando se fue\" on a small, nostalgic [[Andean music|Andean]] melody. Their song was written in a sad and slow [[Afro-Bolivian Saya]] rhythm.<ref>{{cite web|title=El \u00e9xito detr\u00e1s de la canci\u00f3n m\u00e1s famosa de Bolivia: Llorando se fue|url=http://www.fmbolivia.net/noticia21411-el-xito-detrs-de-la-cancin-ms-famosa-de-bolivia-llorando-se-fue.html|publisher=Radio FMBolivia.net|accessdate=April 22, 2011}}</ref>\n\nPrior to Kaoma's 1989 release of the song, several covers of \"Llorando se fue\" had been released as dance tracks:\n*1984 \u2013 Cuarteto Continental from the LP ''Fiesta de Cumbias''<ref>[https://www.facebook.com/discography/album.php?aid=128747957163602]{{dead link|date=July 2016}}</ref>\n*1984 \u2013 Armonia 10 from the LP ''El Chinchorro, Vol. 2''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://armonia10depiura.blogspot.com/p/biografia.html |title=Armonia 10 * Rosita Producciones PERU: BIOGRAFIA |publisher=Armonia10depiura.blogspot.com |date= |accessdate=July 14, 2016}}</ref><ref>[https://www.facebook.com/discography/album.php?aid=116702868353163]{{dead link|date=July 2016}}</ref>\n*1984 \u2013 Sexteto Internacional\n*1984 \u2013 Tropical Ping\u00fcino<ref name=\"elsiglodetorreon\">{{cite web|url=http://www.elsiglodetorreon.com.mx/noticia/90738.tropical-ping%C3%BCino-esta-de-regreso.html|author=El Siglo de Torre\u00f3n|publisher=elsiglodetorreon.com.mx|title=Tropical Ping\u00fcino est\u00e1 de regreso|accessdate=November 10, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=laguloko |url=http://lamusicademicomarcalagunera.blogspot.com/2009/05/tropical-pinguino-2008-20-exitos-1984.html |title=Musica Lagunera Y Coahuilense: Tropical Ping\u00fcino - 2008 - 20 \u00c9xitos (1984-1990) |publisher=Lamusicademicomarcalagunera.blogspot.com |date= |accessdate=July 14, 2016}}</ref>\n*1984 \u2013 [[Wilkins V\u00e9lez|Wilkins]] from the album ''Una Historia Importante \u2013 15 Grandes Exitos''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/dp/B000QQ5G9I |title=Lambada (Llorando Se Fue): Wilkins: MP3 Downloads |publisher=Amazon.com |date= |accessdate=July 14, 2016}}</ref>\n*1985 \u2013 Juan \"Coraz\u00f3n\" Ram\u00f3n from the album ''Cada D\u00eda Mejor''<ref name=\"masoportunidades\">{{cite web|url=http://www.masoportunidades.com.ar/aviso/5695118-album-de-juan-ramon-cada-dia-mejor-microfon-se-60301-1985-disponible-en-capital-federal |archive-url=https://archive.today/20120907062209/http://www.masoportunidades.com.ar/aviso/5695118-album-de-juan-ramon-cada-dia-mejor-microfon-se-60301-1985-disponible-en-capital-federal |url-status=dead |archive-date=September 7, 2012 |publisher=masoportunidades.com.ar |title=Compr\u00e1 y vend\u00e9 por Internet - MasOportunidades |accessdate=November 10, 2016 }}</ref>\n*1985 \u2013 Don Medardo y sus Player from the album ''Lo Mejor del A\u00f1o, Vol.4''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.universotropical.com/albums/don_medardo/1985-lo_mejor_del_ano-vol4.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2011-05-06 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111206055629/http://www.universotropical.com/albums/don_medardo/1985-lo_mejor_del_ano-vol4.html |archivedate=December 6, 2011 |df=mdy }}</ref>\n*1985 \u2013 Vico y su Grupo Karicia from the LP ''Voz y sentimiento''<ref name=\"multiply\">{{cite web|url=http://vicokaricia.multiply.com/reviews/item/2/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110901055845/http://vicokaricia.multiply.com/reviews/item/2 |url-status=usurped |archive-date=September 1, 2011 |title=Pagina Web Internacional de Victor Carrasco Tineo El Popular Rey Vico y Su Grupo Karicia del Peru Para Todo El Mundo |accessdate=November 10, 2016 |language=es}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Hace 1 a\u00f1o. |url=http://lacumbiademisviejos.blogspot.com/2009/05/vico-y-su-grupo-karicia-voz-y.html |title=La Cumbia de mis Viejos: Vico y su Grupo Karicia - Voz y sentimiento |publisher=Lacumbiademisviejos.blogspot.com |date=February 26, 2004 |accessdate=July 14, 2016}}</ref>\n*1986 \u2013 M\u00e1rcia Ferreira<ref name=marciaf>[http://www.marciaferreira.com.br/ M\u00e1rcia Ferreira Official site] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110706153412/http://www.marciaferreira.com.br/ |date=July 6, 2011 }} Biography. marciaferreira.com.br</ref><ref>{{cite book|author=McGowan, Chris and Ricardo Pessanha|title=The Brazilian sound: samba, bossa nova, and the popular music of Brazil|page=156}}</ref><ref>{{cite AV media|people=Ferreira, M\u00e1rcia|year=1986|title=M\u00e1rcia Ferreira|medium=LP|publisher=Continental|url=https://immub.org/album/marcia-ferreira-1|id=1.77.405.010}}</ref>\n*1986 \u2013 Los Graduados from the album ''Flor de un d\u00eda''<ref name=\"losgraduados\">{{cite web|url=http://www.losgraduados.com.uy/Discografia.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110817030015/http://losgraduados.com.uy/Discografia.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=August 17, 2011 |title=Los Graduados |accessdate=November 10, 2016 }}</ref>\n*1986 \u2013 [[Pastor L\u00f3pez]] from the album ''Cumbia Universal''<ref>[https://www.discogs.com/Pastor-L\u00f3pez-Cumbia-Universal/release/5156460 Pastor Lopez \u2013 Cumbia Universal (LP-40023)] discogs.com</ref><ref>[https://www.elsurco.ec/app/disco-vinilo/pastor-lopez-cumbia-universal/ Pastor Lopez \u2013 Cumbia Universal (LP-40023)] elsurco.ec</ref>\n*1987 \u2013 Sonora Andacollo from the album ''Norte Tropical \u2013 Lambada''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.universotropical.com/albums/sonora_andacollo/1987-norte_tropical-lambada.html |title=Sonora Andacollo (1987) Norte Tropical - Lambada |publisher=universotropical.com |accessdate=July 14, 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160813224821/http://www.universotropical.com/albums/sonora_andacollo/1987-norte_tropical-lambada.html |archivedate=August 13, 2016 }}</ref>\n*1988 \u2013 [[Los Hermanos Rosario]] from the album ''Otra Vez''<ref>[http://www.elsoldelasamericas.com/columnistas/el-comunitario/1444-los-hermanosd-rosario-discografia.html]{{dead link|date=July 2016}}</ref>\n*1988 \u2013 Ana Morena from the compilation album ''Baila Baila Baila, Vol. 2''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.artistdirect.com/nad/store/artist/album/0,,47171,00.html |title=Baila Baila Baila Vol 2 @ARTISTdirect |publisher=Artistdirect.com |date= |accessdate=July 14, 2016}}</ref><ref>[http://www.universotropical.com/albums/sonora_jr_l_palacios/1988-vol3-que_siga_la_cumbia.html]{{dead link|date=July 2016}}</ref>\n*1988 \u2013 Tropicalismo Apache from the album ''Exitos Quemantes''\n*1989 \u2013 Los Flamers from the album ''Gran Reventon Gran, Vol. 5''<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.billboard.com/artist/los-flamers/discography/compilations/24869?sort=date&page=3#/artist/los-flamers/discography/compilations/24869?sort=date&page=3 |title=Artists - Top Music Artists and Bands - Page 1 |magazine=Billboard |accessdate=July 14, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://music.msn.com/music/album/los-flamers/gran-reventon-gran-vol-5/ |title=News, reviews, interviews and more for top artists and albums \u2013 MSN Music |publisher=Music.msn.com |date=May 17, 2016 |accessdate=July 14, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 1984 an upbeat version of the song introducing the accordion was released by the Peruvian group Cuarteto Continental, whose  arrangements (produced by Alberto Maravi) were later copied by Kaoma.<ref name=\"facebook.com\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://infopesa.blogspot.com/2010/10/cuarteto-continental-fiesta-de-cumbias.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2011-04-03 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20120714113452/http://infopesa.blogspot.com/2010/10/cuarteto-continental-fiesta-de-cumbias.html |archivedate=July 14, 2012 |df=mdy }}</ref> The first Portuguese translation and recording of \"Llorando se fue\" \u2013 as \"Chorando se foi\" \u2013 was released by [[Brazil]]ian singer Ferreira in 1986 under her third album.<ref name=marciaf />\n\nNowadays the song is credited to the Hermosa brothers (authors), Alberto Maravi, M\u00e1rcia Ferreira and Jos\u00e9 Ari.<ref name=\"duende-music\">{{cite web|url=http://www.duende-music.co.uk/recordings_page.html |title=Recordings Page |publisher=duende-music.co.uk |accessdate=November 30, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120322065403/http://www.duende-music.co.uk/recordings_page.html |archivedate=March 22, 2012 }}</ref>\n\nIn France, the song was used in a television advertisement for [[Orangina]].<ref>{{cite book |first=Alex P. |last=King |title=Hit-parade \u2013 20 ans de tubes |publisher=Pascal |year=2004 |place=Paris |page=349 |language=French |isbn=2-35019-009-9}}</ref>\n\n==Chart performance==\nThe single became a worldwide [[summer hit]], selling over 5&nbsp;million copies in 1989<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1990/07/04/arts/brazilian-wonder-turns-out-bolivian.html?scp=9&sq=%22lambada%22+million&st=nyt|title=Brazilian Wonder Turns Out Bolivian|work=[[The New York Times]]|publisher=[[The New York Times Company]]|date=July 4, 1990 |accessdate=February 2, 2012|first=Riding|last=Alan}}</ref> and was part of the [[Lambada]] [[dance craze]]. It reached number one on eleven different charts, as well as number four on both the [[UK Singles Chart]] and [[Irish Singles Chart]], number five on the Australia [[ARIA Charts|ARIA Singles Chart]], and in 1990<ref name=\"song-database\">{{cite web|url=http://www.song-database.com/chhist.php?sid=21145&from=spu&type=ht|title=Song://Database Sign-In|publisher=song-database.com|accessdate=November 30, 2014}}</ref> it hit number 46 on the U.S. ''Billboard'' [[Billboard Hot 100|Hot 100]], becoming one of the best known Brazilian songs of all time.\n\n\"Chorando Se Foi (Lambada)\" was the 37th best-selling single of the United Kingdom during 1989. In France, where it topped the chart for 12 weeks and sold almost two million copies, the single was the number-one on the year-end list.\n\n==Music video==\nThe music video of the song was filmed on stage on [[Illa de Tagomago|Tago Mago Island]] in the Mediterranean Sea and on Cocos Beach in the city of [[Trancoso, Bahia|Trancoso]], Bahia, Brazil. It features the Brazilian child duo [[Chico & Roberta]] as love interests. Roberta's father does not want her to hang out with Chico, but [[Loalwa Braz|Loalwa]] mends the situation among the three.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lambada.cc/ |title=Lambada Records |publisher=Lambada.cc |date= |accessdate=July 14, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Motion picture==\nThe song was licensed by producer [[Richard L. Albert]] for his film ''[[The Forbidden Dance]]'' after he saw Kaoma perform in a Los Angeles club. Not only was Kaoma's rendition used, but the song was also performed by [[Kid Creole and the Coconuts]] on screen with English lyrics.\n\n==Cover versions, samples and mentions==\nOwing to its huge success outside Brazil, \"Chorando Se Foi (Lambada)\" was also recorded by Kaoma in English and Spanish.\n\nThe song \"Sochna Kya\" from the 1990 [[Hindi]] film [[Ghayal (1990 film)|Ghayal]] copies the melody of \"Chorando Se Foi (Lambada).\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chakpak.com/discussion/well-known-%22indpired%22-numbers-in-hindi-cinema/180|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20120724142509/http://www.chakpak.com/discussion/well-known-%22indpired%22-numbers-in-hindi-cinema/180|url-status=dead|title=Well known \"indpired\" numbers in Hindi |date=July 24, 2012|archivedate=July 24, 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe Japanese singer [[Akemi Ishii]] released a cover version in Japanese on March 21, 1990. It peaked at number 16 on the [[Oricon]] charts and was re-recorded in 2011.\n\nIn France, the song was covered by another group, [[Carioca]], which peaked only at number 22 on September 9, 1989 and remained on the chart for nine weeks.<ref>{{cite web|author=Steffen Hung |url=http://lescharts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=Carioca&titel=Lambada&cat=s |title=Carioca - Lambada |publisher=lescharts.com |date= |accessdate=July 14, 2016}}</ref> It was also covered, around that time, by other Brazilian singers, such as [[Faf\u00e1 de Bel\u00e9m]], whose 1985 album ''Aprendizes da Esperan\u00e7a'' was an early exponent of the lambada rhythm. Also in 1989, a cover by Regina appeared on Chico Mend\u00e9s' LP ''Lambada Tropical'' and on the compilation albums ''Max Mix 9''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://discomixes.ru/ppfiles/maxmix9.htm |title=Max Mix 9 |publisher=Discomixes.ru |date= |accessdate=July 14, 2016}}</ref> and ''Hits '89''.<ref>{{cite web|author=Steffen Hung |url=https://charts.nz/showitem.asp?interpret=Chico+Mendes+feat%2E+Regina&titel=La+Lambada&cat=s |title=Chico Mendes feat. Regina - La Lambada |publisher=charts.nz |date= |accessdate=July 14, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"samplerinfos\">{{cite web|url=http://covers.samplerinfos.de/show_tracklisting.php?id=03710110|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110814010615/http://covers.samplerinfos.de/show_tracklisting.php?id=03710110|url-status=dead|archive-date=August 14, 2011|title=Hits 89 - Die internationalen Superhits|accessdate=November 10, 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe experimental band [[Sun City Girls]] recorded a [[freak folk]] cover entitled \"The Shining Path\" on their 1990 LP, ''[[Torch of the Mystics]]''.\n\nThe Turkish singer Cengiz Co\u015fkuner recorded a version of the song with lyrics written by \u00dclk\u00fc Aker. It was found in his ''Seni Gidi Seni & Kapris Yapma'' album, which was released in 1990.<ref>http://2.bp.blogspot.com/_r-24OVnivxI/TTnyjg3X6yI/AAAAAAAAAfU/ooWXC5yuZek/s320/fuattan_korsan_kaset.jpg</ref>\n\nThe Turkish singer R\u00fcya \u00c7a\u011fla wrote and recorded a version of the song. It was the title track of her ''Lambada'' album, released in 1990.<ref name=\"diskotek\">{{cite web|url=http://www.diskotek.info/Artist/GetCover?RecordId=17910 |publisher=diskotek.info |title=www.diskotek.info/Artist/GetCover?RecordId=17910 |accessdate=November 10, 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160309183549/http://www.diskotek.info/Artist/GetCover?RecordId=17910 |archivedate=March 9, 2016 }}</ref>\n\nIvete Sangalo recorded a live version of the song as a bonus track for her 2005 album ''As Super Novas''. It was released in November 2005 as the third single from the album. She also recorded the song on [[Multishow ao Vivo: Ivete no Maracan\u00e3|her second live album]].\n\nThe British [[girl group]] [[Spice Girls]] mention \"Lambada\" - either the song or the dance - in their 1997 hit single \"[[Spice Up Your Life]]\". They further used an excerpt from the song in a remix version as the final song on their 2007\u20132008 reunion tour [[Return of the Spice Girls]].\n\nDanish [[Eurodance]] group Fem@le released a cover version of the song in 2000.<ref>{{cite AV media notes |title=Lambada  |others=Fem@le |date=2000 |type=liner notes |publisher=Scoop Records |id=SCOOP 66017-4}}</ref>\n\nThe Danish [[electronic dance music]] act [[Aycan]] released a remixed cover of this song in 2006.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.discogs.com/Aycan-Lambada/master/191336 |title=Aycan - Lambada at Discogs |publisher=Discogs.com |date= |accessdate=July 14, 2016}}</ref>\n\n[[Mariana Seoane]] recorded the song in Spanish on her 2007 album ''Est\u00e1 de Fiesta... Atr\u00e9vete!!''.<ref>[http://m.billboard.com/song/mariana/llorando-se-fue/10667282#/song/mariana/llorando-se-fue/10667282]{{dead link|date=July 2016}}</ref>\n\n[[Seikima-II]] frontman [[Demon Kakka]] recorded the song in Japanese/Spanish on his 2008 album ''GIRLS' ROCK Hakurai''.<ref name=\"demon-kogure\">{{cite web|url=http://www.demon-kogure.jp/works/girls_rock_hakurai.html|title=H.E. DEMON KOGURE'S OFFICIAL WEBSITE|publisher=demon-kogure.jp|accessdate=November 30, 2014}}</ref>\n\nAlso a Russian song that uses the famous sample sung by Svetylana Svetykova (\u0421\u0432\u0435\u0442\u043b\u0430\u043d\u0430 \u0421\u0432\u0435\u0442\u0438\u043a\u043e\u0432\u0430) Ft. Salsa Boys called \"Lambada\".\n\nIn 2010, the Reggaeton singer [[Don Omar]] recorded a Spanish version of the song titled \"[[Taboo (Don Omar song)|Taboo]]\" included on his album ''[[Don Omar Presents: Meet the Orphans|Meet the Orphans]]''.\n\n[[Jennifer Lopez]]'s single \"[[On the Floor]]\" samples Kaoma's Lambada or its original by [[Los Kjarkas]].<ref name=\"Levine\">{{cite web |url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/music/singlesreviews/a304082/jennifer-lopez-ft-pitbull-on-the-floor.html |title=Single Review \u2013 Jennifer Lopez feat. Pitbull \"On the Floor\" |publisher=[[Digital Spy]]. ([[Hachette Filipacchi M\u00e9dias|Hachette Filipacchi UK]]) |last=Levine |first=Nick |date=February 16, 2011 |accessdate=February 16, 2011}}</ref> The single hit #3 on [[Billboard Hot 100]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Cobo|first1=Leila|title=20 years later, \"Lambada\" still inspiring hits|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-lambada-idUSTRE7530GO20110604|accessdate=January 5, 2018|work=Reuters|date=June 4, 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn 2011, the Mexican singer [[Anah\u00ed]] recorded a live version of the song as a bonus track for her ''[[Mi Delirio World Tour#Go Any Go|MDWT Go Any Go]]'' tour of Brazil and Mexico.\n\nA variation of the song appears in the game ''[[Parasol Stars]]'' as the game's Boss Music.\n\nThe song's melody is also used as a theme for ice cream trucks.\n\nThe dance is also mentioned on season 1 episode 10 of ''The French Prince of Bel Air'',\n\"Kiss My Butler\" (5 Nov. 1990) when Geoffrey is accused of doing \"...the forbidden dance.\"\n\nThere is a [[Sinhalese language|Sinhalese]] cover version named \"Adare Oba Ma Hata\" by Mariazelle Gunathilake and Piyal Perera.\n\nTwo Persian DJs, Amir Acid and Mehran created a Farsi version of this song, with the original name.\n\nArezo Nikbin, an Afghan artist created an Afghan version of the song with the name \"\u062f\u0644 \u0628\u0647 \u062f\u0644\u0628\u0631 \u0645\u06cc\u200c\u0631\u0633\u062f \u062c\u0627\u0646\u0645\".\n\n==Formats and track listings==\n; 7\" single CBS\n# \"Lambada\" \u2013 3:28\n# \"Lambada\" (instrumental) \u2013 3:48\n\n# \"Lambada\" (Dj Petro Panayoti aka Mixmaster remix) 1989 \u2013 4:50\n\n; 12\" maxi CBS\n# \"Lambada\" (extended version) \u2013 6:44\n# \"Lambada\" (instrumental version) \u2013 3:48\n# \"Lambada\" (Dj Stigma-Berveni remix) \u2013 3:55\n\n# \"Lambada\" (Dj Petro Panayoti Club Remix)2019 \u2013 6:00\n\n==Charts and certifications==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n\n===Weekly charts===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!Chart (1988-89)\n!Peak<br>position\n|-\n{{Singlechart|Australia|5|artist=Kaoma|song=Lambada}}\n|-\n{{Singlechart|Austria|1|artist=Kaoma|song=Lambada}}\n|-\n{{Singlechart|Flanders|1|artist=Kaoma|song=Lambada}}\n|-\n|Canada Dance ([[RPM (magazine)|RPM]])<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/rpm/028020-119.01-e.php?&file_num=nlc008388.9228&type=1&interval=20&PHPSESSID=1ggf3hup0j23maqhpi8m51r7h6 |title=Item Display - RPM - Library and Archives Canada |publisher=Collectionscanada.gc.ca |date= |accessdate=July 14, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160817034532/http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/rpm/028020-119.01-e.php?&file_num=nlc008388.9228&type=1&interval=20&PHPSESSID=1ggf3hup0j23maqhpi8m51r7h6 |archive-date=August 17, 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|3\n|-\n|Canada ([[RPM (magazine)|RPM]])<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/rpm/028020-119.01-e.php?&file_num=nlc008388.9018&type=1&interval=20&PHPSESSID=b7h7no014r6obmscu0is6fgg45 |title=Item Display - RPM - Library and Archives Canada |publisher=Collectionscanada.gc.ca |accessdate=July 14, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160817062146/http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/rpm/028020-119.01-e.php?&file_num=nlc008388.9018&type=1&interval=20&PHPSESSID=b7h7no014r6obmscu0is6fgg45 |archive-date=August 17, 2016 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|78\n|-\n|Denmark ([[IFPI Denmark|IFPI]])<ref>Danish Singles Chart 8 December 1989</ref