        = \n| blank_info_sec2        = \n| website                = http://lakhisarai.bih.nic.in/\n}}\n'''Lakhisarai district''' is one of the thirty-eight [[Districts of Bihar|districts]] of [[Bihar]] [[States and territories of India|state]], [[India]], and [[Lakhisarai]] town is the administrative headquarters of this district. Lakhisarai district is a part of [[Munger Division]]. The district occupies an area of 1228&nbsp;km<sup>2</sup>. \n==History==\nOn 3 July 1994 this district was carved out from [[Munger district]], which comprised the erstwhile Lakhisarai sub-division of the undivided district.\n\n==Geography==\nLakhisarai district occupies an area of {{convert|1228|km2|sqmi}},<ref name='Reference Annual'>{{cite book | last1 = Srivastava, Dayawanti et al. (ed.) | title = India 2010: A Reference Annual | chapter = States and Union Territories: Bihar: Government | edition = 54th | publisher = Additional Director General, Publications Division, [[Ministry of Information and Broadcasting (India)]], [[Government of India]] | year = 2010 | location = New Delhi, India | pages = 1118\u20131119 | isbn = 978-81-230-1617-7}}</ref>\n\n==Economy==\nIn 2006 the [[Ministry of Panchayati Raj]] named Lakhisarai one of the country's 250 [[Poverty in India|districts]] (out of a total of [[Districts of India|640]]).<ref name=brgf/>  It is one of the 36 districts in Bihar currently receiving funds from the Backward Regions Grant Fund Programme (BRGF).<ref name=brgf>{{cite web|author=Ministry of Panchayati Raj |date=September 8, 2009 |title=A Note on the Backward Regions Grant Fund Programme |publisher=National Institute of Rural Development. |url=http://www.nird.org.in/brgf/doc/brgf_BackgroundNote.pdf |accessdate=September 27, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120405033402/http://www.nird.org.in/brgf/doc/brgf_BackgroundNote.pdf |archivedate=April 5, 2012 }}</ref>\n\nIndustrial background; there are various fertilizer and pesticide factories in the district, including Bihar Mineral Industries. The market for fabrics is also flourishing in the district with lots of old and new shops, there are many factories like Sindur, which play a good role in increasing GDP of India.\n[[National Thermal Power Corporation Limited]] and Bihar State Power Generation Company Ltd has signed Memorandum of Understanding to set up 1320MW thermal power plant in Kajra.<ref>{{https://wap.business-standard.com/article-amp/companies/ntpc-to-set-up-1-320-mw-power-plant-in-bihar-114022300260_1.html}}</ref>\n\n==Divisions==\n{{unreferenced section|date=June 2013}}\nThe district consists only one sub-division Lakhisarai, which is divided into Seven developmental [[Community development block in India|block]]s, namely, Lakhisarai, [[Surajgarha]], Barahiya, Halsi, Pipariya, Ramgarh Chowk and Chanan. \n\nThe district headquarters Lakhisarai is a city with mixed population, the majority being the upper-caste (Bhumihaar-Brahmins) people. Still under the process of development, the city has one newly constructed PCC road and a bypass under construction. The Law and Order as well as development process is taking place after [[Nitish Kumar]] Govt came into Power. Also, Piribazar, Chanan police stations are naxal-prone due to their geographical layout. The city well known for its ''sindur'' (vermilion) production.\n\n==Religion==\nLakhisarai is also famous for Indradameshwar Ashokdham temple, Bhagvati sthan temple at Abhaipur, Abhaynath temple at the hills beside Abhaipur Village, Maharani temple at Barahiya, Shree Shesh Nag Temple at Babhangawan, Baba Govind temple at Mano-Rampur Rameshavar Dham singarpur and for Shringirishi mountains and Surya Mandir at Pokhrama village in Alinagar Panchyat. This area is to be developed for Gautam Budha visits and related relics.\n\n==Demographics==\n{{historical populations|11=1901|12=2,29,288|13=1911|14=2,36,466|15=1921|16=2,24,854|17=1931|18=2,53,195|19=1941|20=2,86,239|21=1951|22=3,16,343|23=1961|24=3,52,448|25=1971|26=4,39,256|27=1981|28=5,33,840|29=1991|30=6,46,395|31=2001|32=8,02,225|33=2011|34=10,00,912|percentages=pagr|footnote=source:<ref>[http://www.censusindia.gov.in/2011census/PCA/A2_Data_Table.html Decadal Variation In Population Since 1901]</ref>|align=right}}{{bar box\n|title=Religions in Lakhisarai District\n|titlebar=#Fcd116\n|left1=Religion\n|right1=Percent\n|float=right\n|bars=\n{{bar percent|[[Hindus]]|orange|95.55}}\n{{bar percent|[[Muslims]]|green|4.08}}\n{{bar percent|Not Stated|black|0.28}}\n{{bar percent|Christian|blue|0.05}}\n{{bar percent|Sikh|olive|0.01}}\n{{bar percent|Buddhist|yellow|0.01}}\n{{bar percent|Jain|brown|0.01}}\n{{bar percent|Others|grey|0.01}}\n}}\nAccording to the [[2011 census of India|2011 census]] Lakhisarai district has a [[Demographics of India|population]] of 1,000,912,<ref name=districtcensus>{{cite web |  title = District Census 2011 | year = 2011 | publisher = Census2011.co.in}}</ref>  This gives it a ranking of 445th in India (out of a total of [[Districts of India|640]]).<ref name=districtcensus/> The district has a population density of {{convert| 815 |PD/sqkm|PD/sqmi}} .<ref name=districtcensus/> Its [[Family planning in India|population growth rate]] over the decade 2001-2011 was  24.74%.<ref name=districtcensus/> Lakhisarai has a [[sex ratio]] of 900 [[Women in India|females]] for every 1000 males,<ref name=districtcensus/> and a [[Literacy in India|literacy rate]] of 64.95%.<ref name=districtcensus/>\n\nAt the time of the [[2011 Census of India]], 97.28% of the population in the district spoke [[Hindi]], 1.73% [[Urdu]] and 0.52% [[Maithili language|Maithili]] as their first language.<ref>[http://www.censusindia.gov.in/2011census/C-16.html 2011 Census of India, Population By Mother Tongue]</ref>\n\n===Notable towns===\n<!---\u2666\u2666\u2666 Only add a town to this list if it already has its own article on the English Wikipedia \u2666\u2666\u2666---> \n<!---\u2666\u2666\u2666 Please keep the list in alphabetical order \u2666\u2666\u2666---> \n*[[Barahiya]]\n*[[Jaitpur]]\n*[[Lakhisarai]]\n\n===Notable villages===\n<!---\u2666\u2666\u2666 Only add a village to this list if it already has its own article on the English Wikipedia \u2666\u2666\u2666---> \n<!---\u2666\u2666\u2666 Please keep the list in alphabetical order \u2666\u2666\u2666---> \n*[[Babhangawan]]\n*[[Balgudar]]\n*[[Bhaluee]]\n*[[Maheshpur, Lakhisarai district|Maheshpur]]\n*[[Nijai]]\n*[[Pokhrama]]\n*[[Sabikpur, Lakhisarai|Sabikpur]]\n*[[Siswan]]\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110430231941/http://www.allaboutbihar.com/districts/lakhisarai/index.php Lakhisarai Information Portal]\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n{{Geographic location\n|Centre    = Lakhisarai district\n|North     = [[Begusarai district]]\n|Northeast = \n|East      = [[Munger district]]\n|Southeast = \n|South     = [[Jamui district]]\n|Southwest = [[Sheikhpura district]]\n|West      = [[Nalanda district]]\n|Northwest = [[Patna district]]\n}}\n\n{{Districts of Bihar}}\n{{Munger Division}}\n{{Munger Division topics}}\n\n{{coord|25|10|12|N|86|05|24|E|region:IN-BR_type:adm2nd_source:kolossus-nowiki|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Munger division]]\n[[Category:Districts of Bihar]]\n[[Category:Lakhisarai district| ]]\n[[Category:1994 establishments in India]]\n[[Category:Districts of India]]\n", "text_old": "{{About|the district|its eponymous headquarters|Lakhisarai}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n| name                   = Lakhisarai district\n| settlement_type        = [[Districts of Bihar|District of Bihar]]\n| total_type             = Total\n| native_name            = \n| image_map              = Bihar district location map Lakhisarai.svg\n| map_caption            = Location of Lakhisarai district in Bihar\n| coordinates            = \n| coor_pinpoint          = Lakhisarai\n| subdivision_type       = Country\n| subdivision_name       = [[India]]\n| subdivision_type1      = [[States and union territories of India|State]]\n| subdivision_name1      = [[Bihar]]\n| subdivision_type2      = [[Administrative divisions of India|Division]]\n| subdivision_name2      = [[Munger division|Munger]]\n| established_title      = Established\n| established_date       = \n| seat_type              = Headquarters\n| seat                   = [[Lakhisarai]]\n| parts_type             = [[Tehsils of India|Tehsils]]\n| parts_style            = para\n| p1                     = \n| area_total_km2         = 1228\n| area_footnotes         = \n| population_as_of       = 2011\n| population_total       = 1,000,912\n| population_footnotes   = \n| population_urban       = \n| population_density_km2 = auto\n| demographics_type1     = Demographics\n| demographics1_title1   = [[Literacy in India|Literacy]]\n| demographics1_info1    = 64.95 per cent\n| demographics1_title2   = Sex ratio\n| demographics1_info2    = 900\n| leader_title           = \n| leader_name            = \n| leader_title1          = [[Lok Sabha|Lok Sabha constituencies]]\n| leader_name1           = [[Munger (Lok Sabha constituency)|Munger]]\n| leader_title2          = \n| leader_name2           = \n| timezone1              = [[Indian Standard Time|IST]]\n| utc_offset1            = +05:30\n| registration_plate     = \n| blank_name_sec1        = \n| blank_info_sec1        = \n| blank_name_sec2        = \n| blank_info_sec2        = \n| website                = http://lakhisarai.bih.nic.in/\n}}\n'''Lakhisarai district''' is one of the thirty-eight [[Districts of Bihar|districts]] of [[Bihar]] [[States and territories of India|state]], [[India]], and [[Lakhisarai]] town is the administrative headquarters of this district. Lakhisarai district is a part of [[Munger Division]]. The district occupies an area of 1228&nbsp;km<sup>2</sup>. \n==History==\nOn 3 July 1994 this district was carved out from [[Munger district]], which comprised the erstwhile Lakhisarai sub-division of the undivided district.\n\n==Geography==\nLakhisarai district occupies an area of {{convert|1228|km2|sqmi}},<ref name='Reference Annual'>{{cite book | last1 = Srivastava, Dayawanti et al. (ed.) | title = India 2010: A Reference Annual | chapter = States and Union Territories: Bihar: Government | edition = 54th | publisher = Additional Director General, Publications Division, [[Ministry of Information and Broadcasting (India)]], [[Government of India]] | year = 2010 | location = New Delhi, India | pages = 1118\u20131119 | isbn = 978-81-230-1617-7}}</ref>\n\n==Economy==\nIn 2006 the [[Ministry of Panchayati Raj]] named Lakhisarai one of the country's 250 [[Poverty in India|districts]] (out of a total of [[Districts of India|640]]).<ref name=brgf/>  It is one of the 36 districts in Bihar currently receiving funds from the Backward Regions Grant Fund Programme (BRGF).<ref name=brgf>{{cite web|author=Ministry of Panchayati Raj |date=September 8, 2009 |title=A Note on the Backward Regions Grant Fund Programme |publisher=National Institute of Rural Development. |url=http://www.nird.org.in/brgf/doc/brgf_BackgroundNote.pdf |accessdate=September 27, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120405033402/http://www.nird.org.in/brgf/doc/brgf_BackgroundNote.pdf |archivedate=April 5, 2012 }}</ref>\n\nIndustrial background; there are various fertilizer and pesticide factories in the district, including Bihar Mineral Industries. The market for fabrics is also flourishing in the district with lots of old and new shops, there are many factories like Sindur, which play a good role in increasing GDP of India.\n[[National Thermal Power Corporation Limited]] and Bihar State Power Generation Company Ltd has signed Memorandum of Understanding to set up 1320MW thermal power plant in Kajra<ref>{{https://wap.business-standard.com/article-amp/companies/ntpc-to-set-up-1-320-mw-power-plant-in-bihar-114022300260_1.html}}</ref>.\n\n==Divisions==\n{{unreferenced section|date=June 2013}}\nThe district consists only one sub-division Lakhisarai, which is divided into Seven developmental [[Community development block in India|block]]s, namely, Lakhisarai, [[Surajgarha]], Barahiya, Halsi, Pipariya, Ramgarh Chowk and Chanan. \n\nThe district headquarters Lakhisarai is a city with mixed population, the majority being the upper-caste (Bhumihaar-Brahmins) people. Still under the process of development, the city has one newly constructed PCC road and a bypass under construction. The Law and Order as well as development process is taking place after [[Nitish Kumar]] Govt came into Power. Also, Piribazar, Chanan police stations are naxal-prone due to their geographical layout. The city well known for its ''sindur'' (vermilion) production.\n\n==Religion==\nLakhisarai is also famous for Indradameshwar Ashokdham temple, Bhagvati sthan temple at Abhaipur, Abhaynath temple at the hills beside Abhaipur Village, Maharani temple at Barahiya, Shree Shesh Nag Temple at Babhangawan, Baba Govind temple at Mano-Rampur Rameshavar Dham singarpur and for Shringirishi mountains and Surya Mandir at Pokhrama village in Alinagar Panchyat. This area is to be developed for Gautam Budha visits and related relics.\n\n==Demographics==\n{{historical populations|11=1901|12=2,29,288|13=1911|14=2,36,466|15=1921|16=2,24,854|17=1931|18=2,53,195|19=1941|20=2,86,239|21=1951|22=3,16,343|23=1961|24=3,52,448|25=1971|26=4,39,256|27=1981|28=5,33,840|29=1991|30=6,46,395|31=2001|32=8,02,225|33=2011|34=10,00,912|percentages=pagr|footnote=source:<ref>[http://www.censusindia.gov.in/2011census/PCA/A2_Data_Table.html Decadal Variation In Population Since 1901]</ref>|align=right}}{{bar box\n|title=Religions in Lakhisarai District\n|titlebar=#Fcd116\n|left1=Religion\n|right1=Percent\n|float=right\n|bars=\n{{bar percent|[[Hindus]]|orange|95.55}}\n{{bar percent|[[Muslims]]|green|4.08}}\n{{bar percent|Not Stated|black|0.28}}\n{{bar percent|Christian|blue|0.05}}\n{{bar percent|Sikh|olive|0.01}}\n{{bar percent|Buddhist|yellow|0.01}}\n{{bar percent|Jain|brown|0.01}}\n{{bar percent|Others|grey|0.01}}\n}}\nAccording to the [[2011 census of India|2011 census]] Lakhisarai district has a [[Demographics of India|population]] of 1,000,912,<ref name=districtcensus>{{cite web |  title = District Census 2011 | year = 2011 | publisher = Census2011.co.in}}</ref>  This gives it a ranking of 445th in India (out of a total of [[Districts of India|640]]).<ref name=districtcensus/> The district has a population density of {{convert| 815 |PD/sqkm|PD/sqmi}} .<ref name=districtcensus/> Its [[Family planning in India|population growth rate]] over the decade 2001-2011 was  24.74%.<ref name=districtcensus/> Lakhisarai has a [[sex ratio]] of 900 [[Women in India|females]] for every 1000 males,<ref name=districtcensus/> and a [[Literacy in India|literacy rate]] of 64.95%.<ref name=districtcensus/>\n\nAt the time of the [[2011 Census of India]], 97.28% of the population in the district spoke [[Hindi]], 1.73% [[Urdu]] and 0.52% [[Maithili language|Maithili]] as their first language.<ref>[http://www.censusindia.gov.in/2011census/C-16.html 2011 Census of India, Population By Mother Tongue]</ref>\n\n===Notable towns===\n<!---\u2666\u2666\u2666 Only add a town to this list if it already has its own article on the English Wikipedia \u2666\u2666\u2666---> \n<!---\u2666\u2666\u2666 Please keep the list in alphabetical order \u2666\u2666\u2666---> \n*[[Barahiya]]\n*[[Jaitpur]]\n*[[Lakhisarai]]\n\n===Notable villages===\n<!---\u2666\u2666\u2666 Only add a village to this list if it already has its own article on the English Wikipedia \u2666\u2666\u2666---> \n<!---\u2666\u2666\u2666 Please keep the list in alphabetical order \u2666\u2666\u2666---> \n*[[Babhangawan]]\n*[[Balgudar]]\n*[[Bhaluee]]\n*[[Maheshpur, Lakhisarai district|Maheshpur]]\n*[[Nijai]]\n*[[Pokhrama]]\n*[[Sabikpur, Lakhisarai|Sabikpur]]\n*[[Siswan]]\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110430231941/http://www.allaboutbihar.com/districts/lakhisarai/index.php Lakhisarai Information Portal]\n\n==References==